const ORDINANCES = [
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-6", name:"False Alarm and Service Charges", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Civil fee schedule — not a criminal offense", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 6-6. False alarm and service charges.\n(a)     If false alarm notifications are received for an alarm site, the alarm administrator shall assess the permit holder in control of that alarm site a fee for false alarms emitted from the alarm site in the following amounts:\n(1)   Fifty dollars ($50.00) if the alarm site has had more than three (3), but less than six (6) false burglar alarm notifications in the immediately preceding twelve (12) month period;\n(2)   Seventy-five dollars ($75.00) if the alarm site has had more than five (5), but less than eight\n(8) false burglar alarm notifications in the, immediately preceding twelve (12) month period;\n(3)   One hundred dollars ($100.00) if the alarm site has had eight (8) or more false burglar alarm notifications in the immediately preceding twelve (12) month period;\n(4)   If, within any twelve (12) month period, two (2) false robbery alarm notifications are emitted from an alarm site, the alarm administrator shall assess the permit holder in control of that alarm site a fee for each subsequent false robbery alarm notification emitted from the alarm site. The fee for each false robbery alarm notification under this subsection shall be seventy-five dollars ($75.00);\n(5)   If, within any twelve (12) month period, two (2) false fire alarm notifications are emitted from an alarm site, the alarm administrator shall assess the permit holder in control on that alarm site a fee for each subsequent false fire alarm notification emitted from the alarm site. The fee for each false fire alarm notification under this subsection shall be seventy-five dollars ($75.00);\n(6)   If, within any twelve (12) month period, two (2) false panic alarm notifications are emitted from an alarm site, the alarm administrator shall assess the permit holder in control on that alarm site a fee for each subsequent false panic alarm notification emitted from the alarm site. The fee for each false panic alarm notification under this subsection shall be seventy- five dollars ($75.00); or\n(7)   If, within any twelve (12) month period, two (2) false emergency medical assistance alarm notifications are emitted from an alarm site, the alarm administrator shall assess the permit holder in control of that alarm site a fee for each subsequent false emergency medical assistance alarm notification emitted from the alarm site. The fee for each false medical emergency alarm notification under this subsection shall be seventy-five dollars ($75.00).\n(b)     If the permit holder or responder fails to respond to the scene within thirty (30) minutes to reset the alarm system and provide access to the alarm site, the alarm system may be silenced by authorized city personnel and a fee of fifty dollars ($50.00), in addition to the actual expenses incurred in securing the alarm site, will be charged to the permit holder. All costs of the city in disabling such an alarm system shall be assessed to the permit holder of the alarm site and shall be paid to the city within thirty (30) days after the permit holder has received notice that the costs have been assessed.\n(c)     If a public safety response takes longer than thirty (30) minutes to respond to the alarm dispatch request or cancellation is received by the communication center before the arrival of public safety response personnel to the alarm site, no false alarm fee shall be assessed.\n(d)     A permit holder shall pay a fee assessed under this section within thirty (30) days after receipt of notice that it has been assessed. A failure to pay the fee within thirty (30) days will result in an additional ten percent late fee. Failure of the permit holder to pay the assessed fee and any applicable late fee will result in the permit being revoked.\n(e)     All persons assessed a fee shall have a right to appeal the same using the process set forth in section 6-4 of this chapter. A right to appeal will be included in the notice of the fee.\n(f)     The permit holder will be exempt from any fees charged for a false alarm notification which is later shown to have been in the alarm administrator's sole determination, justified or which was due to a natural or manmade catastrophe or other situation specifically exempted by the director.\n(g)     For the purposes of this chapter, a permit holder shall be considered to be in control of the alarm site for all purposes and at all times, regardless of whether the permit holder is physically present when an alarm is activated and regardless of whether the alarm dispatch is activated by a third person, including but not limited to, another resident of the premises, a family member, a service worker, a guest or an invitee, unless the third party is a trespasser of the alarm site.\n(h)  Alarm permit holders for governmental or public educational sites are exempt from the payment of false alarm fees. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Escalating civil fees assessed against the alarm permit holder for repeated false burglar, robbery, fire, panic, or medical-assistance alarm notifications within a 12-month period, plus a fee for failing to respond within 30 minutes to reset a silenced system. Not a criminal charge — a billed fee with an appeal right.", street:["This is a fee schedule, not an offense — don't write a citation off this section alone.","Fees escalate with repeat false alarms: $50 at 4-5 false burglar alarms in 12 months, $75 at 6-7, $100 at 8+.","Governmental and public educational sites are exempt from false-alarm fees entirely.","No fee applies if a public-safety response takes longer than 30 minutes or cancellation is received before arrival."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-7", name:"Unlawful Reporting of Alarm Signals; Operating Without a Permit", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"(a) unlawful conduct, penalty per § 6-19; (b) misdemeanor, fine up to $250", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 6-7. Unlawful reporting of alarm signals.\n(a)     It is unlawful for an alarm permit holder to report alarm signals through a relaying intermediary that:\n(1)   Does not meet the requirements of this chapter and any rules and regulations promulgated by the alarm administrator; or\n(2)   Is not licensed by the Texas Board of Private Investigators and Private Security Agencies except for a personal emergency response alarm system that does not include a burglar or fire system.\n(b)     A person commits an offense if the person operates any alarm system without having a valid permit for the alarm system and shall be subject to a penalty not to exceed two hundred and fifty dollars ($250.00). Each and every day a violation continues shall constitute a separate offense. This provision shall not apply to a person operating a personal emergency response system that is not part of a combination of a burglar or fire alarm system. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"It is unlawful for a permit holder to route alarm signals through an unlicensed or noncompliant relaying intermediary. Separately, operating any alarm system without a valid permit is a distinct offense, fined up to $250, with each day of continued violation a separate offense.", street:["Two distinct violations live in one section: improper relay reporting (a), and operating without a permit (b) — charge the one that fits the facts.","No permit found for the alarm system at a call is itself chargeable under (b), separate from any false-alarm fee.","Each day without a permit is its own separate offense — document the date you identified the violation."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-8", name:"Offense for Improper Alarm System Operation and Maintenance", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 6-19 general penalty (up to $500)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 6-8. Offense for improper alarm system operation and maintenance. It is unlawful for an alarm user to:\n(1)     Fail to cause an adjustment to be made to the sensory mechanism of his/her alarm system in order to suppress false indications of force so that the alarm system will not be activated by impulses due to:\na.    Transient pressure changes in water pipes;\nb.    Flashes of light;\nc.    Wind noise caused by the rattling or vibrating of doors or windows;\nd.    Vehicular noise adjacent to the installation; or\ne.    Other forces unrelated to actual emergencies.\n(2)     Fail to maintain the premises containing an alarm system in a manner that ensures proper operation of the alarm system;\n(3)     Fail to comply with state law and install only Underwriters Listed CP-01 Alarm Control Panels on all new installations and service replacements;\n(4)     Allow an inside sounder to be installed or operated so that it can be heard outside of the internal premises of the alarm site;\n(5)     Allow an outside sounder be installed at the alarm site;\n(6)     To utilize an automatic voice dialer for purposes of notifying the communications center of an alarm except for panic alarms; or\n(7)     Operate an alarm system that is manually initiated at an arming station without a double action trigger. A double action trigger includes but is not limited to, any of the following:\na.    Simultaneous depression of two (2) buttons, where if either of the buttons have multiple functions, the two (2) buttons are nonadjacent.\nb.    Depression of a single button after lifting the cover that normally protects it if the cover protects only emergency function buttons.\nc. Depression of a single button for at least two (2) seconds. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Unlawful for an alarm user to fail to adjust an alarm's sensory mechanism against known false-trigger sources (water pipe pressure changes, light flashes, wind-rattled doors/windows, vehicle noise), fail to maintain the premises for proper alarm operation, use a non-listed control panel, allow audible sounders heard outside the premises or installed outdoors, use an automatic voice dialer (except for panic alarms), or operate a manually-initiated alarm without a double-action trigger.", street:["This is the 'why does this alarm keep going off' statute — chronic false triggers from foreseeable causes are chargeable maintenance violations, not just fee-generating nuisances.","Outdoor or outside-audible sounders are unlawful outright — note their presence on a call.","No stated in-section penalty; it falls under § 6-19's general chapter penalty (up to $500, each day separate)."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-15", name:"Intentional Activation Unlawful", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 6-19 general penalty (up to $500)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 6-15. Intentional activation unlawful. It shall be unlawful for any person to intentionally activate or cause to be activated any alarm system for other than its intended purpose and with the intent of causing a public safety response. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Unlawful for any person to intentionally activate, or cause to be activated, an alarm system for other than its intended purpose, with the intent of causing a public safety response.", street:["This is the deliberate-false-alarm offense — distinct from a chronic-maintenance false alarm under § 6-8, this requires intent to trigger a response.","Pair with any false-report or hoax-related state charges if the facts support it."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-19", name:"Violations of Chapter; General Penalty", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Misdemeanor, fine up to $500; each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 6-19. Violations of chapter misdemeanor.\n(a)    Any person who violates this chapter shall be, upon conviction, deemed guilty of a misdemeanor and fined an amount not in excess of five hundred dollars ($500.00) unless a lesser maximum amount has been provided for in this chapter. Each day of violation continues shall constitute a separate offense.\n(b)    A person commits an offense if he violates by commission or omission any provision of this chapter that imposes upon him a duty or responsibility.\n(c)  In addition to prohibiting or requiring certain conduct of individuals, it is the intent of this chapter to hold a corporation, partnership, association or other entity criminally responsible for acts or omissions performed by an agent acting on behalf of the corporation, partnership, association, or entity and within the scope of the agent's employment or authority. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"The chapter's catch-all penalty clause: any violation of the Alarm Systems chapter not otherwise graded is a misdemeanor punishable by a fine up to $500, with each day of continuing violation a separate offense. The chapter also reaches corporations, partnerships, and associations criminally through the acts of their agents.", street:["Default to this section's $500 cap when a specific alarm-chapter violation doesn't state its own penalty.","Business entities can be charged directly through an employee or agent's violation within the scope of their duties."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-1", name:"Definitions (Alarm Systems)", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Definitions — reference; not an offense", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 6-1. Definitions. The following definitions shall apply in the interpretation and enforcement of this chapter and shall have the meanings ascribed to them in this section, except where the context clearly indicates a different meaning:\n\nAct of God. An extraordinary interruption by natural causes (such as flood, earthquake, or severe weather) of the usual course of events that experience, foresight, or care cannot reasonably foresee or prevent.\n\nAlarm administrator. A person or persons designated by the chief of police to administer, control, and review false alarm reduction efforts and administer the provisions of this chapter including the alarm administrator's authorized designee.\n\nAlarm company. Any person who is in the business to sell, install, service, or monitor an alarm system located at an alarm site.\n\nAlarm dispatch request. A notification to the communications center that an alarm, whether manual or automatic, has been activated for a particular alarm site.\n\nAlarm permit or permit. A certificate, license, permit, registration, or other form of permission from the alarm administrator that authorizes a person to operate an alarm system at an alarm site.\n\nAlarm site. A single fixed premises or location served by an alarm system or systems that is under the control of one owner or tenant. Each unit if served by a separate alarm system in a multi-unit building or complex shall be considered a separate alarm site and is further defined by the following categories:\n(1) Residential site. A single-family residence and each residential unit of a multifamily unit building which is served by an alarm system.\n(2) Commercial site. Every premises or location where any business activity is regularly conducted and which is served by an alarm system. For any business within the premises that is served by a separate alarm system, shall be considered a separate alarm site.\n(3) Educational site. Every premises or location of a public or private school and their administrative offices.\n(4) Governmental site. Every premises or location of any federal, state, county, or local government office.\n\nAlarm system. A device or system that transmits or relays a signal intended to summon emergency services of the city. Alarm system does not include:\n(1) An alarm installed on a vehicle unless the vehicle is used for habitation at a permanent site;\n(2) An alarm designed to alert only the inhabitants of a premises; nor\n(3) An alarm installed upon premises occupied by the city.\n\nAlarm user. Any person who has contracted for monitoring, repair, installation, or maintenance services from an alarm company for an alarm system, or a person who owns or operates an alarm system that is not monitored, maintained, or repaired under contract with an alarm company.\n\nAlarm user awareness training. In-person or online training conducted for the purpose of educating alarm users about the responsible use, operation, and maintenance of alarm sites and systems and the problems created by false alarms.\n\nArming station. A device that allows control of an alarm system.\n\nANSI standard. The American National Standards Institute, an independent organization that approves standards that have been through an approval process and are accepted as a standard.\n\nAutomatic voice dialer. Any electrical, electronic, mechanical, or other device capable of being programmed to send a prerecorded voice message, when activated, over a telephone line, radio, or other communication system to the communications center requesting dispatch to an alarm site.\n\nBurglar alarm notification. The notification intended to summon the police, which is initiated or triggered manually or by an alarm system designed to respond to a situation characteristic of an unauthorized intrusion.\n\nCancellation. The process where the public safety response is terminated when an alarm company notifies the communications prior to the public safety response arrival at the alarm site.\n\nCommunications center. The City of Frisco public safety response dispatch center.\n\nConversion. The transaction or process by which one alarm company begins monitoring an alarm system previously monitored by another alarm company.\n\nCP-01 ANSI/SIA control panel standard. An alarm control panel that is listed and approved by Underwriters Laboratories as compliant with the standard.\n\nDay(s). Calendar days.\n\nDirector. The chief of police or fire chief of Frisco, or his/her authorized representative.\n\nECV. The ANSI/CSAA CS-V-01 standard for the telephonic verification of intrusion alarms.\n\nEmergency medical assistance alarm. An alarm system which summons emergency medical assistance.\n\nFalse alarm or false alarm notification. An alarm notification to summon a public safety response and there is no evidence of a need for a public safety response.\n\nFalse burglar alarm notification. A burglar alarm notification to the police, and when the responding police officer finds no evidence of unauthorized intrusion or attempted unauthorized intrusion.\n\nFalse emergency medical assistance alarm notification. An emergency medical assistance alarm notification to the communications center and the responding public safety personnel find there is no evidence of a need for medical assistance.\n\nFalse fire alarm notification. A fire alarm notification to the fire department, and the responding fire personnel find no evidence of fire.\n\nFalse panic alarm notification. An emergency alarm notification has been made to the communications center, and the responding public safety personnel find no evidence or circumstances requiring an emergency response.\n\nFalse robbery alarm notification. A robbery alarm notification to the police, and the responding police officer finds no evidence of a robbery.\n\nFire alarm notification. A notification to summon the fire department initiated or triggered by smoke or fire, fire sprinkler activation or other situations that are characteristic of a fire.\n\nLate fee. The fee charged for failing to pay the original fee owed for a false alarm, permit renewal fee, or other allowable fee that is not paid on time. The late fee is in addition to the amount originally owed.\n\nPanic alarm notification. Is an emergency alarm notification that is manually triggered and relayed to the communications center for the purpose of summoning a public safety response.\n\nPermit holder. A person issued an alarm permit.\n\nPerson. An individual, corporation, partnership, association, organization or other entity.\n\nPublic safety response. A response by City of Frisco police, fire, and/or emergency medical services personnel.\n\nResponder. An individual capable of reaching the alarm site within thirty (30) minutes and has access to the alarm site, including the code, and is able to disarm the false alarm, and to authorize repairs to the alarm system.\n\nRobbery alarm notification. A silent alarm system signal generated by the entry of a designated code into an arming station in order to signal that the alarm user is being forced to turn off the alarm system and requires a law enforcement response. It also includes a silent alarm generated by the manual activation of a device to signal a robbery in progress or immediately after it occurred.\n\nTakeover. The transaction or process which an alarm user takes control of an existing alarm system that was previously controlled by another alarm user.\n\nVerify. An attempt by the alarm company to contact the alarm site or alarm user by telephone, including text message, whether or not actual contact is made. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Defines the terms used throughout the Alarm Systems chapter, including alarm system, alarm site (residential, commercial, educational, governmental), alarm user, alarm company, responder, the several false-alarm-notification types (burglar, robbery, fire, panic, medical), and key roles (alarm administrator, director, communications center). Note the alarm-system definition excludes vehicle alarms (unless the vehicle is used for habitation at a permanent site), alarms that only alert the premises' inhabitants, and alarms on city-occupied premises.", street:["Whether a device is even a covered 'alarm system' turns on this section — a self-contained alarm that only sounds to alert the occupants (no signal summoning city services) is expressly excluded, as is a vehicle alarm.", "A 'responder' has a specific meaning: someone who can reach the site within 30 minutes, has access and the code, and can disarm and authorize repairs — relevant to the 30-minute response duties elsewhere in the chapter.", "A robbery alarm notification is a silent, code- or manually-triggered signal indicating a person is being forced to disarm — treat it as a possible in-progress robbery, not a routine false-alarm response."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-2", name:"Permit and Fee Required; Application, Duration, Renewal, Transferability", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Offense to operate/fail to apply without a permit — operate-without-permit capped at $250 (§ 6-7(b)); other violations up to $500 (§ 6-19). Fees are civil.", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 6-2. Permit and fee required; application, duration, renewal transferability.\n(a) Permit required. Any person owning or operating an alarm system must apply for a permit within thirty (30) days of installation of the alarm system. A person commits an offense if he fails to apply for a permit within thirty (30) days after installation of the alarm system and/or if he thereafter operates or causes to be operated an alarm system without a valid permit issued pursuant to this chapter. A separate permit application is required for each alarm site and each type of alarm system. It is a defense to prosecution if the permit application has been submitted to the alarm administrator in accordance with this chapter and the alarm administrator is processing the permit application.\n(b) Fees.\n(1) An annual, nonrefundable fee of thirty-five dollars ($35.00) is required for each residential alarm permit or renewal of a permit. The annual nonrefundable fee for each commercial permit is one hundred dollars ($100.00), including renewal of a permit.\n(2) A permit is valid for a period of twelve (12) months from the date of issuance. Permits must be renewed within ten (10) days of the expiration of the previously issued permit. An updated application and registration renewal fee must be submitted for renewal.\n(3) Governmental and public educational sites are exempt from all permit fees, false alarm charges, service fees and fines that are assessed under this chapter as long as the entity has a valid alarm permit, but shall comply with all other requirements of this chapter.\n(c) Late fee for renewal. A failure to renew within the ten-day period shall incur a late fee of twenty-five dollars ($25.00) for each alarm system that was not renewed in the applicable period.\n(d) Authority for city to enter and deactivate alarm. Application for a permit under the provisions of this section constitutes a grant of approval to the city to deactivate an alarm system that sounds an alarm signal for longer than thirty (30) minutes after being notified, including entry onto and into the premises of the alarm site for this purpose. The right of entry includes a waiver of any damages incurred to the premises or the alarm system as a result of this access and deactivation.\n(e) Permit requirements. Each permit application must contain the following information and be complete, true and accurate in its entirety:\n(1) Name, address, and telephone number(s) of the permit holder who will be responsible for the proper maintenance and operation of the alarm system and payment of fees assessed under this chapter; the mailing address if different than the address of the permit holder or the alarm site;\n(2) The classification of the alarm site as either residential or commercial including the building number and the apartment number;\n(3) For each alarm system located at the alarm site, the classification of the alarm system (i.e. burglary, robbery, panic alarms or other) and for each classification, whether such alarm is audible or silent;\n(4) Any dangerous, hazardous, or special conditions present at the alarm site;\n(5) The name and telephone number of the alarm company that has agreed to receive calls for the permitted alarm system, if applicable;\n(6) Provide at least two (2) names of responders and their telephone numbers who are able to receive notification of an alarm system activation and respond to the alarm site within thirty (30) minutes of being notified with a key or other means of access to the premises and, if needed, can deactivate the alarm system. Preference should be given to the use of cellular phone numbers as backup contact to the primary alarm site number; or\n(7) Signed certification from the alarm user that includes the following:\na. The date of the installation, conversion, or takeover of the alarm system;\nb. The name, address, and telephone number of the alarm installation company or companies performing the installation, conversion, or takeover;\nc. The name, address and telephone number of the alarm company that performs the monitoring service if different than subsection b. above;\nd. That a set of written operating instructions for the alarm system that include guidelines on how to avoid false alarms, have been left with the applicant by the alarm company;\ne. That the applicant has been trained by the alarm company in the proper use of the alarm system, including instructions on how to avoid false alarms;\nf. That in consideration for the ability to have an alarm permit, the applicant is authorized to and grants to the city the right to enter onto the alarm site, including the right to enter into a residence or building for the purpose of disarming a false alarm if the alarm user or responder is not present or is unable to deactivate the false alarm. The right of entry includes a waiver of any damages incurred to the premises or the alarm system as a result of this access and deactivation; and\ng. Any other information required by the alarm administrator that is necessary for the enforcement of this chapter.\n(f) A city resident who has a valid permit that is more than sixty (60) days from expiration may transfer said permit to a new location within the city.\n(g) Upon receipt of a completed alarm permit application and the alarm permit fee including any past due fees, penalties and fines, the alarm administrator shall register the applicant and issue a permit number unless the applicant has:\n(1) Failed to pay a fine, penalty or fee assessed under this chapter;\n(2) Had an alarm permit for the alarm site suspended or revoked, and the violation that resulted in a suspension or revocation has not been corrected; or\n(3) Made any false statement or misrepresentation of a material fact for the purpose of obtaining an alarm permit or renewal, or while making a change thereto. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Requires anyone owning or operating an alarm system to apply for a permit within 30 days of installation, with a separate application for each alarm site and each type of system. Failing to apply within 30 days, or thereafter operating without a valid permit, is an offense (it is a defense that a complete application is on file and being processed). Sets annual fees ($35 residential / $100 commercial), a 12-month validity with a 10-day renewal window, a $25 late fee, and exempts governmental and public-educational sites from fees. Applying for a permit grants the city authority to enter and deactivate an alarm sounding longer than 30 minutes.", street:["Operating an alarm system with no permit on file is chargeable — but there is a defense if a complete application has been submitted and is being processed, so ask whether one is pending before citing.", "The operate-without-permit offense is specifically capped at $250 under § 6-7(b); the fail-to-timely-apply offense defaults to the § 6-19 $500 cap.", "Governmental and public educational sites are fee-exempt but must still hold a valid permit and comply with everything else.", "By applying for the permit, the holder has pre-consented to city entry to deactivate an alarm sounding past 30 minutes — that consent is the permit's, not a substitute for a warrant in any criminal-investigation context."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-3", name:"Revocation of Permit", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Offense to operate after revocation/refusal — penalty per § 6-19 (up to $500)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 6-3. Revocation of permit.\n(a) The alarm administrator may revoke or refuse to renew an alarm system permit for failure to meet the standards and requirements set out in this chapter.\n(b) The alarm administrator may revoke or refuse to renew an alarm permit if the alarm administrator determines, in his/her sole discretion, that the alarm system in question has a history of unreliability, which unreliability shall be presumed upon the occurrence, in the immediately preceding twelve (12) month period, of:\n(1) Eight (8) false burglar alarms;\n(2) Five (5) false robbery alarms;\n(3) Five (5) false fire alarms;\n(4) Five (5) false medical emergency assistance alarms; or\n(5) Five (5) false panic alarms.\n(c) The alarm administrator may revoke a permit for a false robbery alarm activated by a single action, nonrecessed button.\n(d) A revoked permit may be reissued upon the payment of a twenty-five dollars ($25.00) reinstatement fee and upon:\n(1) Determination by the alarm administrator that the applicant has made a sufficient showing that the conditions which caused the false alarms have been corrected and that the alarm system is likely to be maintained and operated in a responsible manner in accordance with the provisions of this chapter;\n(2) Payment of all outstanding fees, penalties and fines; and\n(3) If required by the alarm administrator, a certification from an alarm company, stating that the alarm system at the alarm site has been repaired or adjusted in a manner to attempt to eliminate false alarms and describes the actions that occurred to make that certification, and that the alarm user has been made aware of the issues that resulted or may result in false alarms, including but not limited to the impact of pets, home decorations, changes in the environment, need to train responders who have access to the premises by providing the responders the code(s) to deactivate the alarm system and passwords to identify the responders to the alarm company in an alarm situation.\n(e) A person may appeal a revocation or refusal to renew a permit in accordance with the procedures set forth in section 6-4.\n(f) A person commits an offense if he operates an alarm system after the alarm administrator revokes or refuses to issue or renew a permit for that alarm system. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Lets the alarm administrator revoke or refuse to renew a permit for failing to meet chapter standards or for a presumed 'history of unreliability' — presumed at 8 false burglar alarms, or 5 false robbery/fire/medical/panic alarms, in the preceding 12 months — and specifically for a single-action, non-recessed robbery button. A revoked permit can be reissued on a $25 reinstatement fee, payment of outstanding amounts, and (if required) a corrective certification. Operating an alarm system after revocation or refusal to issue/renew is an offense.", street:["The patrol-relevant offense is subsection (f): operating an alarm system after the permit has been revoked or a renewal refused.", "The unreliability thresholds (8 false burglar / 5 false robbery, fire, medical, or panic in 12 months) are the administrator's revocation triggers — useful context on a chronic-false-alarm address.", "A single-action, non-recessed 'robbery' button is a specific revocation ground — its presence tends to explain repeated accidental robbery-alarm dispatches."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-4", name:"Appeal from Denial, Revocation or Nonrenewal of a Permit", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Administrative appeal procedure — not an offense", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 6-4. Appeal from denial, revocation or nonrenewal of a permit.\n(a) If the alarm administrator refuses to issue or renew a permit, or revokes a permit, the alarm administrator shall send to the applicant or permit holder by certified mail, return receipt requested, written notice of the alarm administrator's decision and a statement of the right to an appeal. The applicant or permit holder may appeal the decision of the alarm administrator to the director by filing with the director a written request for a hearing, setting forth the reasons for the appeal, within ten (10) calendar days after the receipt of the notice from the alarm administrator. The filing of a request for an appeal hearing with the director stays the action of the alarm administrator until the director makes the final decision. If a request for an appeal hearing is not made within the ten (10) day period, the action of the alarm administrator is final. An alarm permit holder with an existing permit, must have thirty days' notice before the nonrenewal is effective.\n(b) The director shall serve as hearing officer at an appeal hearing and consider evidence offered by any interested person. The formal rules of evidence do not apply at any appeal hearing and the director shall make his final decision on the basis of a preponderance of the evidence presented at the hearing. The director must render a decision within thirty (30) days after the request for an appeal hearing is filed. The director shall affirm, reverse, or modify the action of the alarm administrator, and his decision is final. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Sets the administrative appeal path: the administrator must give certified-mail notice of a denial, revocation, or nonrenewal and of the right to appeal; the applicant/holder may appeal to the director within 10 calendar days, which stays the action pending decision. The director sits as hearing officer under a preponderance standard (formal rules of evidence do not apply), must decide within 30 days, and may affirm, reverse, or modify — the director's decision is final.", street:["This is procedure, not an offense — no enforcement action flows from this section on patrol.", "Useful context if a permit holder claims their permit is still valid: a timely-filed appeal stays the administrator's action until the director rules, so a revocation may not yet be final."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-5", name:"Other Types of Alarms", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Unlawful conduct — penalty per § 6-19 general penalty (up to $500)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 6-5. Other types of alarms.\n(a) It shall be unlawful for a person to install or maintain an alarm system that summons a public safety response from the city for the purpose of eliciting responses to burglaries, robberies, fires, panic or medical emergencies unless specifically authorized by this chapter.\n(b) If innovations in alarm systems or other types of alarm devices adversely affect emergency services in the city, the director may promulgate other rules and regulations in order to protect the city's emergency services. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Makes it unlawful to install or maintain an alarm system that summons a city public-safety response for burglaries, robberies, fires, panic, or medical emergencies unless specifically authorized by this chapter, and lets the director issue additional rules if new alarm technologies begin to adversely affect city emergency services.", street:["Catches alarm setups that summon a public-safety response but fall outside what the chapter authorizes — the hook is 'not specifically authorized by this chapter.'", "No stated in-section penalty; charge under the § 6-19 general chapter penalty (up to $500, each day separate)."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-9", name:"Duties of the Alarm User", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"User duties — breach chargeable per § 6-19 (up to $500)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 6-9. Duties of the alarm user.\n(a) An alarm user shall:\n(1) Operate the alarm site and the alarm system in a manner that minimizes or eliminates false alarms;\n(2) Make every reasonable effort to have a responder to the alarm site within thirty (30) minutes when requested by the communications center in order to:\na. Deactivate the alarm;\nb. Provide access to the alarm site and alarm system;\nc. Provide alternative security to the alarm site.\n(b) Not activate an alarm system for any reason other than an occurrence of an event that the alarm system was designed to report.\n(c) Adjust the mechanism of an inside sounder so that the alarm will sound for no longer than ten (10) minutes.\n(d) Maintain a written set of operating instructions for each alarm system at the alarm site.\n(e) Upon reasonable notification, allow the alarm administrator or his designee to inspect the alarm site and alarm system of the permit holder.\n(f) Not use a robbery alarm notification that is a single action, nonrecessed button.\n(g) Inform the alarm administrator in writing of any changes that alter information listed on the permit application within five (5) business days of the change. No fee will be assessed for such changes. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Lists the alarm user's affirmative duties: operate so as to minimize/eliminate false alarms; make every reasonable effort to get a responder on scene within 30 minutes when dispatch requests it (to deactivate, provide access, or arrange alternative security); not trigger the system except for events it was designed to report; limit an inside sounder to 10 minutes; keep written operating instructions on site; allow inspection on reasonable notice; not use a single-action, non-recessed robbery button; and report permit-application changes within 5 business days.", street:["The 30-minute responder duty is the practical one on scene — when dispatch has requested a responder, the user's failure to make a reasonable effort to get one there is a breach of duty.", "An inside sounder running longer than 10 minutes is a specific, observable violation.", "Breach of any listed duty is chargeable under § 6-19 (up to $500); document which specific duty was not met."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-10", name:"Duties of Alarm Company", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Company duties — breach chargeable per § 6-12 / § 6-19", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 6-10. Duties of alarm company.\n(a) All alarm companies shall be licensed through the Texas Department of Public Safety Private Security Bureau as required by the Texas Occupation Code, chapter 1702, as amended.\n(b) An alarm company shall:\n(1) Confirm with the alarm administrator that a valid alarm permit has been issued by the city for an alarm site before performing any alarm system conversion at the alarm site.\n(2) Send a certification to the alarm administrator within thirty (30) days of performing or causing the performance of an alarm system installation or conversion. The certificate must state:\na. The date of installation or conversion of the alarm system, whichever is applicable;\nb. The name, address, telephone number and current state license number of the alarm company providing the alarm system installation or conversion;\nc. The name, address, telephone number and current state license number of the alarm company providing monitoring for the alarm system if different from the alarm company under contract to provide installation or conversion for the alarm system;\nd. That a complete set of written operating instructions for the alarm system, including, without limitation, written guidelines on how to avoid false alarms has been left with the applicant; or\ne. That the alarm company has trained the applicant in the proper use of the alarm system, including, without limitation, instructions on how to avoid, and through their alarm company, how to cancel false alarms.\n(3) Send notification of an alarm to the city by the means currently specified by the alarm administrator;\n(4) Communicate alarm dispatch requests and cancellations to the communication center in a manner determined by the alarm administrator;\n(5) Communicate any available information (permit number, north south, front, back, floor, etc.) about the premises on all alarm signals related to the alarm dispatch request;\n(6) Communicate the type of alarm activation (silent, audible, interior or perimeter);\n(7) After making an alarm dispatch request, promptly advise the communications center if the alarm company is aware that the alarm user and/or responder is on the way to the alarm site;\n(8) Contact the alarm user or responder within twenty-four (24) hours via mail, email, fax, telephone or other electronic means when an alarm dispatch request is made;\n(9) Report alarms signals and dispatch requests by using telephone numbers designated by the alarm administrator; and\n(10) Before requesting an alarm dispatch request to an alarm signal, verify every alarm signal, except a panic, robbery, fire or emergency medical alarm activation, by making a minimum of two (2) telephone calls to two (2) separate phone numbers as per ANSI/CSAA C-V-01 Standard for the telephone verification of alarm signals.\n(c) An alarm company shall not install an automatic voice dialer as part of an alarm system unless it is limited to panic alarm notifications. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Requires alarm companies to be licensed through the Texas DPS Private Security Bureau (Occupations Code ch. 1702) and imposes operational duties: confirm a valid permit before a conversion; certify installations/conversions within 30 days; transmit dispatch requests and cancellations as the administrator directs; pass along premises and activation details; advise dispatch when a responder is en route; contact the user/responder within 24 hours of a dispatch request; and, before requesting dispatch on a non-panic/robbery/fire/medical signal, verify by at least two calls to two separate numbers (ANSI/CSAA two-call verification). Automatic voice dialers may only be installed for panic notifications.", street:["The two-call verification duty (b)(10) is why routine burglar-alarm dispatches should already have been verified — panic, robbery, fire, and medical activations are exempt from that verification step.", "An unlicensed alarm company is itself a violation — company licensing runs through Texas DPS, not the city.", "Company breaches are reachable through § 6-12 (offenses for alarm companies) and the § 6-19 general penalty, and entities are criminally liable through their agents under § 6-19(c)."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-11", name:"Duty to Maintain and Provide Records", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Company recordkeeping duty — breach chargeable per § 6-19 (up to $500)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 6-11. Duty to maintain and provide records. Upon the effective date of this chapter, an alarm company shall:\n(1) Maintain for a period of one (1) year from the date of the alarm dispatch request, records relation to alarm dispatch requests. That include the name, address and telephone number of the alarm user and evidence that demonstrates attempts to verify. The alarm administrator may request copies of the records of individually named alarm users located in the city. If the request is made within sixty (60) days of an alarm request dispatch, the alarm company shall furnish the requested records within three (3) business days of receipt of the request. If the request is made between sixty (60) days to one year after an alarm dispatch request, the alarm company shall furnish the records within thirty (30) days of the request.\n(2) Provide the alarm administrator with the names and telephone numbers of the alarm user's responders maintained by the alarm company for that alarm user at the time of the alarm dispatch request or within a reasonable time thereafter, not to exceed forty-eight (48) hours, if the communication center requests that information. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Requires an alarm company to keep alarm-dispatch-request records (alarm user name, address, phone, and evidence of verification attempts) for one year and produce them to the administrator on request — within 3 business days if requested within 60 days of the dispatch, within 30 days if requested later — and to provide the user's responder names and numbers, on request, within 48 hours.", street:["Company-facing recordkeeping duty — not a patrol offense, but the verification-attempt records it preserves are the paper trail behind a disputed false-alarm dispatch.", "Breach defaults to the § 6-19 general penalty."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-12", name:"Offenses for Alarm Companies", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Offense (unlicensed/noncompliant relaying) — penalty per § 6-19 (up to $500)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 6-12. Offenses for alarm companies. A person commits an offense if he engages in the business of relaying alarm notifications in the city without complying fully with this chapter. This shall not apply to installation or activation of a personal emergency response system, as defined by Texas Occupation Code, section 1702.331, as amended. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Makes it an offense to engage in the business of relaying alarm notifications in the city without fully complying with the chapter. Does not apply to installation or activation of a personal emergency response system as defined by Texas Occupations Code § 1702.331.", street:["This is the company-side offense hook: relaying alarm notifications as a business while out of compliance with the chapter.", "Personal emergency response systems (medical-alert style) under Occupations Code § 1702.331 are carved out.", "Entities are criminally liable through their agents under § 6-19(c) — the offense can run against the company itself."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-13", name:"Duties and Authority of the Alarm Administrator", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Administrator duties/authority — not an offense", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 6-13. Duties and authority of the alarm administrator.\n(a) The alarm administrator shall establish a procedure for notification to the alarm user of a false alarm. The notice shall include the following information:\n(1) Date and time of public safety response;\n(2) Identification number of the public safety person; and\n(3) A statement advising the alarm user to ensure that the alarm system is properly operated, inspected and serviced in order to avoid false alarm and resulting fees and fines.\n(b) The alarm administrator may implement an alarm user awareness class.\n(c) The alarm administrator may require an alarm user to remove a robbery alarm that is a single action, nonrecessed button, if a false alarm has occurred. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Directs the alarm administrator to set up a false-alarm notification procedure (notice stating the date/time of response, the responder's ID number, and a reminder to service the system), authorizes an alarm-user awareness class, and lets the administrator require removal of a single-action, non-recessed robbery button after a false alarm.", street:["Administrative authority, not an offense — this is the administrator's toolkit, not a patrol charging section.", "Note (in the source PDF, this section's text was displaced under the § 6-17 heading by the export's layout; it belongs here under 'Duties and authority of the alarm administrator')."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-14", name:"Direct Alarm Reporting", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Unlawful conduct — penalty per § 6-19 general penalty (up to $500)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 6-14. Direct alarm reporting. It shall be unlawful for any person or business to operate or energize an alarm system or an alarm device which activates an automatic dialing device that sends a signal to the communications center. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Makes it unlawful for any person or business to operate or energize an alarm system or device that activates an automatic dialing device sending a signal directly to the communications center.", street:["Targets auto-dialer devices that ring the dispatch center directly — a discrete, chargeable configuration distinct from the § 6-8 maintenance offenses.", "Read alongside § 6-9(a)(6)/§ 6-10(c), which bar automatic voice dialers except for panic notifications.", "No stated in-section penalty; charge under § 6-19 (up to $500, each day separate)."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-16", name:"Confidentiality", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Records confidentiality — not an offense", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 6-16. Confidentiality. To the extent allowed by law, all information contained in and gathered through the alarm registration applications, records relating to alarm dispatch requests, and applications for appeals shall, are confidential and shall be held in confidence by all employees or representatives of the city and by any third-party administrator or employees of a third-party administrator with access to such information. This provision shall not prevent an alarm company from receiving confirmation from the city that an alarm permit has been issued for an alarm site. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Makes alarm registration applications, alarm-dispatch-request records, and appeal applications confidential, to be held in confidence by city employees/representatives and any third-party administrator, to the extent allowed by law — while still permitting an alarm company to receive confirmation that a permit has been issued for a site.", street:["Handling/disclosure rule for alarm records — not a charging section.", "Bears on public-records and disclosure requests for alarm registration data; the carve-out lets a company confirm a site's permit status."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-17", name:"Termination of Response", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Response-termination policy — not an offense", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 6-17. Termination of response.\n(a) Responses from the police and fire departments may be terminated to nonpermitted alarm sites after notification to the owner or last known permit holder of the alarm site has been made by regular and certified mail, return receipt requested.\n(b) Responses will not be terminated because of excessive false burglar notifications to a residential alarm site as long as a valid permit exists and all fees are paid in full. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Allows police and fire response to be terminated to nonpermitted alarm sites after certified-mail notice to the owner or last known permit holder, but bars termination of response to a residential alarm site for excessive false burglar notifications as long as a valid permit exists and all fees are paid in full.", street:["Policy on when the city may stop responding — context, not a patrol offense.", "A permitted residential site in good standing (fees paid) keeps its response even with excessive false burglar alarms; the no-response tool is aimed at nonpermitted sites.", "Note (in the source PDF, this section's body was split across the page break and displaced near § 6-19 by the export's layout; it belongs here under 'Termination of response')."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 6-18", name:"Government Immunity", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alarms"], level:"Liability disclaimer / governmental immunity — not an offense", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 6-18. Government immunity. The issuance of an alarm permit and/or the provisions set forth in this chapter are not intended to, nor do they create a contract, duty or obligation, either expressed or implied, of a response by the city. Any and all liability and consequential damage resulting from the failure to respond to a notification is hereby disclaimed and governmental immunity as provided by law is retained. By applying for an alarm permit, the permit holder acknowledges that law enforcement, fire and/or emergency medical response may be influenced by factors such as, among other things: availability, priority of calls, weather conditions, traffic conditions, emergency conditions and staffing levels and that an alarm permit is not a guarantee of any public safety response at any time notwithstanding the above, the city may discontinue service to an alarm site for failure to pay false alarm fees. (Ordinance 16-11-91 adopted 11/15/16)", summary:"Provides that issuing an alarm permit creates no contract, duty, or obligation to respond, disclaims liability for any failure to respond, retains governmental immunity, and has the permit holder acknowledge that response may be affected by availability, call priority, weather, traffic, emergencies, and staffing — and that the city may discontinue service for unpaid false-alarm fees.", street:["Liability/immunity provision — no enforcement action flows from it.", "Reinforces that a permit is not a guarantee of response and that service can be discontinued for unpaid false-alarm fees."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 10-1", name:"Definitions (Alcoholic Beverages)", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alcohol"], level:"Definitions — reference; not an offense", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 10-1. Definitions. Unless the context otherwise requires, the following terms as used in this article shall be construed according to the definitions given below:\n\nAlcoholic beverage. Any spirits, wine, beer, ales, or other liquid containing more than one-half of one percent of alcohol by volume, which is fit for beverage purposes.\n\nLate hours permit. Any permit, license or other authorization issued by the state that grants the holder thereof a privilege to sell and offer for sale alcoholic beverages between midnight and 2:00 a.m. on any day.\n\nPublic place. Any place to which the public, or a substantial group of the public, has access and includes, but is not limited to streets, alleys, highways, public parks, in the common areas of schools, hospitals, churches, apartment houses, office buildings, transport facilities and shops. (Ordinance 80-07-02, sec. 2, adopted 7/15/80; Ordinance 14-11-73, sec. 3, adopted 11/18/14; Ordinance 14-12-76, sec. 2, adopted 12/8/14)", summary:"Defines terms for the Alcoholic Beverages chapter: 'alcoholic beverage' (any liquid containing more than one-half of one percent alcohol by volume that is fit for beverage purposes), 'late hours permit' (state authorization to sell between midnight and 2:00 a.m.), and 'public place' (broadly, anywhere the public or a substantial group of the public has access — including streets, alleys, highways, parks, and the common areas of schools, hospitals, churches, apartment houses, office buildings, transport facilities, and shops).", street:["The 0.5%-ABV threshold is the same line the Texas Alcoholic Beverage Code draws for what counts as an alcoholic beverage.", "'Public place' is defined broadly here and reaches the common areas of apartment houses and office buildings, not just streets and parks — note it for any public-place question that turns on this article."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 10-2", name:"Late Night Hours Sales", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alcohol"], level:"Regulatory — not an offense; states the legal sale window", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 10-2. Late night hours sales. The holder of a late hours permit may sell and offer for sale alcoholic beverages between midnight and 2:00 a.m. on any day, provided that the holder complies with the Texas Alcoholic Beverage Code, as it exists or may be amended. (Ordinance 14-11-73, sec. 4, adopted 11/18/14; Ordinance 14-12-76, sec. 3, adopted 12/8/14)", summary:"A holder of a late-hours permit may sell alcoholic beverages between midnight and 2:00 a.m. on any day, provided the holder also complies with the Texas Alcoholic Beverage Code.", street:["Confirms the legal window for late-hours sales (midnight–2 a.m.) — compliance still requires a valid state TABC permit alongside the city late-hours permit.","If a business is selling after 2 a.m., or has no late-hours permit at all, look to the Texas Alcoholic Beverage Code for the state offense — this ordinance only extends the local hours, it doesn't create the underlying sales offense."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 10-19", name:"Permit Required; Annual Permit Fee Established", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alcohol"], level:"Unlawful to sell/distribute without a city permit — penalty not stated in this article; charge under the city's general penalty provision (Ch. 1)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 10-19. Permit required and annual permit fee established. It shall be unlawful for any person to manufacture, distill, brew, import, transport, store for purposes of sale, distribute or sell any beer, wine or other alcoholic beverage within the city without first paying the appropriate fee to the city secretary and obtaining a city permit to sell alcoholic beverages at a specific location. The fee shall be equal to one-half of the fee charged by the state, as amended, for the particular license issued by the Texas Alcoholic Beverage Commission (\"TABC\"), except when said fee is waived according to the provisions of the state alcoholic beverage code. Following payment of the fee and approval of the permit application, as set forth herein, the city secretary shall issue a permit for that location for a period of one year. Such permit fee shall be paid to the city secretary annually. (Ordinance 09-07-39, sec. 3, adopted 7/27/09)", summary:"Makes it unlawful to manufacture, distill, brew, import, transport, store for sale, distribute, or sell any alcoholic beverage within the city without first paying the city permit fee and obtaining a city permit for the specific location. The city fee is one-half the corresponding state (TABC) license fee unless waived under state law; the permit runs one year and the fee is paid annually.", street:["This is a city permit-to-sell requirement layered on top of the state TABC license — a business can hold a valid TABC license and still violate this by lacking the city permit for that location.", "The prohibited conduct is broad: not only selling, but manufacturing, transporting, storing for sale, and distributing without the city permit.", "No penalty is stated in this article; charge under the city's general penalty provision (Chapter 1). Verify Chapter 1 before stating any fine amount.", "The city fee is pegged at half the state license fee — a licensing/fee compliance matter more than a field-enforcement one."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 10-20", name:"Permit Application Review / Certificate of Wet-Dry Status", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alcohol"], level:"Administrative (city secretary duty) — not an offense", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 10-20. Permit application review/certificate of wet/dry status. Prior to issuing a city permit to applicant for the proposed location, the city secretary shall certify whether the location is located in an area that is wet and that the sale of alcoholic beverages at this location is not prohibited by charter and/or ordinance. The city secretary shall keep a record of all permits and certificate[s] issued under this chapter. (Ordinance 09-07-39, sec. 4, adopted 7/27/09)", summary:"Directs the city secretary, before issuing a city permit, to certify that the proposed location is in a 'wet' area and that alcohol sales there are not prohibited by charter or ordinance, and to keep a record of all permits and certificates issued under the chapter.", street:["Administrative gatekeeping by the city secretary — not a patrol offense — but it is the wet/dry and location-eligibility check behind whether a location could lawfully hold a city permit at all.", "If a location's wet/dry status is in question on a sales-related call, this is the record the city secretary maintains."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 10-21", name:"Savings / Repealing Clause (Alcoholic Beverages Permits)", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["alcohol"], level:"Savings/repealing clause — not an offense", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 10-21. Savings/repealing clause. All provisions of any ordinance in conflict with this article are hereby repealed, but such repeal shall not abate any pending prosecution for violation of the repealed ordinance, nor shall the repeal prevent a prosecution from being commenced for any violation if occurring prior to the repeal of the ordinance. Any remaining portions of said ordinance shall remain in full force and effect. (Ordinance 09-07-39, sec. 5, adopted 7/27/09)", summary:"A standard savings/repealing clause for the Article II permit provisions: it repeals conflicting ordinance provisions but does not abate pending prosecutions and allows prosecution for violations occurring before the repeal; any unaffected portions remain in full force.", street:["Boilerplate savings/repealing clause — no enforcement action flows from it.", "It preserves the ability to prosecute violations that occurred before the older ordinance was repealed."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 14-4", name:"Rabies Control — Vaccination Requirements", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 14-22 general penalty (up to $2,000)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 14-4. Rabies control.\n(a)    Vaccination requirements.The owner and/or custodian of a domestic dog, domestic cat or domestic ferret shall have his/her animal vaccinated against rabies by four months of age. The animal must receive a rabies booster within a 12-month interval following the initial vaccination. Every domestic dog, cat or ferret must be revaccinated against rabies a minimum of at least once every three years with a rabies vaccine licensed by the USDA. The vaccine must be administered according to label instructions. Livestock should be vaccinated against rabies. Nothing in this section prohibits a veterinarian and owner or custodian from selecting a more frequent rabies vaccination interval. Any person moving into the city from a location outside of the city shall comply with this section of this chapter within 30 days after having moved into the City of Frisco. If the animal inflicted a bite and/or scratch on any person or another animal within the last ten days, the owner and/or custodian of said animal shall report the bite and/or scratch incident to animal services as soon as possible, but not later than 24 hours of moving into the City of Frisco. No rabies vaccine shall be administered during the 240-hour observation period until the 240-hour observation period is concluded according to state law, as it exists or may be amended.\n(b)    Certificate of vaccination.Upon vaccination with an approved rabies vaccine, the veterinarian shall execute and furnish to the owner of the animal as evidence thereof, a certificate upon a form furnished by the veterinarian. The veterinarian shall retain a duplicate copy. Such certificate shall contain the following information:\n(1)   The current name, address and telephone number of the owner of the vaccinated animal;\n(2)   The date of vaccination;\n(3)   The date vaccination expires (revaccination due date);\n(4)   The type of rabies vaccine used, expiration date, and serial number;\n(5)   The year and number of rabies tag to be worn by animal at all times;\n(6)   The breed, age, color, and sex of the vaccinated animal; and\n(7)   The veterinarian's signature or signature stamp and license number.\n(c)    Rabies tags.Concurrent with the issuance and delivery of the certificate of rabies vaccination referred to in subsection (b), the owner of the animal shall cause to be attached to the collar or harness of the rabies vaccinated animal, a metal tag that is serially numbered to correspond with the vaccination certificate number, and bearing the year of issuance and the name of the issuing veterinarian or veterinarian's clinic and his/her telephone number. The owner shall cause the collar or harness with the attached rabies vaccination metal tag to be worn by the animal at all times. Rabies vaccination certificates and tags shall be valid only for the animal for which it was originally issued.\n(d)    Duplicate rabies tags.In the event of loss or destruction of the original rabies tag provided in subsection (c), the owner of the animal shall obtain a duplicate rabies tag from the licensed veterinarian who originally vaccinated the animal. Duplicate rabies vaccination certificates and tags shall be valid only for the animal for which it was originally issued.\n(e)    Proof of vaccination.It shall be unlawful for any person who owns or harbors a vaccinated animal to fail or refuse to exhibit his/her copy of the certificate of vaccination upon demand to any person charged with the enforcement of this chapter.\n(f)    Harboring unvaccinated animal.It shall be unlawful for any person to harbor any animal that has not been vaccinated against rabies, as provided herein, or that cannot be identified as having a current rabies vaccination certificate.\n(g)    Animals exposed to rabies.Any person having knowledge of the existence of any domestic animal known to have been, or suspected of being, exposed to rabies must immediately report such knowledge to animal services, and the LRCA or his/her designee, and provide any information that may be required. For any animal known to have been, or suspected of being, exposed to rabies, the following rules must apply:\n(1)   Domestic animals that have a current rabies vaccination must be humanely euthanized or revaccinated immediately and placed in strict isolation, at the owner's expense, in a primary enclosure for observation according to the method prescribed by the LRCA for a period of not less than 45 days or the suspected rabies carrier animal is available for testing, is tested and the test has returned a negative result for rabies. (See Exhibit A [which is hereby recognized as being in full force and effect as if set out in this Code and kept on file in the city clerk or secretary's office].)\n(2)   Domestic animals that do not have a current rabies vaccination should be humanely euthanized. However, if the owner of such an animal elects, he/she may, at his/her expense and in a manner prescribed by the LRCA, quarantine said animal in a primary enclosure or the suspected rabies carrier animal is available for testing, is tested and the test has returned a negative result for rabies. Such animal must be vaccinated immediately following exposure and placed in strict isolation for not less than 90 days and given booster vaccinations during the third and eighth weeks while in isolation during the observation period. For young animals, additional vaccinations may be necessary to ensure the young animal receives at least two vaccinations at or after the age prescribed by the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) for the vaccine administered. (See Exhibit A attached hereto.)\n(3)   This section only applies to domestic animals for which an approved rabies vaccine is available.\n(4)If a licensed veterinarian determines that a quarantined animal shows the clinical signs of rabies, the veterinarian or animal services shall humanely euthanize the animal. If an animal dies or is euthanized while in quarantine, the veterinarian or animal services shall remove the head of the animal and submit it to the nearest state-approved department laboratory for testing. (Ordinance 08-01-06, sec. 4, adopted 1/15/08; Ordinance 2020-01-03 adopted 1/21/20)", summary:"Owners and custodians of domestic dogs, cats, and ferrets must have the animal vaccinated against rabies by a licensed veterinarian and keep current vaccination records. Sets out reporting duties and the vaccination schedule.", street:["Ask for proof of current rabies vaccination on any animal-related call — lack of a valid vaccination record is independently chargeable.","Ties directly into the § 14-6 quarantine procedure when a bite or exposure is reported."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 14-8", name:"Animals at Large", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 14-22 general penalty (up to $2,000)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 14-8. Animals at large.\n(a)    Prohibition.It shall be unlawful for any owner, custodian, or harborer to allow any domestic dog or other animal possessed, kept, or harbored, to roam at large as defined in section 14-3 of this chapter.\n(b)  Authority of animal services officer.Animal services officers are authorized to pursue onto private and public property and impound animals that roam at large, and may impound animals at large under conditions specified in section 14-13 of this chapter, or when he/she has received a complaint that said animal has caused a nuisance or hazard to the health, safety or welfare of human beings or the animal population. (Ordinance 08-01-06, sec. 8, adopted 1/15/08; Ordinance 2020-01-03 adopted 1/21/20)", summary:"Unlawful for an owner, custodian, or harborer to allow a domestic dog or other animal to roam at large as defined in § 14-3. Animal services officers are authorized to pursue onto private and public property to impound animals at large, including on a nuisance or public-safety complaint.", street:["The core 'loose dog' charge — roaming at large is the violation itself, no bite or injury required.","Animal services' pursuit-and-impound authority extends onto private property, not just public right-of-way.","\"At large\" is defined in § 14-3 — confirm the animal meets that definition before charging."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 14-9", name:"Animal Nuisances", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 14-22 general penalty (up to $2,000)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 14-9. Animal nuisances.\n(a)    The keeping of any animal that physically molests passersby or passing vehicles, attacks other animals, is not accompanied by a responsible person who maintains physical control over the animal by leash, cord, rope or other physical restraint device, trespasses on school grounds, and/ or damages public or private property is prohibited.\n(b)    The keeping of bees in such a manner as to deny the lawful use of adjacent property or endanger personal health, safety and welfare is prohibited. Upon determination that a bee colony situated within the city limits is not being kept in compliance with this section, animal services may order the bees to be removed from the city or destroyed.\n(c)    It shall be unlawful and constitute a public nuisance for an owner/custodian of a cat to allow the cat to roam beyond the boundaries of the owner's/custodian's property.\n(d)    It shall be unlawful and constitute a public nuisance to keep any animal(s) that causes frequent, excessive or long continuous barking, whining, crying, meowing, howling, or other animal- related noise that interferes with public peace and comfort.\n(e)    It shall be unlawful and constitute a public nuisance for any person to maintain any animal in such a manner or allow any pen, enclosure, yard or similar place used for the keeping of animals to become unsanitary, offensive by reason of odor, offensive by lack of maintenance or creates a visual nuisance, creates any favorable condition for any zoonotic diseases or any other diseases, or creates any condition that is a breeding place for fleas, ticks or other vectors.\n(f)    It shall be unlawful and constitute a public nuisance for the owner/custodian of any animal to allow excreta deposited by his/her animal to remain on public or private property. Any condition injurious to public health caused by the lack of or improper disposal of animal waste will be considered a violation of this section. Public property includes, but is not limited to, walks, sidewalks, alleys, parks, or recreation areas.\n(g)    It shall be unlawful for any person to intentionally cause, suffer or permit the maintenance of an attractive environment for the assembly of unconfined and unvaccinated stray dogs or cats by the placement of food. It shall be an affirmative defense that the dogs or cats were feral and that the person placed the food solely for the purpose of apprehending stray dogs or cats.\n(h)    It shall be unlawful for any owner, custodian or person to allow any animal to remain a public nuisance as defined herein.\n(i) It shall be unlawful and constitute a public nuisance to slaughter or kill an animal in public view. (Ordinance 08-01-06, sec. 9, adopted 1/15/08; Ordinance 15-10-76, sec. 2, adopted 10/6/15; Ordinance 2020-01-03 adopted 1/21/20)", summary:"Prohibits keeping an animal that molests passersby or vehicles, attacks other animals, isn't under physical restraint and trespasses on school grounds, or damages property; keeping bees that endanger adjacent property or health; allowing a cat to roam beyond the owner's property; excessive or continuous animal noise disturbing the peace; and unsanitary animal-keeping conditions.", street:["Covers the 'neighbor complaint' animal calls broadly — nuisance barking, roaming cats, unsanitary conditions, and molesting passersby are each independently chargeable here.","Bee-keeping that endangers adjacent property can result in an order to remove or destroy the colony.","Excessive/continuous animal noise is charged here, not under the general noise ordinance (§ 54-90)."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 14-10", name:"Protection of Animals", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 14-22 general penalty; (d) is its own stated offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 14-10. Protection of animals.\n(a)    Baby fowl.It shall be unlawful for any person to sell, offer for sale, barter, or give away as toys, premiums or novelties, baby chickens, ducklings, or other fowl under eight weeks old. Sale of such animals for agricultural purposes is exempt from this provision if sold in quantities of ten or more.\n(b)    Change of color of certain animals.It shall be unlawful to color, dye, stain, or otherwise change the natural color of any chickens, ducklings, other fowl, or rabbits, or to possess for the purpose of sale or to be given away, any of the above-mentioned animals which have been so colored.\n(c)    Animals as prizes or inducements.No person shall give away any animal as:\n(1)   A prize or use as an inducement to enter any contest, game or competition;\n(2)   An inducement to enter a place of amusement or other nonresidential establishment; or\n(3)   An offer or as incentive to enter into any business establishment whereby the offer was for the purpose of attracting trade.\n(d)    Sales of animals from public property.A person commits an offense if he/she sells, exchanges, barters or gives away or offers to sell, exchange, barter or give away any animal from:\n(1)   Any public property; or\n(2)   Any property to which the public has access that does not have a valid certificate of occupancy allowing the sale of animals on the property. It is an affirmative defense to prosecution under this subsection that the person is:\na.    Animal services;\nb.    A government-operated animal shelter; or\nc.    An animal welfare organization.\n[Subsection (e), pet store permitting and facility standards, omitted — code-enforcement/business-licensing matter, not patrol-relevant.]", summary:"Prohibits selling or giving away baby fowl under eight weeks old as toys or novelties, dyeing or altering the natural color of fowl or rabbits for sale, giving away animals as contest prizes or business inducements, and selling or bartering animals from public property (or private property open to the public without a certificate of occupancy for animal sales) — with an affirmative defense for animal services, government shelters, and animal welfare organizations.", street:["The 'puppies for sale in a parking lot' scenario is squarely covered by subsection (d) — sales from public property or open-access private property without a certificate of occupancy.","Dyeing chicks or ducklings for Easter-type sales is its own unlawful act, independent of any animal-cruelty charge.","Animal services, government shelters, and recognized welfare organizations have an affirmative defense to the public-property sales prohibition — verify the seller's status before charging."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 14-11", name:"Wild, Prohibited Animal", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 14-22 general penalty (up to $2,000)", lvlClass:"m", kw:"exotic pet snake reptile monkey primate wolf hybrid venomous illegal pet", text:"§ 14-11. Wild, prohibited animal.\n(a)    An owner shall not own, harbor, shelter, or have custody or control of a wild animal or other prohibited animal for any purpose within the Frisco City limits, except as follows:\n(1)   A county, municipality, agency of the state, an agency of the United States, or an agent or official of a county, municipality, state or agency acting in an official capacity;\n(2)   A research facility, as that term is defined by Section 2(e), Animal Welfare Act (7 U.S.C. sec. 2132), and its subsequent amendments, that is licensed by the Secretary of Agriculture of the United States under that Act;\n(3)   An organization that is an accredited member of the American Zoo and Aquarium Association;\n(4)   An injured, infirmed, orphaned or abandoned wild animal or other prohibited animal while being transported for care or treatment;\n(5)   An injured, infirmed, orphaned or abandoned wild animal or other prohibited animal while being rehabilitated, treated or cared for by a licensed veterinarian, an incorporated human society or animal shelter or a person that holds a rehabilitation permit issued under V.T.C.A., Parks and Wildlife Code ch. 43, subch. C, as it currently exists or may be amended;\n(6)   A wild animal or prohibited animal owned by and in custody or control of a transient circus company that is not based in this state if the animal is used as any essential, integral part of the circus performances;\n(7)   A wild animal or prohibited animal while in the temporary custody or control of a television or motion picture production company during filming of a television or motion picture production in this state; or\n(8)   A wild animal or prohibited animal while being transported in interstate commerce through the state in compliance with the animal Welfare Act (7 U.S.C. sec. 2131 et seq.) and its subsequent amendments and the regulations adopted under that Act.\n(b)    An owner of a wild animal or prohibited animal, even if kept in violation of this section, shall:\n(1)   Notify animal services, the LRCA, and the Frisco Police Department of any attack on a human being by the animal within 24 hours of the attack.\n(2)   Immediately notify animal services, the LRCA, and the Frisco Police Department of any escape of the animal.\n(c)    An owner of a wild animal or prohibited animal that escapes is liable for all costs incurred in apprehending and confining the animal and for any costs and expenses incurred by way of personal injury or death in attempting to apprehend and confine such animal.\n(d)    The LRCA, animal services officers, Frisco Police Officers, or an employee of animal services, or any city-authorized person or agent, shall not be liable to an owner of a wild animal or other prohibited animal for damages that arise in connection with the escape or attack of a wild animal or other prohibited animal, including, but not limited to, liability for damage, injury, or death caused by the wild animal or other prohibited animal during or after the wild animal's or other prohibited animal's escape, or for injury to, or death of, the wild animal or other prohibited animal as a result of apprehension or confinement of the wild animal or other prohibited animal after escape.\n(e)  Search and seizure.Animal services officers, Frisco Police Officers, the LRCA, the LHA, and/or other city-authorized personnel shall be authorized to obtain a search and seizure warrant if there is reason to believe that an animal ordered to be removed from the City of Frisco for being a wild animal or other prohibited animal has not been so removed. (Ordinance 08-01-06, sec. 11, adopted 1/15/08; Ordinance 2020-01-03 adopted 1/21/20)", summary:"Unlawful to own, harbor, shelter, or have custody or control of a wild animal or other prohibited animal within the city for any purpose, subject to the chapter's definitions of prohibited/wild animals.", street:["Confirm the species actually falls within the chapter's 'wild animal' or 'prohibited animal' definition (§ 14-3) before charging.","This is a strict possession-type prohibition — no bite, attack, or nuisance conduct is required."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 14-12", name:"Dangerous Animal", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Class C misdemeanor; Class A if serious bodily injury or death results", lvlClass:"m", kw:"dangerous dog vicious dog pit bull dog bite attack unprovoked biting animal aggressive", text:"§ 14-12. Dangerous animal.\n(a)    It shall be unlawful for any person to own, keep or harbor a dangerous animal within the Frisco City limits, except as provided in this section.\n(b)    For the purposes of this section, a person learns that the person is the owner/custodian of a dangerous animal when the:\n(1)   Owner/custodian knows of an attack committed by the animal as described in the definition of \"dangerous animal\" in section 14-3 above; or\n(2)   Owner/custodian is informed by the court of competent jurisdiction that the animal is a dangerous animal.\n(c)    If the licensee or owner/custodian of a dangerous animal is a minor, the parent or guardian of the minor shall be liable for all costs, injuries and property damage sustained by any person or domestic animal in an unprovoked attack by the dangerous animal.\n(d)    Should any person desire to file a complaint concerning an animal which is believed to be a dangerous animal, a sworn, written complaint must be first filed with animal services and include the following:\n(1)   Name, address and telephone number of complainant and other witnesses;\n(2)   Date, time and location of any incident involving the animal;\n(3)   Description of the animal;\n(4)   Name, address and telephone number of the animal's owner, if known;\n(5)   A statement describing the facts upon which such complaint is based; and\n(6)   Statement describing any incidents where the animal has exhibited dangerous propensities in past conduct, if known.\n(e)    If a person reports an incident described by the definition of \"dangerous animal\" in section 14-3 above, animal services may investigate the incident. Animal services shall accept sworn statements from all victims and witnesses to the attack.\n(f)    After a sworn complaint is filed, it shall be referred to the court of competent jurisdiction to set a time and place for a hearing not to exceed 20 days from the date and time the complaint is received. The animal services officer, or his/her designee, shall give notice of the hearing to the animal's owner at least ten days prior to the hearing date. After the owner of the animal is notified, the owner shall immediately surrender such animal to an animal services officer to keep such animal at the city's animal shelter or at a veterinarian's clinic at the owner's expense, until such time the hearing is held by the court of competent jurisdiction. The owner is liable for all fees and citations pertaining to the animal's impoundment. Each day the animal has not been surrendered to animal services shall constitute a separate offense.\n(1)   Any interested party, including the City of Frisco City Attorney, is entitled to present evidence at the hearing.\n(2)   The court of competent jurisdiction shall receive testimony at the hearing to determine if the animal specified in the complaint is a dangerous animal and should be permanently removed from the City of Frisco, euthanized, or registered as a dangerous animal for the protection of the public health, safety and welfare of the community. To order euthanasia, removal, or registration as a dangerous animal for the public health, safety and welfare, the court of competent jurisdiction must find the following facts to be true:\na.    The animal is a dangerous animal; and\nb.    The euthanasia, removal, or registration of a dangerous animal is necessary to preserve the public health, safety and welfare of the community.\n(3)   If the court of competent jurisdiction finds the animal to be dangerous, the owner shall have a microchip inserted into the dangerous animal by a licensed veterinarian and provide animal services with the alphanumeric combination code contained in the microchip within 30 days to assist in the identification of the dangerous animal. The owner of the dangerous animal shall assume all responsibility for microchipping their animal, including all costs. The dangerous animal must also be made available, at any time, to animal services to verify the microchip data by scanning the animal. Failure to microchip, show proof of microchipping, or make the animal available for scanning shall constitute separate offenses.\n(4)   If the court of competent jurisdiction orders destruction, removal or registration of the animal and the owner is not present at the hearing, the owner shall be given notice of the decision. If the destruction, removal or registration of the animal is not ordered, the city's animal services officer or other city-authorized person shall return the animal to the owner upon the owner's payment of all fees to the city and its authorized agents. If the court of competent jurisdiction orders the animal removed from the city, the owner has 30 days to do so. The owner shall furnish animal services and/or other city-authorized designee evidence of such removal within ten days thereof.\n(5)   A person commits an offense if he/she possesses and fails to release to the city's animal services, or veterinarian as approved by animal services, an animal that has been charged by sworn complaint as provided in subsection (d) of this section and whose euthanasia or removal has been ordered by the court of competent jurisdiction; provided that such euthanasia or removal order has not been appealed. Each day the animal has not been released to the city's animal services or approved veterinarian shall constitute a separate offense.\n(g)    An owner or person filing the action may appeal the decision of the court of competent jurisdiction in the manner provided for the appeal of cases from the court of competent jurisdiction within 10 days of the decision.\n(h)    The City of Frisco may, after notification an animal has been declared a dangerous animal, provide public notice of the declaration.\n(1)   The declaration shall include the dangerous animal's description, place of residence, and any other public information the City of Frisco deems relevant to maintain the public health, safety and welfare.\n(2)   The City of Frisco may provide notice of the dangerous animal by, but is not limited to, publishing notice in a newspaper or other periodical or circular in circulation in the area where the dangerous animal resides, holding a neighborhood meeting, posting notices in the area where the dangerous animal resides, or posting notice on the City of Frisco website.\n(3)   For purposes of determining liability, the release or withholding of information by an appointed or elected official of the City of Frisco is a discretionary act.\n(i)    It is a defense to the determination of an animal as dangerous that:\n(1)   The threat, injury or damage was sustained by a person who at the time was committing a willful trespass or other tort upon the premises occupied by the owner of the animal;\n(2)   Person was teasing, tormenting, abusing or assaulting the animal or has, in the past, been observed or reported to have teased, tormented, abused or assaulted the animal;\n(3)   Person was committing or attempting to commit a crime;\n(4)   Animal(s) attacked or killed was at the time teasing, tormenting, abusing or attacking the alleged dangerous animal;\n(5)   Animal was protecting or defending a person within the immediate vicinity of the animal from an unjustified attack or assault;\n(6)   Animal was injured and responding to pain; or\n(7)   Animal at issue is a trained guard animal in the performance of official duties while confined or under the control of its handler.\n(j)    It is a defense to prosecution under this section that the:\n(1)   Person is a veterinarian, a peace officer, a person employed by a recognized animal shelter or person employed by the state, or a political subdivision of the state, to deal with stray animals and has temporary ownership, custody or control of the animal; provided, however, that for any person to claim a defense in this subsection, that person must be acting within the course and scope of his or her official duties as regards to the dangerous animal;\n(2)   Person is an employee of the institutional division of the Texas Department of Criminal Justice or a law enforcement agency and trains or uses animals for law enforcement or corrections purposes; provided, however, that for any person to claim a defense in this subsection, that person must be acting within the course and scope of his or her official duties as regards to the dangerous animal; or\n(3)   Person is a trainer or an employee of a guard animal company under the Private Investigators and Private Security Agencies Act in V.T.C.A., Occupation Code ch. 1702, as it exists or may be amended; provided, however, that for any person to claim a defense in this subsection, that person must be acting within the course and scope of his/her official duties as regards to the dangerous animal.\n(k)    Requirements for any dangerous animal within the Frisco City limits the owner must comply with all of the following:\n(1)   Register the dangerous animal with animal services within 30 days of entering the city limits or of being determined as a dangerous animal by the court of competent jurisdiction. The dangerous animal registration is valid for one year from the date of issue for the original owner and is not transferable;\n(2)   Present proof of current rabies vaccination;\n(3)   Provide proof of liability insurance in a single incident amount of $100,000.00 for bodily injury or death of any person or persons, of for damage to property owned by any person which may result from the ownership of such animal;\n(4)   Maintain on the dangerous animal at all times a fluorescent orange colored ID collar visible at 50 feet in normal daylight and a tag that provides the animal services issued registration number of the dangerous animal, along with the owner's name, current address and current telephone number so the animal can be identified;\n(5)   Keep all dangerous animals securely confined indoors or in a secure enclosure behind the front building line, except when leashed as provided herein;\n(6)   Not keep a dangerous animal on a porch, patio or in any part of a house or structure that would allow the animal to exit such building of its own volition. In addition, no dangerous animal may be kept in a house or structure when the windows are open or when screen windows or screen doors are the only obstacles preventing the animal from exiting the structure;\n(7)   Prevent a dangerous animal from going outside its secure enclosure, unless such animal is securely leashed with a leash not longer than six feet in length and in the immediate control of a person;\n(8)   Prevent a dangerous animal from going outside its secure enclosure, unless such animal is muzzled in a manner that will not cause injury to the animal, nor interfere with its vision or respiration but shall prevent it from biting any person or animal when the dangerous animal is taken out of its secure enclosure for any reason;\n(9)   Display on their premises a sign that is easily readable by the public using the words \"Beware - dangerous animal\" in a conspicuous place on the enclosure or pen of such dangerous animal and posted on all entrances to the dwelling, building or structure. The sign shall be no smaller than one foot (12 inches x 18 inches) total area, with alphabetic letters with no less than two-inch height;\n(10) Provide to animal services a minimum of two current color photographs of the dangerous animal in two different poses (front and side views) showing the color, any specific markings, and the approximate size of the dangerous animal;\n(11) Have a microchip inserted into the dangerous animal by a licensed veterinarian and provide animal services with the alphanumeric combination code contained in the microchip within ten days. The dangerous animal must also be made available, at any time, to animal services to verify the microchip data by scanning the animal;\n(12) Report any attack(s) the dangerous animal makes on any person or animal as soon as possible, but not later than 24 hours from the time of the incident;\n(13) Report to animal services in writing within 30 calendar days that:\na.    The dangerous animal has been removed from the City of Frisco, along with the new owner's name, current address and current telephone number;\nb.    The dangerous animal has died; or\nc.    The dangerous animal has moved within the city, along with the new owner's name, current address and current telephone number. The new owner must comply with this section and re-register the dangerous animal with animal services.\n(14) Comply with the ownership requirements listed above. If the owner of a dangerous animal fails to comply with the ownership requirements, the owner or harborer will be given written notice that if the animal is not surrendered to animal services for impoundment within seven calendar days, then the dangerous animal may be seized and impounded. A written notice left at the entrance to the premises where the dangerous animal is kept or harbored will be considered valid notice under this subsection.\n(l)    Search and seizure.Animal services officers, Frisco Police Officers, the LRCA, and other city- authorized personnel shall be authorized to obtain a search and seizure warrant if there is reason to believe that:\n(1)   An animal ordered to be removed from the City of Frisco for being dangerous has not been so removed;\n(2)   An animal ordered to be euthanized for being dangerous has not been so euthanized;\n(3)   An owner has failed to comply with one or more of the requirements for registering a dangerous animal according to subsection (k); or\n(4)   A dangerous animal seized and impounded under this section shall not be returned to the owner until the owner complies with all requirements for ownership of a dangerous animal as determined by the court of competent jurisdiction. If all the fees have not been paid and all requirements have not been met within ten days, the dangerous animal may be humanely euthanized.\n(m) Violation.A person commits an offense if the person is the owner of a dangerous animal and the dangerous animal makes an unprovoked attack on another person outside of the animal's secure enclosure and causes bodily injury to the other person.\n(n)    Other violations.A person who owns or keeps custody or control of a dangerous animal commits an offense if the person fails to comply with any provision of this section. An offense under this section is a class C misdemeanor:\n(1)   An offense under this section is a class C misdemeanor, unless the attack causes serious bodily injury or death, in which event the offense is a class A misdemeanor, unless otherwise classified by state law.\n(2)   If a person is found guilty of an offense under this section, the court may order the dangerous animal destroyed by a person listed in V.T.C.A., Health and Safety Code sec. 822.004, as it currently exists or may be amended.\n(3)In addition to criminal prosecution, a person who commits an offense under this section is liable for a civil penalty not to exceed $10,000.00. The City of Frisco Attorney may file suit in a court of competent jurisdiction to collect the penalty. Penalties collected under this subsection shall be retained by the City of Frisco. (Ordinance 08-01-06, sec. 12, adopted 1/15/08; Ordinance 2020-01-03 adopted 1/21/20)", summary:"Comprehensive dangerous-animal scheme: unlawful to own, keep, or harbor a dangerous animal outside a secure enclosure absent a license; sets reporting duties, complaint/hearing/appeal procedures, defenses, search-and-seizure authority for animal services and Frisco police, and grading. An unprovoked attack causing bodily injury outside the animal's enclosure is a Class C misdemeanor, elevated to Class A if the attack causes serious bodily injury or death — with the court able to order destruction of the animal under Texas Health and Safety Code § 822.004.", street:["Grade turns on injury severity: Class C for bodily injury, Class A if the attack causes serious bodily injury or death.","Animal services officers, Frisco PD, and their agents have express search-and-seizure authority under this section — review subsection (l) before acting.","A conviction can trigger a court-ordered destruction of the animal under the state Health & Safety Code — this ties directly into state law, not just the city code.","Check subsections (i)-(j) for statutory defenses before charging — provocation and enclosure-related defenses are built into the section."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 14-13", name:"Impoundment", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Procedural authority — not an offense", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 14-13. Impoundment.\n(a)    The following animals may be impounded:\n(1)   Any animal believed to be infected with rabies;\n(2)   Any animal posing a threat to the public health, safety or welfare;\n(3)   Any animal found at large;\n(4)   Any animal treated in a manner determined by animal services to be cruel and/or inhumane;\n(5)   Any animal that is suspected of biting or scratching a human being, or any animal that is suspected of coming into contact with a rabies high risk animal that requires isolation to observe for possible rabies, as determined by animal services and/or state or federal authorities;\n(6)   Any animal in protective custody;\n(7)   Any animal seized pursuant to a warrant or court order;\n(8)   Any animal violating any provision of V.T.C.A., Penal Code secs. 42.09,42.091 or 42.10, as they currently exist or may be amended;\n(9)   Any animal violating any provision of V.T.C.A., Health and Safety Code ch. 821, as it currently exists or may be amended;\n(10) Any animal violating any provision of V.T.C.A., Health and Safety Code ch. 822, as it currently exists or may be amended;\n(11) Any animal violating any provision of V.T.C.A., Health and Safety Code ch. 826, as it currently exists or may be amended;\n(12) Any animal violating any provision of V.T.C.A., Health and Safety Code ch. 828, as it currently exists or may be amended;\n(13) Any animal violating any provision of V.T.C.A., Administrative Code ch. 169, as it currently exists or may be amended; and/or\n(14) Any animal violating any provisions of this chapter.\n(b)    If any animals named in this chapter are found upon the premises of any resident located within Frisco's City limits, the city resident shall have the right to confine such animal in a humane manner until he/she can notify animal services to retrieve the animal for impoundment. When so notified, it shall be the duty of animal services to impound such animal as herein provided.\n(c)    Reasonable effort shall be made by animal services to contract the animal owner of any animal impounded that is wearing an identification tag of any type; however, final responsibility for location of an impounded animal is that of the animal owner.\n(d)    The owner can resume possession of any impounded animal upon payment of impoundment fees, handling fees, and any veterinarian bills incurred by animal services and the city's authorized agents for the welfare of the animal, and upon compliance with vaccination, and registration provisions of this chapter.\n(e)    Disposition of animals impounded as a result of cruel or inhumane treatment will be determined by the court of competent jurisdiction.\n(f)    If any animal is being held in quarantine or observation for rabies, the owner shall not be entitled to possession until it has been released from the quarantine observation period by animal services and has satisfied payment of any impoundment fees, handling fees, any veterinarian bills, or any other fees incurred while in the custody of animal services or the city's authorized agents.\n(g)    The city council or city manager shall select and establish a place for impounding animals. The animal shelter will establish criteria and procedures for adoption and final disposition of animals in accordance with the State of Texas Health and Safety Codes in relation to animal handling and care. The City of Frisco will adhere to the animal shelter criteria as part of this chapter.\n(h)    Any animal not reclaimed by the owner may be humanely euthanized or adopted after being impounded for three days, unless under quarantine, by animal services or its city-authorized agents. Any animal wearing a current rabies tag shall be impounded for not less than six days, unless under quarantine. Unclaimed animals wearing an identification tag that are in the custody of animal services or any of its authorized agents may be humanely euthanized or adopted after being impounded for six days.\n(i)    Any seized or impounded, dangerous animal, or wild animal, unless there is reason to believe such animal has an owner, may have its disposition immediately determined as deemed appropriate by animal services, or Frisco's authorized agents.\n(j)    Any nursing baby animal impounded without it's mother, or where the mother cannot or refuses to provide nutritious milk, may be immediately euthanized to prevent further suffering.\n(k)    An animal owner, who no longer wishes responsibility for an animal or believes the animal to be in an ill or injured condition, may sign a written waiver supplied by animal services or its agents, that surrenders the animal to animal services or its authorized agents. The written waiver surrenders the animal to animal services or its authorized agents to be impounded for adoption or to be immediately euthanized in a humane manner. No warm-blooded animal that has bitten or scratched a human being shall be euthanized before the expiration of the quarantine observation period, unless said animal's owner requests the animal be euthanized for rabies testing.\n(l)  Any impounded animal that appears to be suffering from extreme injury or illness may be humanely euthanized as soon as practical or given to a nonprofit humane organization for the purposes of veterinary care or as determined by animal services. (Ordinance 08-01-06, sec. 13, adopted 1/15/08; Ordinance 2020-01-03 adopted 1/21/20)", summary:"Authorizes impoundment of animals believed rabid, posing a threat to public health/safety/welfare, found at large, or otherwise in violation of the chapter, and sets out the impoundment process.", street:["Use this to confirm impoundment authority and process before removing an animal from a scene, especially absent an owner on-site."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 14-15", name:"Animal Ownership Limitation", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 14-22 general penalty (up to $2,000)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 14-15. Animal ownership limitation.\n(a)    From and after the effective date of this chapter, it shall be unlawful for any person, firm or corporation to keep or harbor more than six domestic dogs, or six domestic cats, or three domestic ferrets, or any combination of six thereof, providing the number of domestic ferrets does not exceed three of that species, (i.e., five domestic dogs and one domestic cat; one domestic dog and five domestic cats; three domestic dogs, two domestic cats and one domestic ferret) over the age of six months on any one residential dwelling property located within the Frisco City limits.\n(b)  Kennels are only permitted in districts that meet the requirements of the City of Frisco Comprehensive Zoning Ordinance, as it currently exists or may be amended. (Ordinance 08-01-06, sec. 15, adopted 1/15/08; Ordinance 2020-01-03 adopted 1/21/20)", summary:"Unlawful to keep or harbor more than six domestic dogs or six domestic cats (in combination) at a single premises.", street:["A straightforward headcount violation — six-dog/six-cat combined limit per premises, no nuisance or complaint required to charge."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 14-16", name:"Small Livestock and Large Livestock", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 14-22 general penalty (up to $2,000)", lvlClass:"m", kw:"pig hog chicken goat sheep horse backyard chickens farm animal livestock complaint", text:"§ 14-16. Small livestock and large livestock.\n(a)    Swine:It shall be unlawful for any person, firm or corporation to keep any swine, including potbellied pigs, within the Frisco City limits, unless certified for medical, biological, or other scientific research or study.\n(b)    Cattle and equine:It shall be unlawful for any person to keep a cow, steer, bull or horse, donkey, or mule (at times, collectively referred to as \"cow or horse\") on any premises where the overall area is less than one acre for each cow or horse kept, or is less than one acre for two foals or two calves up to nine months of age. The number of foals or calves permitted on one acre shall not exceed two foals or two calves under nine months of age. Any one adult cow or horse and its young up to nine months of age are permitted on one acre. Agriculture properties are exempt, so long as the person(s) do not keep more than can be cared for under sanitary conditions and/or create a nuisance. The person(s) in lawful possession of the premises as owner, occupant or tenant may keep thereon cattle, horses, calves, or foals belonging to others, but limitation to number of cattle, horses, foals, or calves on the premises and the area and distance requirements of this section shall not be done as a commercial business in violation of the City of Frisco Comprehensive Zoning Ordinance No. 00-11-01, as it currently exists or may be amended.\n(c)    Holding areas for small livestock and/or large livestock:Small livestock and large livestock must be kept within an enclosure, pen, corral or restrictive area to prevent exit by the animal(s). The fence posts must not sway more than six inches when tested by an animal services officer. Gates for small livestock enclosures shall be mounted on hinges to a solid wall or fence posts. Such a gate must connect with another fence post or wall in such a manner that small livestock cannot pass through it, and the gate itself must be constructed so that there is not an opening that will allow the animal(s) to escape the enclosed area. Such gates must have a latch or chain attached capable of keeping the gate closed when tested by an animal services officer.\n(d)    Proximity of livestock areas:It shall be unlawful for any owner to keep on premises within the Frisco City limits under his/her control, any small livestock or large livestock in such a manner that the livestock will be quartered closer than 100 feet from any human living quarters measured in a straight line from any direction, whether occupied or unoccupied. Notwithstanding, if the human living quarters are the living quarters of the owner or keeper, then the small livestock or large livestock must not be quartered closer than 20 feet thereto, measured in a straight line from any direction.\n(e)  Confinement of male horses:Male equines, including, but not limited to, horses, capable of breeding, will be confined in such a manner that said animal will not be dangerous to human beings, and all breeding shall be under the control of the owner or handler. (Ordinance 08-01-06, sec. 16, adopted 1/15/08; Ordinance 2020-01-03 adopted 1/21/20)", summary:"Regulates and restricts keeping swine (including potbellied pigs, absent medical certification) and other small/large livestock within city limits.", street:["Swine — including pot-bellied pigs kept as pets — are unlawful within city limits absent a medical-certification exception; verify before charging a livestock complaint."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 14-19", name:"Treatment of Animals", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Guidelines; does not replace Penal Code animal cruelty offenses", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 14-19. Treatment of animals. The following are established as guidelines for pet animal and animal care and not intended to contravene with the provisions for animal cruelty as contained in V.T.C.A., Penal Code secs. 42.09 and42.10, as they currently exist or may be amended.\n(1)    Every owner/custodian or other person having care and control of any animal shall provide the following for each animal under his/her care and control:\na.    Sufficient nutritious and wholesome food served to the animal in clean containers to maintain the animal in good health;\nb.    Clean and wholesome water served to the animal in a clean container and such water to be available to the animal at all times;\nc.    Adequate shelter, which shall allow the pet animal to remain dry and protected from the elements at all times, allow room for the pet animal to stand, move around and lay down apart from its excrement and which shall provide either natural or artificial shade for the pet animal to avoid direct sunlight. If the shelter is provided by enclosure, the enclosure shall allow for adequate ventilation;\nd.    Veterinary care as needed to prevent suffering;\ne.    Any animal which is not provided the basic level of care and protection as outlined in this section may be immediately removed and impounded. Any animal left without basic care due to injury, illness, incarceration or other involuntary absence of the person responsible for the care of such animal may be immediately removed and impounded. The animal shall remain in the custody of animal services until the conditions are improved and an animal services officer has determined that such animal can be safely returned to the owner or agent. The owner or agent reclaiming such animal will be responsible for paying all applicable fees and citations. If the conditions have not improved within 30 days, final disposition of the animal shall be determined by animal services.\n(2)    No person shall torture, beat, cruelly ill-treat, overload, overwork or otherwise abuse an animal; or cause, instigate, or permit any dogfight, cockfight, bullfight, or other combat between animals or between animals and human beings.\n(3)    No owner of an animal shall abandon such animal.\n(4)    Any person who, as the operator of a motor vehicle or any other means of transportation, strikes any domestic animal or livestock shall stop at once and render such assistance and shall immediately report such injury or death to the animal's owner. In the event the animal's owner cannot be ascertained and/or located, such operator shall at once report the accident to animal services or the appropriate law enforcement agency.\n(5)    No person shall intentionally or knowingly trip a horse or other equine.\n(6)    No owner/custodian or person shall leave any animal in a standing or parked vehicle in such a way as to endanger the animal's health, safety or welfare, including but not limited to, dangerous temperature, lack of food, water or attention, or confinement with a dangerous animal. Any animal services officer, peace officer, fire personnel or other city-authorized person is authorized to use reasonable force to remove an animal, including but not limited to, the breaking of a vehicle window, whenever it appears the animal's health, safety or welfare is, or soon will be, endangered and said animal may be impounded.\n(7)    Tethering animals.A person commits an offense if he/she tethers an animal to a stationary object for any length of time.\na.    It shall be an affirmative defense to prosecution under subsection a. if the animal is tethered on the owner/custodian's property or as part of a lawful city-sponsored event, veterinary treatment, grooming, training, law enforcement activity, or when needed to protect the safety or welfare of a person or animal, provided that all of the following conditions are met:\ni.     The animal's owner/custodian maintains continuous, direct physical control of the animal throughout the period of restraint; ii.    The tether is attached to a properly fitting collar or harness and is not wrapped around the animal's neck. Choke or prong-type collars shall not be used; iii.   The tether is designed and placed in a manner to prevent entanglement or injury; and iv.    The tether does not allow the animal to move outside the owner/custodian's property or to come within ten (10) feet of public property if tethered outside of a fenced area.\nb. It shall be an affirmative defense to prosecution under subsection a. if the tether includes a \"skyline\"-type aerial trolley consisting of a line that is strung between two (2) fixed points that are at least twenty (20) feet apart with a down line that is at least five (5) feet in length provided that the conditions of subsections a.i through a.iv are met and the animal is enclosed behind a fence of adequate size and strength capable of preventing the general public, including children, or other animals from entering the area. (Ordinance 08-01-06, sec. 19, adopted 1/15/08; Ordinance 15-10-76, sec. 2, adopted 10/6/15; Ordinance 2020-01-03 adopted 1/21/20)", summary:"Establishes city-level care and treatment guidelines for pet animals, expressly stated not to contravene the state animal cruelty provisions in the Texas Penal Code.", street:["This section is guidelines, not a substitute for a state animal-cruelty charge — for actual cruelty, torture, or abandonment, charge under the Penal Code cruelty-to-animals provisions, not this section alone."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 14-20", name:"Animal Traps", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 14-22 general penalty (up to $2,000)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 14-20. Animal traps.\n(a)    Only humane live animal traps may be used for capturing animals roaming unrestrained in the City of Frisco. The use of steel jaw traps to apprehend animals is illegal. As an exception to this section, government agencies and entities shall be permitted to use such traps and equipment as necessary and permitted by state law or regulation, as they currently exist or may be amended.\n(b)    No person shall remove, alter, damage or otherwise tamper with a trap or equipment set out by animal services or the city's agent(s).\n(c)    Animal services traps placed at a site at the request of a property owner or resident are the responsibility of the property owner or resident. The property owner or resident shall check all such traps at least once each day. The property owner or resident shall contact animal services within 24 hours after the property owner or resident becomes aware that an animal has been captured. The property owner or resident shall be responsible for caring for any captured animal until the animal is removed by animal services. In the event that a trap placed by animal services is damaged or lost, the property owner or resident shall reimburse the city for the cost of the trap and shall pay any other costs incurred as a result of the damaged or lost trap. (Ordinance 08-01-06, sec. 20, adopted 1/15/08; Ordinance 15-10-76, sec. 2, adopted 10/6/15; Ordinance 2020-01-03 adopted 1/21/20)", summary:"Only humane live animal traps may be used to capture animals roaming unrestrained in the city; steel jaw traps are illegal, with a limited exception.", street:["Steel jaw traps are flatly illegal for capturing loose animals — a common complaint-generating violation, verify the trap type before charging."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 14-21", name:"Enforcement (Animals)", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Procedural authority — not an offense", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 14-21. Enforcement.\n(a)    Enforcement of this chapter shall be the responsibility of animal services and/or other authorized city personnel and/or its authorized agents.\n(b)    Animal services officers, peace officers, code enforcement officers, health inspectors, the local rabies control authority (LRCA), the local health authority (LHA), and/or other authorized city personnel or the city's authorized agents shall have the authority to issue citations for any violation of this chapter or remedy violations by limitations set forth by state or federal law.\n(c)    If the person being cited is not present, animal services or other city-authorized personnel or the city's authorized agents may send a citation to the alleged offender. Such notice may be given in any one of the following ways:\n(1)   Sent via registered or certified mail addressed to the owner at the owner's address; or\n(2)   By hand delivery to the owner at the owner's address. If the City of Frisco or its authorized agents mails a citation to the owner and the United States Postal Service returns the notice as \"refused\", \"unclaimed\", or if the address that was used for sending the citation is returned as \"not deliverable as addressed\" (or an equivalent marking), the validity of the citation mailed to the owner is not affected, and the citation is considered as delivered.\n(d)    Any person who violates a provision of this chapter or fails to perform an act required of him/her by this chapter commits an offense.\n(e)    A culpable mental state is not required for the commission of an offense under this chapter, unless the provision defining the conduct expressly requires a culpable mental state.\n(f)    It shall be unlawful for any person to prevent, interfere with, obstruct, or give false information to animal services or any city-authorized person or city-authorized agent who is in the lawful discharge of his/her duties under this chapter or other local, state or federal law.\n(g)    Animal services officers, peace officers, the local rabies control authority (LRCA), local health authorities, or other city-authorized personnel and/or city's authorized agents are given the right to trespass onto any private property in the city for the purpose of determining whether or not any provision of this chapter, state statutes or the TexasPenal Code relating to animals have been violated and to impound any animal kept or harbored in violation of any terms of this chapter, state statutes or the Texas Penal Code relating to animals.\n(h)    It shall be unlawful for any person being issued a citation for a violation of this section, a violation of state statutes or the Texas Penal Code relating to animals to be filed in municipal court or any civil proceeding to intentionally or knowingly fail to give the animal services officer their true name and address or to intentionally or knowingly fail to appear in accordance with the terms of a citation issued by the animal services officer or other city-authorized person. For the purpose of this section, a person shall be in violation immediately upon his/her failure to provide the requisite identification information upon request for such information by an animal services officer or other city-authorized person.\n(i)    In addition to imposing a monetary penalty against a person convicted of an offense under this section a court may do one or more of the following:\n(1)   Require the person, at the person's expense, to attend a responsible pet ownership program approved by animal services.\n(2)   Order the impoundment of any animal owned by a person, forfeit the person's ownership of the animal and award the animal to the City of Frisco.\n(3)   Suspend the person's right to own an animal in the city for a period of time specified by the court.\n(4)   Require the person to have any animal owned by the person spayed or neutered within a time period specified by the court.\n(5)   Revoke any permit issued to the person under any section of this chapter.\n(6)   Impose any other condition(s) or restriction(s) that would reasonably abate the violation(s) for which the person was convicted.\n(7)   Take any and all other action(s) authorized by law.\n(j)    It shall be unlawful for any person to claim or disclaim ownership of an animal that he/she knows is false.\n(k)    It shall be unlawful for any person to report a violation of this chapter or other local, state or federal law that he/she knows is false.\n(l)  It shall be unlawful for any person to knowingly make, convey or cause to be imparted or conveyed false statements in an application submitted under this chapter, or to furnish, present or exhibit any fictitious or false documentation submitted under this chapter. (Ordinance 08-01-06, sec. 21, adopted 1/15/08; Ordinance 15-10-76, sec. 2, adopted 10/6/15; Ordinance 2020-01-03 adopted 1/21/20)", summary:"Enforcement of the Animals chapter is the responsibility of animal services and other authorized city personnel; animal services officers and peace officers share enforcement authority under this section.", street:["Confirms peace officers share direct enforcement authority under this chapter alongside animal services — you don't need an animal services officer present to act."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 14-22", name:"Penalty (Animals — General)", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor, fine up to $2,000", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 14-22. Penalty. Any owner, custodian, person, firm, corporation, or business entity violating this chapter shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction thereof shall be fined a sum not exceeding $2,000.00. Each continuing day's violation under this chapter shall constitute a separate offense. The Texas Penal Code provisions imposed under this chapter shall not preclude Frisco from filing suit to enjoin the violation. Frisco retains all legal rights and remedies available to it pursuant to local, state and federal law. (Ordinance 08-01-06, sec. 22, adopted 1/15/08)", summary:"The Animals chapter's catch-all penalty: any owner, custodian, person, firm, corporation, or business entity violating the chapter is guilty of a misdemeanor, fined up to $2,000 unless another section states its own penalty.", street:["Default to this $2,000 cap for any Animals-chapter violation that doesn't state its own penalty — notably higher than the Alarm Systems chapter's $500 cap."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 22-58 – 22-59", name:"Peddlers & Solicitors — Purpose, Scope & Key Definitions", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["solicitation"], kw:"solicit solicitation peddler handbill charitable donation panhandle door to door canvass", level:"Definitions / scope — reference; not an offense. Governs Article III (Peddlers & Solicitors).", lvlClass:"p", text:"Note: In the source PDF's two-column export, several Article III blocks were displaced across headings (the § 22-58 exclusions list and the \"commercial handbill\" / \"home solicitation transaction\" definition bodies were swapped). They are reassembled here by heading. Only the enforcement-relevant terms are reproduced; § 22-59 defines additional administrative terms not shown here.\n\n§ 22-58. Purpose. This article regulates the time, place and manner for the solicitation of funds and the distribution of handbills. The provisions of this article, however, shall not apply to:\n(1) The regular delivery of newspapers, magazines, or other items which have been subscribed to by the persons receiving them or by occupants of the premises to which they are delivered;\n(2) The interruption of service notices by utility companies;\n(3) The distribution of mail by the United States government;\n(4) The service of any lien foreclosure; or\n(5) Governmental notices of any character distributed by the City of Frisco or any other governmental entity.\n\n§ 22-59. Definitions (key terms).\nCharitable purpose means philanthropic, religious or other nonprofit objectives, including the benefit of poor, needy, sick, refugee or handicapped persons; the benefit of any church or religious society, sect, group or order; the benefit of a patriotic or veterans' association or organization; the benefit of any fraternal, social or civil organization, or the benefit of any educational institution. \"Charitable purpose\" shall not be construed to include the direct benefit of the individual making the solicitation. \"Charitable purpose\" shall not be construed to include the benefit of any political group or political organization which is subject to financial disclosure under state or federal law.\nHandbill, commercial means and includes any printed or written matter, any sample or devise, dodger, circular, leaflet, pamphlet, paper, booklet, or any other printed or otherwise reproduced original copies of any matter or literature, which: (a) Advertises for sale any merchandise, product, commodity, service, or thing; (b) Directs attention to any business, mercantile, commercial establishment, or other activity for the purpose of either directly or indirectly promoting the interest thereof; (c) Directs attention or advertises any meeting, theatrical performance, exhibition, group, fundraiser, or other event whether the purpose of directing attention and advertising is for private gain or for raising funds for a charitable purpose; or (d) Contains information that is of a noncommercial nature, but remains predominantly and essentially an advertisement, and is distributed or circulated for advertisement purposes, for private gain, or for raising funds for a charitable purpose.\nHandbill, noncommercial means and includes any printed or written matter... pertaining to any speech not included in the definition of commercial handbill. Noncommercial handbills include, but are not limited to, handbills containing exclusively political and religious speech.\nHome solicitation transaction means: (a) A consumer transaction for the purchase of goods, services, or realty, payable in installments or in cash, in which the merchant engages in a personal solicitation of the sale to the consumer at a residence in person and the consumer's agreement or offer to purchase is given at the residence to the merchant; or (b) Any request for funds made by a person soliciting to the occupant of a residence at a place of residence and the solicitor is unknown to the occupant or owner of the residence at which the request for funds is made. [Excludes preexisting charge-account sales, sales from prior business-location negotiations, consumer-initiated appointments, and certain realty sales.]\nJob placement activities means any request, offer, enticement, or action which announces the availability for or of employment or seeks to secure employment. As defined herein, \"job placement activities\" shall be deemed complete when made whether or not an actual employment relationship is created.\nSolicit funds or solicitation of funds or solicitation shall mean any home solicitation transaction; any request for the donation of money, property, or anything of value, or the pledge of a future donation of money, property, or anything of value; or the selling, or offering for sale, or the purchasing, or offering to purchase, of any property, real or personal, tangible or intangible... including, but not limited to, goods, books, pamphlets, tickets, publications or subscriptions to publications, or taking or attempting to take orders for the future delivery of goods, merchandise, wares, services, or personal property. A solicitation of funds is complete when the solicitation is communicated to any individual then located within the corporate limit of the city. Expressly excluded from the meaning of \"solicit funds\" or \"solicitation of funds\" or \"solicitation\" is any offers of membership in any organization. (Ordinance 08-07-67, secs. 3, 4, adopted 7/15/08)", summary:"Article III regulates the time, place, and manner of soliciting funds and distributing handbills in Frisco. It does not reach subscribed newspaper/magazine delivery, utility service-interruption notices, U.S. mail, lien-foreclosure service, or governmental notices. Key definitions: \"solicitation/solicit funds\" (broadly, any request for a donation or any sale/offer/purchase of property — complete once communicated to anyone inside the city, but excluding mere offers of organizational membership); \"charitable purpose\" (nonprofit/religious/veterans/fraternal/educational benefit, but not the solicitor's own direct benefit and not a political group subject to financial disclosure); commercial vs. noncommercial handbills (noncommercial expressly includes purely political and religious speech); \"home solicitation transaction\"; and \"job placement activities.\"", street:["\"Solicitation\" is defined very broadly and is complete the moment it's communicated to anyone inside the city — but a mere offer of membership in an organization is expressly excluded.","The commercial/noncommercial handbill line matters for the permit rules: noncommercial handbills (which expressly include purely political and religious speech) don't require a permit, so distinguish the message type before treating handbilling as a permit violation.","\"Charitable purpose\" cuts out two things people assume it covers: the solicitor's own personal benefit, and political organizations subject to campaign-finance disclosure.","Confirm the activity isn't one of the five carve-outs in § 22-58 (subscribed delivery, utility notices, U.S. mail, lien-foreclosure service, government notices) before treating it as regulated solicitation."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 22-71", name:"Solicitation / Commercial-Handbill Permit Required; When No Permit Is Needed", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["solicitation"], kw:"solicitor permit license peddler no permit charitable canvassing door to door", level:"Permit required to solicit funds or distribute commercial handbills — penalty not stated in Article III; defaults to the § 1-12 general penalty (up to $500).", lvlClass:"m", text:"Note: In the source export the \"permit required / no permit required\" blocks below appeared under the § 22-72 heading; they are the substance of § 22-71 (Permits required) and are filed here accordingly. The § 22-72 application-detail requirements are administrative and are summarized in the tips rather than reproduced.\n\n§ 22-71. Permits required for solicitation and commercial handbill distribution.\n(a) Except as otherwise provided, a permit is required for an individual to personally, or through an agent or employee:\n(1) Solicit funds; or\n(2) Distribute any commercial handbill in or upon another's property.\n(b) A permit is not required for:\n(1) The distribution of noncommercial handbills;\n(2) The solicitation of funds for charitable purposes by any organization or association from its members;\n(3) The solicitation of funds for charitable purposes by a person when such solicitation occurs on premises owned or controlled by the person soliciting funds or with the permission of the person who owns or controls the premises, when previously invited to the premises for the solicitation;\n(4) The solicitation or distribution of commercial or noncommercial handbills on a public sidewalk designed for pedestrian use; or\n(5) The issuance of any announcement or advertisement that charitable solicitation will occur or which announces or advertises an event at which unannounced charitable solicitation will occur. (Ordinance 08-07-67, sec. 5, adopted 7/15/08)", summary:"A permit is required to solicit funds or to distribute commercial handbills on another's property — but not for distributing noncommercial handbills, charitable solicitation of an organization's own members, charitable solicitation on the solicitor's own or permission-granted premises when previously invited, solicitation or handbill distribution on a public pedestrian sidewalk, or announcements that charitable solicitation will occur. Solicitation permits are administered by the Frisco Police Department (application, issuance, and revocation), run for the length requested up to six months, and are $50.", street:["The permit hook is narrow: it applies to soliciting funds and to commercial handbills. Noncommercial handbills — including purely political and religious speech — and distribution on a public pedestrian sidewalk are expressly exempt, which is the constitutional pressure valve. Don't treat those as no-permit violations.","Frisco PD is the issuing authority. Under § 22-74, PD may deny a permit if the applicant has a felony conviction, gave false information, has an outstanding arrest warrant, is subject to an emergency protective order, or is a registered sex offender — all worth checking when you contact a solicitor.","Under § 22-75, a first offense draws up to a 30-day permit suspension; a second within 12 months means revocation and a 12-month bar. A felony arrest suspends the permit until disposition.","No penalty is stated in Article III itself, so a no-permit solicitation violation routes to the § 1-12 general penalty (up to $500, each day a separate offense)."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 22-91", name:"Solicitor Must Carry & Produce Permit + ID on Request", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["solicitation"], kw:"solicitor permit identification produce show ID demand check", level:"Duty to carry and produce on request — penalty not stated in Article III; defaults to § 1-12 (up to $500).", lvlClass:"m", text:"Note: In the source export the (1)–(3) list below appeared under the § 22-92 heading; it is the body of § 22-91 and is filed here.\n\n§ 22-91. Solicitor's and handbill distributor's identification. Each solicitor and handbill distributor shall carry with him/her and produce upon the request of any citizen, city employee, or city official, the following information and identification:\n(1) The permit issued by the City of Frisco pursuant to this article;\n(2) A copy of the valid state sales tax certificate, if applicable; and\n(3) A valid driver's license or other valid, official photo identification. (Ordinance 08-07-67, sec. 11, adopted 7/15/08)", summary:"Every solicitor and handbill distributor must carry — and produce on the request of any citizen, city employee, or city official — their Frisco solicitation permit, a copy of any applicable valid state sales-tax certificate, and a valid driver's license or other official photo ID.", street:["This is your on-scene demand hook: a solicitor or handbill distributor must produce the city permit and photo ID on request — not just to an officer, but to any citizen or city official.","Failure to produce the permit and ID is itself a violation of this section, separate from whether the underlying solicitation was permitted.","Read together with § 22-71's exemptions: someone distributing only noncommercial handbills or working a public pedestrian sidewalk may not need a permit in the first place, so confirm the activity is permit-required before treating a missing permit as the violation."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 22-92", name:"Solicitation & Distribution — Prohibited Acts and Residential Hours", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["solicitation"], kw:"solicit handbill hours time residence door knock supervisor litter flyer", level:"Offense (per prohibited act) — penalty not stated in Article III; defaults to § 1-12 (up to $500).", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 22-92. Solicitation and distribution.\n(a) Except as otherwise prohibited, the distribution of any handbill, including noncommercial and commercial handbills may only be distributed by:\n(1) Handing the noncommercial handbill or commercial handbill directly to the owner, occupant, or any other person then present in or upon such premises; or\n(2) Depositing the noncommercial handbill or commercial handbill in a secure manner to prevent such handbill from being blown or drifting about the premises, except that mailboxes may not be used when prohibited by federal postal laws or regulations.\n(b) An individual, directly or through an agent or employee, may not:\n(1) Throw, cast or scatter any commercial handbill or noncommercial handbill, or leave any commercial handbill or noncommercial handbill unattended that is not securely affixed to the place of deposit.\n(2) Solicit funds or distribute commercial or noncommercial handbills at a place of residence during the following hours unless invited to do so by the occupant or owner of the residence:\nMonday-Friday: Before 9:00 a.m. and after the earlier of dusk or 9:00 p.m.\nSaturday and Sunday: Before 10:00 a.m. and after the earlier of dusk or 9:00 p.m.\nFor purposes of this section, dusk means thirty (30) minutes after sunset.\n(3) Solicit funds or distribute commercial handbills after the revocation or expiration of any permit issued or during the suspension of any permit issued, as hereinafter provided.\n(4) Solicit funds or distribute commercial handbills for a purpose other than what was represented in the application upon which the permit was issued.\n(5) Represent that the issuance of a permit by the city constitutes an endorsement or approval of the solicitation or distribution by the city or its officers or employees.\n(6) Distribute any commercial handbill or noncommercial handbill in or upon any premises which are temporarily or continuously uninhabited or vacant.\n(7) Distribute any commercial handbill or noncommercial handbill upon any premises if requested not to do so by the owner, occupant, or any other person then present in or upon such premises, or if there is placed on such premises in a conspicuous place upon or near the main entrance to the residence or premises, a card as provided in section 22-94 of this Code.\n(8) Distribute any commercial or noncommercial handbill in any place, under any circumstances, which does not have printed on the cover, front or back thereof, the name, address and telephone number of the handbill sponsor who caused the same to be distributed; provided, however, that in the case of a fictitious person or club, in addition to such fictitious name, the true names and addresses of the owners, managers, or agents for the fictitious person or club sponsoring such commercial handbill shall also appear thereon.\n(9) Employ, hire, request, direct or cause, directly or indirectly, another person who does not have a permit to distribute commercial handbills or solicit funds within the city.\n(10) Distribute commercial handbills or solicit funds under the direction of another and not have a supervisor who can arrive at the location where the person is distributing the handbills or soliciting within ten minutes of being requested to appear, by the police or otherwise.\n(11) Direct someone else to distribute commercial handbills or solicit funds and not provide a supervisor who can arrive at the location where the person is distributing the handbills or soliciting within ten minutes of being requested to appear, by the police or otherwise.\n(12) Allow a person to use a permit issued in another person's name or to use a permit issued in another person's name. (Ordinance 08-07-67, sec. 12, adopted 7/15/08; Ordinance 14-05-25, sec. 4, adopted 5/6/14)", summary:"Sets the manner rules and prohibited acts for soliciting and handbill distribution. Handbills may only be handed directly to a person present or deposited securely (no mailboxes where federal law bars it). Prohibited acts include: scattering or leaving handbills unsecured; soliciting or distributing at a residence outside the allowed hours (M–F before 9 a.m./after the earlier of dusk or 9 p.m.; Sa–Su before 10 a.m./after the earlier of dusk or 9 p.m.; dusk = 30 minutes after sunset) unless invited; working after a permit's revocation/expiration or during suspension; soliciting for a purpose other than the permit represented; claiming a city endorsement; distributing on vacant premises; distributing where the owner/occupant said no or a § 22-94 card is posted; distributing handbills lacking the sponsor's name/address/phone; using unpermitted helpers; lacking a supervisor able to reach the scene within 10 minutes; or using someone else's permit.", street:["The residential time windows are the most citable piece: no soliciting/handbilling at a residence before 9 a.m. or after dusk-or-9 p.m. (M–F), or before 10 a.m. (weekends), unless the occupant invited them. \"Dusk\" is fixed at 30 minutes after sunset.","The 10-minute supervisor rule (b)(10)–(11) is a practical field tool: a crew soliciting under someone's direction must be able to get a supervisor to your location within 10 minutes of your request — inability to do so is itself a violation.","Handbills must carry the sponsor's name, address, and phone; scattered, littered, or vacant-premises distribution and ignoring a posted no-solicitation card are each independently chargeable.","Each prohibited act is its own violation; penalty routes to the § 1-12 general penalty (up to $500)."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 22-93", name:"Use of Public Right-of-Way — Vehicle & Median Solicitation", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["solicitation"], kw:"panhandle panhandling median solicit right of way roadway traffic island vehicle window beg begging day labor street corner", level:"Offense — penalty not stated in Article III; defaults to the § 1-12 general penalty (up to $500).", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 22-93. Use of public right-of-way.\n(a) Solicitation of persons in vehicles. Except as permitted by state law, it shall be unlawful for any person to peddle, sell, offer, or exhibit for sale any merchandise or service, whether for profit, for a charitable purpose or otherwise to any person in a motor vehicle, truck, motorcycle or other vehicle (collectively hereinafter \"Vehicle\") while the Vehicle is located within a public right-of-way.\n(b) Solicitation in public right-of-way. Except as permitted by state law, it shall be unlawful for any person to solicit funds, donations, contributions, employment, business or a ride, whether for profit, for a charitable purpose or otherwise, upon any public street, street right-of-way, median, traffic island, parkway, or other public right-of-way, excluding sidewalks designed for pedestrian use, within the City of Frisco.\n(c) Acknowledgement of state law. Frisco acknowledges that the state legislature has adopted V.T.C.A., Transportation Code sec. 552.0071, which became effective on May 3, 2005.\n(d) Selling or attempting to sell on sidewalk/right-of-way. It shall be unlawful for any person to peddle, sell, offer, or exhibit for sale any merchandise or service, whether for profit, for a charitable purpose or otherwise on a public sidewalk or road without previous permission granted by the city manager, or his designee. (Ordinance 08-07-67, sec. 13, adopted 7/15/08)", summary:"Makes it unlawful to (a) peddle/sell/offer merchandise or a service to an occupant of a vehicle while the vehicle is in a public right-of-way; (b) solicit funds, donations, contributions, employment, business, or a ride on any public street, ROW, median, traffic island, parkway, or other public right-of-way — sidewalks designed for pedestrian use excepted; and (d) peddle or sell on a public sidewalk or road without prior permission from the city manager. Subsection (c) acknowledges the parallel state statute, Transportation Code § 552.0071.", street:["This is the median / roadway solicitation section. The (b) offense is broad — it reaches soliciting funds, donations, employment, business, or even a ride from a street, median, traffic island, parkway, or ROW — but pedestrian sidewalks are carved out, so location matters.","(a) covers the person working car windows in traffic; (b) covers the person soliciting from the median or roadway itself. Charge the subsection that matches where they were.","Ordinances like this are heavily litigated on First Amendment grounds. Enforce it content-neutrally on the conduct — being in the roadway/median soliciting — not on the message or who's asking (a charity, a day-laborer, and a panhandler are treated the same under the text).","Subsection (c) points to Transportation Code § 552.0071 (pedestrian soliciting a ride/business/contribution from a roadway occupant) — the state offense that often fits the same facts; check it alongside the ordinance.","No penalty is stated in Article III, so it routes to the § 1-12 general penalty (up to $500)."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 22-94", name:"\"No Solicitation / No Handbills\" Card; Removing a Card Prohibited", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["solicitation"], kw:"no solicitation sign card no handbills doorbell knock privacy remove deface", level:"Offense — penalty not stated in Article III; defaults to § 1-12 (up to $500).", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 22-94. Exhibiting card prohibiting solicitation and handbills of any type.\n(a) A person desiring that no merchant or other person engage in solicitation, a home solicitation transaction, or distribution of commercial handbills, noncommercial handbills at his/her premises shall exhibit, in a conspicuous place upon or near the main entrance to the premises (including but not limited to entrances to: an apartment unit, building or complex; a single- or multi-family residential structure; private sidewalks; a development with private streets; or areas maintained by a property owner's association) a weatherproof card, not less than three inches by four inches in size bearing the words, \"no advertisements\", \"no solicitation\", or \"no handbills\", to indicate that the occupants of such premises do not desire to be molested or to have their right of privacy disturbed, or to have a handbill of any type left upon the premises. The letters on such cards shall be not less than two-thirds (2/3) of an inch in height.\n(b) Every person upon going onto any premises shall first examine the premises to determine if any notice prohibiting soliciting or distribution of commercial handbill or noncommercial handbill distribution is exhibited upon or near the main entrance to the premises. If notice prohibiting solicitation or commercial handbill or noncommercial handbill distribution is exhibited, the person shall immediately depart from the premises without distributing, placing, or depositing any type of handbill or disturbing the occupant, unless the visit is the result of a request made by the occupant.\n(c) No person shall go upon any premises and ring the doorbell, or rap or knock upon the door or create any sound in a manner calculated to attract the attention of the occupant of the premises, for the purpose of securing an audience with the occupant and engaging in or attempting to engage in a solicitation or distribution transaction, if a card, as described in this section, is exhibited in compliance with this section, unless the visit is the result of a request made by the occupant.\n(d) No person, other than the owner or occupant of the premises, shall remove, deface, or render illegible, a card placed by the occupant pursuant to this section.\n(e) Any merchant or person who has gained entrance to a premises, or audience with the occupant, whether invited or not, shall immediately depart from the premises without disturbing the occupant further when requested to leave by the occupant. (Ordinance 08-07-67, sec. 14, adopted 7/15/08)", summary:"Lets an occupant post a conspicuous, weatherproof \"no advertisements,\" \"no solicitation,\" or \"no handbills\" card (at least 3\\\" x 4\\\", 2/3-inch letters) near the main entrance. Where such a card is posted, a solicitor/distributor must examine for it, must not ring, knock, or otherwise try to get the occupant's attention to solicit, and must immediately depart without leaving any handbill — unless the occupant invited the visit. Anyone who has gained entry or an audience must leave when asked. It is unlawful for anyone other than the owner/occupant to remove, deface, or render illegible a posted card.", street:["A posted \"no solicitation / no handbills\" card that meets the size and placement rules makes further soliciting, knocking, or ringing at that premises a violation — the card does the work, no prior warning from the occupant is needed.","Subsection (d) is its own offense: removing, defacing, or obscuring someone else's posted card. Useful when a solicitor pulls down the sign to claim they never saw it.","Refusing to leave after the occupant asks (subsection (e)) is independently chargeable and pairs naturally with a state criminal-trespass analysis.","Penalty routes to the § 1-12 general penalty (up to $500)."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 22-95", name:"Job Placement Activities in Unauthorized Locations", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["solicitation"], kw:"day labor labor solicitation job placement hiring corner sign posted english spanish", level:"Offense — penalty not stated in Article III; defaults to § 1-12 (up to $500).", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 22-95. Prohibition of job placement activities in unauthorized locations.\n(a) No person shall engage in or attempt to engage in job placement activities in an unauthorized location. This section shall not apply to job placement activities concerning employment or business for the owner or lawful tenants of the subject premises.\n(b) For purposes of this section, an unauthorized location is any premises or place where the occupant or owner has a notice posted, in both English and Spanish in a conspicuous place at each street entrance and exit to such location not less than 18 by 24 inches in size with lettering not less than one inch in height and not to exceed, in total area, six square feet, containing a message in substantially the following form: \"It is unlawful to engage in job placement activities on these premises.\"\n(c) This section shall override other ordinances, excluding safety, structural integrity and traffic visibility requirements, regulating the placement of signage, temporary or permanent, for the purpose of solicitation or job placement in and throughout the City of Frisco. (Ordinance 08-07-67, sec. 15, adopted 7/15/08)", summary:"Makes it unlawful to engage in — or attempt to engage in — job placement activities (announcing available employment or seeking to secure employment, per § 22-59) at an \"unauthorized location.\" A location becomes unauthorized when the owner/occupant posts the prescribed bilingual (English and Spanish) notice at each street entrance/exit — at least 18\\\" x 24\\\", 1-inch lettering, up to six square feet — stating \"It is unlawful to engage in job placement activities on these premises.\" It does not apply to job placement for the owner or lawful tenants of the premises themselves.", street:["This is the day-labor / hiring-site tool: it's an offense only where the owner has posted the specific bilingual notice at the entrances — no posted sign, no § 22-95 violation.","\"Job placement activities\" is defined broadly in § 22-59 and is complete when made, whether or not anyone actually gets hired.","It doesn't reach hiring for the property's own owner or lawful tenants — confirm the activity is third-party job placement, not the business staffing itself.","Penalty routes to the § 1-12 general penalty (up to $500)."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 22-111", name:"Ticket Scalping Prohibited", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["solicitation"], kw:"ticket scalping resale resell scalper event stadium the star concert above face value", level:"Offense — penalty not stated in this section; defaults to the § 1-12 general penalty (up to $500).", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 22-111. Ticket scalping prohibited.\n(a) Definitions. For the purposes of this section, the following words and phrases shall have the following meanings:\nCity property means any property that is owned or used by the City of Frisco, including but not limited to, parks, grounds or buildings.\nCity right-of-way means any public alley, sidewalk, street, street right-of-way, median, traffic island, parkway, or other public right-of-way within the City of Frisco.\nEvent means an event or happening of public entertainment or amusement.\nEvent sponsor means an owner, lessee, operator, promoter or manager of an event or the site of an event.\nResell means to sell a ticket for an event after it has been acquired from the event sponsor or from an individual, entity or association authorized to sell the ticket by the event sponsor.\n(b) Prohibited activities.\n(1) Except as otherwise provided, it shall be unlawful for any person to resell or offer to resell a ticket to an event in any city right-of-way.\n(2) Except as otherwise provided, it shall be unlawful for any person to resell or offer to resell a ticket to an event for a price in excess of the price authorized to be offered to the general public by the event sponsor on:\na. Any city property;\nb. On any property owned, leased or managed by the event sponsor;\nc. The area within the boundaries of State Highway 121, Preston Road (State Highway 289), Warren Parkway and Legacy Drive; or\nd. The area within the boundaries of Lebanon Road, Preston Road (State Highway 289), Eldorado Parkway and Legacy Drive.\n(3) A person may resell or offer to resell a ticket to an event if that person does so on private property and so long as that private property is not owned or leased by the event sponsor. (Ordinance 08-07-67, sec. 16, adopted 7/15/08)", summary:"Two distinct prohibitions: (1) reselling or offering to resell an event ticket in any city right-of-way is unlawful outright, regardless of price; and (2) reselling above the event sponsor's authorized public price (scalping) is unlawful on city property, on the event sponsor's own property, and within two defined geographic zones (bounded by SH 121 / Preston Rd / Warren Pkwy / Legacy Dr, and by Lebanon Rd / Preston Rd / Eldorado Pkwy / Legacy Dr — the areas around The Star and the Stonebriar/stadium district). Reselling on private property not owned or leased by the event sponsor is allowed.", street:["Two separate offenses: resale in any city ROW is barred at any price, while resale above face value is barred on city/sponsor property and inside the two mapped venue zones. Pin down which applies before citing.","The geographic zones (subsection (b)(2)c–d) are the venue districts — confirm the location falls inside the described street boundaries.","Resale on private property not owned/leased by the event sponsor is expressly lawful — so the seller's location is the whole case.","No penalty is stated in the section; it routes to the § 1-12 general penalty (up to $500)."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 22-236 – 22-238", name:"Display of Sexually Explicit Materials to Minors", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["publicconduct"], kw:"sexually explicit material display minor store magazine cover harmful obscene adult", level:"Misdemeanor, fine up to $500; each day a separate offense (§ 22-238).", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 22-236. Definitions.\nDisplay means to locate an item in such a manner that, without obtaining assistance from an employee of the business establishment: (1) It is available to the general public for handling and inspection; or (2) The cover or outside packaging on the item is visible to members of the general public.\nMinor means a person younger than 18 years of age.\nPerson means an individual, corporation, partnership, limited partnership, limited liability company or any other business entity.\nPossession means actual care, custody, control or management.\nSexually explicit materials means books, pamphlets, newspapers, magazines, films or videocassettes, the cover of which depict, in a manner calculated to arouse sexual lust or passion for commercial gain or to exploit sexual lust or perversion for commercial gain, any of the following: (1) Human sexual intercourse, masturbation or sodomy; (2) Fondling or other erotic touching of human genitals, pubic region, buttocks or female breasts; (3) Less than completely and opaquely covered human genitals, buttocks or that portion of the female breast below the top of the areola; or (4) Human male genitals in a discernibly turgid state, whether covered or uncovered. (Ordinance 97-10-19, sec. 2, adopted 10/21/97)\n\n§ 22-237. Display of sexually explicit materials to minors. A person commits an offense if, in his establishment open to persons under the age of 18 years, he displays sexually explicit materials. (Ordinance 97-10-19, sec. 3, adopted 10/21/97)\n\n§ 22-238. Violation; penalty. Any person, firm or corporation who violates any provisions of this article shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction therefor, shall be fined any sum not exceeding $500.00, and each and every day that such violation continues shall be considered a separate offense; provided, however, that such penal provision shall not preclude a suit to enjoin such violation. (Ordinance 97-10-19, sec. 4, adopted 10/21/97)", summary:"Makes it a misdemeanor for a person (including a business entity) to display sexually explicit materials in an establishment that is open to persons under 18. \"Display\" means placing an item so that, without staff assistance, the public can handle/inspect it or see its cover/packaging. \"Sexually explicit materials\" is defined by cover depictions calculated to arouse or exploit sexual lust for commercial gain, across four enumerated categories. Punishable by a fine up to $500, with each day a separate offense.", street:["The offense is the visible display in a store open to under-18s — not sale to a minor. The test is whether an unassisted member of the public (including a minor) can handle the item or see its cover/packaging.","\"Sexually explicit materials\" is defined by the four cover-content categories in § 22-236 — apply that definition rather than a general obscenity judgment.","This is a city display offense distinct from the Texas Penal Code's \"harmful material to a minor\" (§ 43.24) and obscenity provisions — check state law separately if the conduct goes beyond display.","Each day of continued display is a separate offense."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 54-20", name:"Smoking and Smokeless Tobacco Prohibited", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["smoking"], level:"Graded per § 54-26 ($100 / $200 / $500 escalating fines)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 54-20. Smoking and smokeless tobacco prohibited.\n(a)    Smoking prohibited in certain public areas.\n(1)   A person commits an offense in violation of this article if he smokes or possesses a burning tobacco, tobacco substitute , weed, other plant product, electronic cigarette or e-cigarette or liquid nicotine in any of the following indoor and/or enclosed areas:\na.    A public or private preschool, primary or secondary school;\nb.    Elevators, museums, libraries, galleries, public transportation facilities open to the public and service lines of establishments doing business with the general public;\nc.    Hearing rooms, conference rooms, meeting rooms or any public service area of any facility owned, operated or managed by the city in which business is conducted, when the public business requires and/or provides an opportunity for direct participation and/or observation by the general public;\nd.    Any building or indoor or outdoor sports arena which is used for or designated for the purpose of exhibiting any motion picture, stage drama, lecture, musical recital, athletic event or any other event whenever open to the public, including all restrooms and any area commonly referred to as a lobby; however, smoking, which is a part of a stage performance, is permitted;\ne.    Any retail or service establishment serving the general public, including but not limited to, any food products establishment, department store, restaurant, grocery store, private club, bingo parlor, bowling center, drug store, shopping mall, hair styling salons, including service lines;\nf.    All restrooms open for public use;\ng.    All areas in a laundromat open to and available to use by the public;\nh.    Within all areas available to and customarily used by the general public in all businesses and nonprofit entities patronized by the public, including, but not limited to, commercial, financial and professional offices, including banks, hotels and motels; or\ni.    Within 20 linear feet of any entrance of any facility where smoking is prohibited.\n(2)   Notwithstanding any other provision of this section, any owner, operator, manager or other person who controls any establishment or facility described in this section may declare the entire establishment or facility as a nonsmoking establishment.\n(3)   It shall be a defense to prosecution under this section that the public place in which the offense takes place does not have prominently displayed a conspicuous notice that smoking is prohibited and that an offense is punishable by a fine not to exceed $2,000.00.\n(b)    Prohibition of smoking in places of employment.\n(1)   Where smoking is prohibited, it shall be the responsibility of employers to provide a smoke- free workplace for all employees.\n(2)   Each employer having any enclosed place of employment located within the city shall adopt, implement, make known and maintain a written smoking policy, which shall contain the following requirements: \"Smoking shall be prohibited in all enclosed facilities within a place of employment except where expressly permitted under city ordinance. This includes common work areas, auditoriums, classrooms, conference and meeting rooms, private offices, elevators, hallways, medical facilities, cafeterias, employee lounges, stairs, restrooms, vehicles, and all other enclosed facilities.\"\n(3)   The smoking policy shall be communicated to all employees within four (4) weeks of its adoption.\n(4)   All employers shall supply a written copy of the smoking policy upon request to any existing or prospective employee.\n(c)    Prohibited in parks.A person commits an offense in violation of this article if, in any park, he smokes or smokeless tobacco is contained within the person's mouth.\n(d)    Prohibited on portions of outdoor patios.A person commits an offense in violation of this article if he smokes or possesses a burning tobacco, tobacco substitute, weed, other plant product, electronic cigarette or e-cigarette or liquid nicotine in an outdoor patio area of a retail or service establishment that is defined fully or partially by a barrier or that provides seating for patrons where any portion of the outdoor patio is located fewer than 10 linear feet from public property, an outdoor patio of another establishment or an operable window into a building. (Ordinance 00-12-12, sec. 4, adopted 12/5/00; Ordinance 06-11-118, secs. 3, 8, adopted 11/7/06; Ordinance 14-02-08, sec. 2, adopted 2/18/14; Ordinance 14-08-45, sec. 3, adopted 8/5/14; Ordinance 19-03-14 adopted 3/5/19)", summary:"Prohibits smoking and smokeless tobacco use in designated public areas and enclosed public places/places of employment, subject to the article's posted-sign and compliance requirements.", street:["Confirm the location falls within the article's covered public areas or places of employment before charging.","Fine escalates with repeat violations within a year — check for prior violations under this article."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 54-26", name:"Smoking — Violations and Penalties", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["smoking"], level:"Misdemeanor: $100 (1st), $200 (2nd within 1 yr), $500 (3rd+ within 1 yr)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 54-26. Violations and penalties.\n(a)    It shall be unlawful for any person who owns, manages, operates or otherwise controls the use of any premises subject to regulation under this chapter to fail to comply with all of its provisions, except for violations noted in paragraph (b) of this section.\n(b)    It shall be unlawful for any person to smoke in any area where smoking is prohibited by the provisions of this article.\n(c)    Any person who violates any provision of this article shall be guilty of an offense punishable by:\n(1)   A fine not exceeding $100.00 for the first violation;\n(2)   A fine not exceeding $200.00 for a second violation within a one-year period of the first violation; or\n(3)A fine not exceeding $500.00 for an additional violation within a one-year period of the first violation. (Ordinance 00-12-12, sec. 10, adopted 12/5/00; Ordinance 06-11-118, sec. 7, adopted 11/7/06)", summary:"Separately makes it unlawful for a person who owns, manages, or controls a regulated premises to fail to comply with the article, and for any individual to smoke where prohibited. Fines escalate: up to $100 for a first violation, $200 for a second within one year, $500 for any further violation within that year.", street:["Two different actors can be charged: the person smoking, and separately the business owner/manager who fails to enforce the no-smoking policy on their premises.","Check for a prior violation within the last year before assessing the fine tier — this is the article's own escalating schedule, not the general chapter penalty."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 54-29 to 54-32", name:"Illegal Smoking Material — Sale, Possession, Paraphernalia, and Defenses", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["smoking"], level:"Misdemeanor per general chapter penalty — no fine stated in these sections", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 54-29. Sale, delivery, offer, or gift. It shall be unlawful for any person to sell, offer to sell, deliver to or to give any illegal smoking material to any person. (Ordinance 10-07-33, sec. 3, adopted 7/29/10)\n\n§ 54-30. Use or possession of illegal smoking material. It shall be unlawful for any person to have in their possession or to use illegal smoking materials within the corporate limits of the city. (Ordinance 10-07-33, sec. 3, adopted 7/29/10)\n\n§ 54-31. Use or possession of illegal smoking paraphernalia. It shall be unlawful for any person to have in their possession any illegal smoking paraphernalia with the intent to use it, to ingest, inhale or otherwise consume illegal smoking material. If a person is found in possession of this type of paraphernalia it will be a violation of this article if appropriate forensic testing is done on the paraphernalia and traces of illegal smoking material are present on the device. (Ordinance 10-07-33, sec. 3, adopted 7/29/10)\n\n§ 54-32. Defenses to prosecution.\n(a) It shall be a defense to prosecution for a violation of this article if the use of the illegal smoking material is at the direction or under a prescription issued by a licensed physician or dentist authorized to prescribe controlled substances within the State of Texas.\n(b) It shall be a defense to prosecution under the terms of this article if any person charged with a violation can provide proper and complete historic documentation that the use of such materials is a portion of a religious undertaking or activity of a religious denomination in which they have long standing historic membership supported by documentation from clergy or spiritual leader recognized by the State of Texas. (Ordinance 10-07-33, sec. 3, adopted 7/29/10)", summary:"Three related offenses aimed at synthetic/illegal smoking materials (as defined elsewhere in the article): selling, offering to sell, delivering, or giving illegal smoking material to any person; possessing or using illegal smoking material; and possessing illegal smoking paraphernalia with intent to use it. Defenses to prosecution are set out in § 54-32.", street:["This targets synthetic drugs/'legal high' smoking products marketed to evade the Controlled Substances Act — confirm the material meets the article's 'illegal smoking material' definition before charging.","Sale/delivery, possession/use, and paraphernalia possession are three separate chargeable offenses — they don't require each other.","§ 54-32 gives two defenses to prosecution: (a) the material's use is at the direction of, or under a prescription from, a Texas-licensed physician or dentist authorized to prescribe controlled substances; and (b) documented long-standing religious use supported by recognized clergy. Confirm neither applies before charging."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 54-19", name:"Illegal Smoking Material & Paraphernalia — Definitions", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["smoking"], kw:"K-2 K2 spice synthetic marijuana cannabinoid JWH-018 JWH salvia salvinorin potpourri incense bath salts bong pipe chillum legal high", level:"Definitions — reference; not an offense. Supplies the \"illegal smoking material\" and \"paraphernalia\" definitions that make §§ 54-29–54-31 chargeable.", lvlClass:"p", text:"Note: § 54-19 is a long definitions section supporting all of Article II (Smoking). Reproduced below are only the two offense-defining terms that make §§ 54-29–54-31 (illegal smoking material) chargeable, quoted verbatim and complete. § 54-19 also defines general smoking terms (cigar, cigarette, electronic cigarette/e-cigarette, liquid nicotine, tobacco product, tobacco substitute, smoke/smoking, place of employment, public area, and others) that are not reproduced here; in the source export a few of those general definitions (e.g., \"smokeless tobacco\") were truncated and should be taken from the official eCode source if the full definitions section is ever needed.\n\n§ 54-19. Definitions.\n\nIllegal smoking material. Any substance, however marketed, which can reasonably be converted for smoking purposes whether it is presented as incense, tobacco, herbs, spices or any blend thereof if it includes any of the following chemicals or a comparable chemical:\n(1) Salvia Divinorum or Salvinorin A; all parts of the plant presently classified botanically as Salvia Divinorum, whether growing or not, the seeds thereof, any extract from any part of such plant, and every compound, manufacture, salts, derivative, mixture or preparation of such plant, its seeds or extracts;\n(2) 2-[(1R,3S)-3-hydroxycyclohexyl]-5-(2-methyloctan-2-yl) phenol (also known as CP47,497) and homologues;\n(3) (6aS,10aS)-9-(hydroxymethyl)-6, 6-dimethyl-3-(2-methyloctan-2-yl)-6a, 7,10,10a-tetrahydrobenzo [c] chromen-1-ol (also known as HU-211 or Dexanabinol);\n(4) 1-pentyl-3-(1-naphthoyl) indole (also known as JWH-018);\n(5) 1-butyl-3-(1-naphthoyl) indole (also known as JWH-073); or\n(6) 1-pentyl-3-(4-methoxynaphthoyl) indole (also known as JWH-081).\nProducts containing some or all of the above substances are currently being marketed under the following commercial names: \"K-2,\" \"K-2 Summit,\" \"K-2 Sex,\" \"Genie,\" \"Dascents,\" \"Zohai,\" \"Sage,\" \"Spice,\" \"KO Knock-out 2,\" \"Spice Gold,\" \"Spice Diamond,\" \"Yucatan Fire,\" \"Solar Flare,\" \"Pep Spice,\" \"Fire N' Ice,\" and \"Salvia Divinorum.\" Any product containing any of the chemical compounds set forth above shall be subject to the provisions of this article, regardless of whether they are marketed under alternative names.\n\nIllegal smoking material paraphernalia. Any paraphernalia, equipment or utensil that is used or intended to be used in ingesting or inhaling illegal smoking materials and may include, but is not limited to:\n(1) A metal, wooden, acrylic, glass, stone, plastic, or ceramic pipe with or without a screen, permanent screen, hashish head, or punctured metal bowl;\n(2) A water pipe;\n(3) A carburetion tube or device;\n(4) A smoking or carburetion mask;\n(5) A chamber pipe;\n(6) A carburetor pipe;\n(7) An electric pipe;\n(8) An air-driven pipe;\n(9) A chillum;\n(10) A bong; or\n(11) An ice pipe or chiller.\n(Ordinance 00-12-12, sec. 3, adopted 12/5/00; Ordinance 06-11-118, sec. 2, adopted 11/7/06; Ordinance 10-07-33, sec. 2, adopted 7/29/10; Ordinance 14-02-08, sec. 2, adopted 2/18/14; Ordinance 14-08-45, sec. 2, adopted 8/5/14; Ordinance 19-03-14 adopted 3/5/19; Ordinance 2024-08-35 adopted 8/20/2024)", summary:"Reproduces the two offense-defining terms from § 54-19: \"illegal smoking material\" (any substance marketed for smoking — incense, herbs, \"potpourri\" — that contains Salvia Divinorum/Salvinorin A, CP47,497, HU-211/Dexanabinol, or the JWH-018/073/081 synthetic cannabinoids, or a comparable chemical, regardless of the brand name it is sold under) and \"illegal smoking material paraphernalia\" (pipes, water pipes, bongs, chillums, carburetion tubes/masks, and similar items used to ingest it). These are the definitions that make the §§ 54-29–54-31 sale/possession/paraphernalia offenses enforceable. § 54-19 also defines many general smoking terms not reproduced here.", street:["This is the definition that gives §§ 54-29–54-31 teeth — the material qualifies by its chemistry (a listed synthetic cannabinoid or Salvia/Salvinorin, or a comparable chemical), not by what the package calls it. A product sold as \"incense,\" \"potpourri,\" or under any brand name is still covered if it contains a listed compound.","The named brands (K-2, Spice, etc.) are illustrative, not the test — the ordinance reaches the material \"regardless of whether they are marketed under alternative names.\" Chemical content controls.","Paraphernalia under § 54-31 needs more than the item itself: intent to use it plus forensic testing showing traces of illegal smoking material on the device. This list tells you what counts as paraphernalia; § 54-31 supplies the testing element.","This is a 2010 city ordinance that predates Texas's own scheduling of synthetic cannabinoids in the Health & Safety Code — check current state controlled-substance law, which may now reach the same material as a state offense with a heavier penalty.","Only the illegal-smoking-material and paraphernalia definitions are reproduced here; § 54-19's general smoking definitions (and a couple truncated in the source export, e.g., \"smokeless tobacco\") should be pulled from the official eCode source if the full definitions section is needed."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 54-21", name:"Smoking in Hospitals; Health Care Facilities", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["smoking"], kw:"hospital clinic nursing home doctor dentist convalescent smoking vape e-cigarette", level:"Graded per § 54-26 ($100 / $200 / $500 escalating fines)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 54-21. Hospitals; health care facilities. A person commits an offense in violation of this article if he smokes or possesses a burning tobacco, weed, other plant product, electronic cigarette or e-cigarette or liquid nicotine in any public area of a health care facility or hospital, including, but not limited to, clinics, physical therapy facilities, doctor's offices, nursing and convalescent homes, residential treatment centers/homes and dentists' offices. In bed space areas of health care facilities or hospitals, smoking shall be prohibited unless the smoking of a lawful substance is authorized by a physician as part of a medical directive or procedure. Separate ventilation exhaust may be required by the building official to accommodate such orders. (Ordinance 00-12-12, sec. 5, adopted 12/5/00; Ordinance 14-02-08, sec. 2, adopted 2/18/14; Ordinance 19-03-14 adopted 3/5/19)", summary:"Makes it an offense to smoke or possess burning tobacco, weed, other plant product, an e-cigarette, or liquid nicotine in any public area of a health care facility or hospital — including clinics, physical therapy facilities, doctor's and dentist's offices, and nursing/convalescent/residential treatment homes. In patient bed-space areas smoking is prohibited unless a physician authorizes a lawful substance as part of a medical directive or procedure.", street:["Reaches the full range of health care settings, not just hospitals — clinics, PT facilities, doctor's and dentist's offices, and nursing/convalescent/residential treatment homes are all named.","The only carve-out is a bed-space area where a physician has authorized a lawful substance as part of a medical directive or procedure; otherwise the public-area prohibition is flat.","Penalty tracks § 54-26's escalating schedule ($100 first / $200 second / $500 further, within a one-year period) — same as the general smoking prohibition under § 54-20."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 54-24", name:"Where Smoking Is Not Prohibited (Exceptions)", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["smoking"], level:"Exceptions to the smoking prohibition — reference; functions as a defense to §§ 54-20/54-21.", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 54-24. Where smoking is not prohibited. Notwithstanding any other provision of this article to the contrary, smoking is not prohibited in the following areas:\n(1) Private residences, except when used as a licensed child care, adult day care or health care facility;\n(2) Hotel and motel rooms rented to guests, if permitted by the hotel or motel;\n(3) Retail tobacco stores that have an enclosed smoking room provided that the following requirements are met:\na. Smoking rooms shall have a physical barrier to prevent the escape of visible smoke, vapor or other objectionable nonvisible products of smoking without any action required of adjacent tenant spaces.\nb. Smoking rooms shall have dedicated ventilation systems separate from all other rooms or spaces where smoking is prohibited. Ventilation systems shall consist of exhaust, air purification, filtration, air exchange or a combination of methods to eliminate all visible and nonvisible products of smoking from the indoor environment.\nc. Patrons shall not be required to enter or pass through smoking rooms to access required public sanitary facilities.\nd. No person under 21 years of age shall be allowed entrance into or be required to work in a smoking room.\ne. Entrance doors into a smoking room shall not allow entry into the smoking room directly from the exterior of the building. Entrance doors must allow entry only from a vestibule or an interior portion of a retail tobacco store.\n(4) Retail and service establishments that have an enclosed smoking lounge provided that the following requirements are met:\na. Smoking lounges shall have a physical barrier to prevent the escape of visible smoke, vapor or other objectionable nonvisible products of smoking without any action required of adjacent tenant spaces.\nb. Smoking lounges shall have dedicated ventilation systems separate from all other rooms or spaces where smoking is prohibited. Ventilation systems shall consist of exhaust, air purification, filtration, air exchange or a combination of methods to eliminate all visible and nonvisible products of smoking from the indoor environment.\nc. Patrons shall not be required to enter or pass through smoking lounges to access required public sanitary facilities.\nd. No person under 21 years of age shall be allowed entrance into or be required to work in a smoking lounge.\ne. The smoking lounge area shall be limited to a maximum of 15 percent of the gross floor area of the common or associated retail or service establishment.\nf. Entrance doors into a smoking lounge shall not allow entry into the smoking lounge directly from the exterior of the building. Entrance doors must allow entry only from a vestibule or an interior portion of a retail or service establishment.\n(5) Any area of fraternal organization member space not serving the general public.\n(6) Any area exterior to the building in which the establishment or facility is located, except as otherwise regulated under section 54-20 of this article.\n(7) In retail electronic cigarette stores provided that only the smoking of e-cigarettes may be permitted and further provided that a physical barrier exists to prevent the escape of visible smoke, vapor or other objectionable nonvisible products of smoking without any action required of adjacent tenant spaces. (Ordinance 00-12-12, sec. 8, adopted 12/5/00; Ordinance 06-11-118, sec. 5, adopted 11/7/06; Ordinance 14-02-08, sec. 2, adopted 2/18/14; Ordinance 19-03-14 adopted 3/5/19; Ordinance 2024-08-35 adopted 8/20/2024)", summary:"Lists the areas exempt from the article's smoking prohibition: private residences (unless used as licensed child/adult day care or a health care facility); hotel/motel guest rooms if the property permits; qualifying enclosed smoking rooms in retail tobacco stores and enclosed smoking lounges in retail/service establishments (each conditioned on strict barrier, dedicated-ventilation, 21-and-over, and access requirements — plus a 15%-of-floor-area cap on lounges); fraternal-organization member space not serving the public; exterior areas (except as § 54-20 regulates); and retail e-cigarette stores meeting a physical-barrier requirement.", street:["This is effectively the defense side of the smoking prohibition — if a location is one of these, § 54-20/§ 54-21 doesn't apply. But the smoking-room and lounge exemptions are conditional: the barrier, dedicated-ventilation, 21-and-over, and access requirements must all be met, so a room that merely calls itself a \"smoking lounge\" without meeting them is not exempt.","Private residences lose the exemption when used as a licensed child care, adult day care, or health care facility.","Exterior areas are generally exempt except where § 54-20 reaches them (within 20 feet of an entrance, the park ban, and the outdoor-patio rule) — read this alongside § 54-20 before clearing an outdoor smoking complaint."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 54-132 – 54-137 (Repealed)", name:"Juvenile Curfew — Repealed", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["publicconduct"], kw:"curfew juvenile minor teen nighttime daytime hours truancy repealed no longer", level:"REPEALED — no longer an enforceable offense. Article V (juvenile curfew) was repealed in its entirety effective 8/15/2023.", lvlClass:"p", text:"Article V — (Reserved). Former Article V, §§ 54-132–54-137, which established the Frisco juvenile curfew, was repealed and deleted in its entirety by Ordinance 2023-08-37, adopted 8/15/2023. There is currently no Frisco municipal juvenile curfew offense. Prior to deletion, the article derived from Ordinance 07-09-50, sec. 2, adopted 9/18/07; Ordinance 13-09-50 adopted 9/3/13; Ordinance 17-04-24 adopted 4/4/17; Ordinance 2020-03-10 adopted 3/3/20; and Ordinance 2023-02-05 adopted 2/7/2023.", summary:"Frisco's juvenile curfew (former Article V, §§ 54-132–54-137) was repealed and deleted in its entirety by Ordinance 2023-08-37, effective 8/15/2023. There is currently no Frisco municipal juvenile curfew offense. Included here so the repeal is visible in the guide rather than a silent gap.", street:["There is no Frisco juvenile curfew to enforce — Article V was repealed in full effective 8/15/2023. Don't cite §§ 54-132–54-137 or rely on a curfew as the basis for a stop.","The repeal also coincides with 2023 Texas legislation limiting municipal and county juvenile-curfew authority statewide — confirm current state law before relying on any curfew ordinance, here or in another jurisdiction."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 54-56", name:"Carrying Firearms in City Buildings", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["firearms"], level:"Penalty not stated in this section — see Ch. 54 general penalty provision", lvlClass:"m", kw:"gun pistol handgun weapon city hall municipal building", text:"§ 54-56. Carrying firearms in city buildings.\n(a)    It shall be unlawful for any person to carry a firearm in any city building except a duly licensed person may carry a handgun on those city premises where allowed by state law and this article.\n(b)    It is unlawful for any person, except for a licensed handgun holder who has a concealed handgun, to have any other firearm, including an openly carried handgun, at any governmental meeting that is posted in accordance with the Texas Open Meetings Act.\n(c)    These restrictions shall not apply to a peace officer or to a city employee who has written authorization from the city manager or his authorized designee to carry a firearm as part of the city employee's official duties.\n(d)    The terms \"city building\" and \"city premises,\" as used in this section, have the same meaning as the term \"premises,\" as that term is defined in section 46.035(f) of the Texas Penal Code, as the same may be amended.\n(e)    The term \"firearm,\" as used in this section, has the same meaning as in section 46.01(3) of the Texas Penal Code, as the same may be amended.\n(f)    The term \"handgun,\" as used in this section, has the same meaning as in section 46.01(5) of the Texas Penal Code, as the same may be amended.\n(g)    The term \"concealed the handgun,\" as used in this section, shall mean that its presence is not openly discernible to the ordinary observation of a reasonable person.\n(h)    The term \"possession,\" as used in this section, means on the person or the person has access thereto, except where storage of a firearm is allowed by law.\n(i)  Signs shall be posted in accordance with the law notifying persons of the restrictions provided in this section. (Ordinance 95-12-14, secs. 1, 2, adopted 12/19/95; Ordinance 16-03-22, sec. 3, adopted 3/1/16)", summary:"Unlawful to carry a firearm in any city building, except a duly licensed person may carry a handgun on city premises where allowed by state law and this article; a separate, narrower prohibition bars any firearm (other than a licensed concealed handgun) at a posted governmental meeting under the Texas Open Meetings Act. Peace officers and authorized city employees are exempted.", street:["Scoped narrowly to city-owned buildings and posted governmental meetings — this is not a general public-carry restriction, consistent with Texas's broad state preemption of local firearm regulation.","Peace officers are expressly exempted from these restrictions.","'City building,' 'firearm,' and 'handgun' are defined in this section by cross-reference to the Texas Penal Code (§§ 46.01, 46.035) — use the state definitions."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 54-57", name:"Discharge of Firearms in City Limits", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["firearms"], level:"Penalty not stated in this section — see Ch. 54 general penalty provision", lvlClass:"m", kw:"gun shooting gunshot shots fired discharge weapon", text:"§ 54-57. Discharge of firearms in city limits.\n(a)    (1)   It shall be unlawful for a person to discharge a firearm within the city limits except within a sport shooting range or on property zoned for such use. This provision shall not apply if the discharge of a firearm is on property that was annexed after September 1, 1981 or is in the city's extraterritorial jurisdiction and meets the exceptions from regulation contained in section 229.002 of the Local Government Code, as the same may be amended.\n(2)   This provision shall not supersede the restrictions on carrying or discharging firearms and other devices as set out in chapter 58 (Parks and Recreation), section 58-92(17)b of the Code of Ordinances.\n(b)    This section shall not be construed to prohibit a peace officer from discharging a firearm in the performance of his duty or to prohibit any citizen from discharging a firearm when lawfully defending himself, another person, or property, or when he is otherwise allowed by law to discharge a firearm.\n(c)  The term \"firearm,\" as used in this section, shall mean all percussion weapons, but shall not include air guns, air pistols, air rifles, and all other firearms using air pressure, propellant, or a spring to propel a projectile, (Ordinance 16-03-22, sec. 3, adopted 3/1/16)", summary:"Unlawful to discharge a firearm within city limits except at a sport shooting range or on property zoned for that use, with an exception for property annexed after September 1, 1981 or in the city's extraterritorial jurisdiction that meets the exceptions in Local Government Code § 229.002.", street:["This section is written to track the state preemption statute directly (Local Government Code § 229.002) — it does not attempt to regulate discharge beyond what state law allows a city to reach.","Confirm zoning and annexation history before charging — the ETJ and post-1981-annexation exceptions are real limits on this section's reach, not defenses to be raised later."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 54-90", name:"Specific Noise Disturbance Prohibited", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["noise"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 54-91(b) — fine up to $500; each day separate", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 54-90. Specific noise disturbance prohibited.\n(a)    No person shall allow, make or cause to be made any unreasonably loud or disturbing noise in the city which is offensive to the sensibilities of a reasonable, prudent adult person, renders the enjoyment of life or property uncomfortable, interferes with public peace and comfort, or causes a noise disturbance as defined herein.\n(b)    The following list includes, but is not limited to, activities which can create unreasonably loud or disturbing noises in violation of this article, including activities which are noise disturbances per se, unless an exemption exists pursuant to section 54-91 or a permit of variance was first obtained as provided in section 54-92.\n(1)   Animals.Owning, keeping, possessing, or harboring any animal or animals which, by frequent or habitual noise making, unreasonably disturbs or interferes with the peace, comfort or repose of the citizens of the city, or causes a noise disturbance as defined herein. The provisions of this article shall apply to all private or public facilities including any animal shelter or commercial kennel, which hold or treat animals.\n(2)   Radios, television sets, musical instruments, loud speaking amplifiers and similar devices.\na.    The using, operating or permitting to be played, used or operated any sound production or reproduction device, radio, receiving set, musical instrument, drums, phonograph, television set, loudspeakers and sound amplifiers or other machine or device for the producing or reproducing of sound within a residential district or quiet zone, or within 500 feet of any residence or quiet zone, in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance. Furthermore, any such activity shall create a noise disturbance per se if conducted between the hours of 10:00 p.m. and 7:00 a.m.\nb.    The using, operating or permitting to be played, used or operated any sound production or reproduction device, radio, receiving set, musical instrument, drums, phonograph, television set, loudspeakers and sound amplifiers or other machine or device for the producing or reproducing of sound within a nonresidential area in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance.\nc.    The using, operating or permitting to be played, used or operated any sound production or reproduction device, radio, receiving set, musical instrument, drums, phonograph, television set, loudspeakers and sound amplifiers or other machine or device that produces or reproduces sound for the purpose of attracting attention to any cause or demonstration, or to any performance, show, sale or display of merchandise so as to attract attention to such cause, demonstration or premises when such use is done in a manner which causes a noise disturbance.\nd.    The using, operating or permitting to be played, used or operated any sound production or reproduction device, radio, receiving set, musical instrument, drums, phonograph, television set, loudspeakers and sound amplifiers or other machine or device on trucks or other moving vehicles for the purpose of attracting attention to any cause or demonstration, or for advertising any show, sale or display of merchandise when such use is done in a manner which causes a noise disturbance.\n(3)   Vehicular sound amplification systems.Operating or controlling a motor vehicle in either a public or private place within the city and operating any sound device which is part of, or connected to, any radio, stereo receiver, compact disc player, cassette tape player, or other similar device in the motor vehicle, in such a manner that, when operated, it is audible at a distance of 30 feet, or when operated, causes a person to be aware of the vibration accompanying the sound at a distance of 30 feet from the source when such operation is done in a manner which causes a noise disturbance.\n(4)   Yelling, shouting, etc.The yelling, shouting, crying, hooting, whistling or singing of peddlers, hawkers or any other person within the city in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance.\n(5)   Loading operations.The loading or unloading of any vehicle within the city in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance.\n(6)   Construction/maintenance work.\na.    Operating or permitting to be operated any equipment used in construction, maintenance, repair, alteration or demolition work on buildings, structures, streets, alleys, lawns, golf courses or appurtenances thereto and/or the erection, including excavation, demolition, alteration or repair of any building within a residential district or quiet zone, or within 500 feet of any residence or quiet zone, in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance. Furthermore, any such activity shall create a noise disturbance per se if conducted between the hours of 10:00 p.m. and 7:00 a.m.\nb.    Operating or permitting to be operated any gravel pit, rock crusher or other machinery for the separation, gathering, grading, loading or unloading of sand, rock or gravel, within a residential district or quiet zone, or within 500 feet of any residence or quiet zone, in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance. Furthermore, any such activity shall create a noise disturbance per se if conducted between the hours of 10:00 p.m. and 7:00 a.m.\nc.    Operating or permitting to be operated any equipment used in construction, maintenance, repair, alteration or demolition work on buildings, structures, streets, alleys, lawns, golf courses or appurtenances thereto within a nonresidential district in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance.\nd.    Operating or permitting to be operated any gravel pit, rock crusher or other machinery for the separation, gathering, grading, loading or unloading of sand, rock or gravel within a nonresidential district in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance.\n(7)   Power equipment.\na.    Operating or permitting to be operated any power equipment (as defined herein and excluding construction equipment which is specifically regulated by subsection (6) above) within a residential district or quiet zone, or within 500 feet of any residence or quiet zone, in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance. Furthermore, any such activity shall create a noise disturbance per se if conducted between the hours of 10:00 p.m. and 7:00 a.m.\nb.    Operating or permitting to be operated any power equipment (as defined herein and excluding construction equipment which is specifically regulated by subsection (6) above) within a nonresidential district in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance.\n(8)   Motor vehicles-Repairs or testing.\na.    The repairing, rebuilding, modifying or testing of any motor vehicle (including off- road vehicles) or watercraft within a residential district or quiet zone, or within 500 feet of any residence or quiet zone, in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance. Furthermore, any such activity shall create a noise disturbance per se if conducted between the hours of 10:00 p.m. and 7:00 a.m.\nb.    The repairing, rebuilding, modifying or testing of any motor vehicle (including off- road vehicles) or watercraft within a nonresidential district in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance.\n(9)   Same-Running loud or out of repair.\na.    The use of any automobile, motorcycle or other vehicle so out of repair, so modified, or so loaded, which emits or creates loud or unnecessary grading, grinding or rasping noise, the excessive spinning of the tires, or the racing of a motor vehicle engine unnecessarily within a residential district or quiet zone, or within 500 feet of any residence or quiet zone, in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance. Furthermore, such activity shall create a noise disturbance per se if conducted between the hours of 10:00 p.m. and 7:00 a.m.\nb.    The use of any automobile, motorcycle or other vehicle so out of repair, so modified, or so loaded, which emits or creates loud or unnecessary grading, grinding or rasping noise, the excessive spinning of the tires, or the racing of a motor vehicle engine unnecessarily within a nonresidential district in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance.\n(10) Same-Exhaust.The discharge into the open air of the exhaust of any motor vehicle in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance, except as discharged through a muffler or other device which effectively and efficiently prevents loud and unusual noises and annoying smoke.\n(11) Impulsive sources.Causing impulsive sound sources including, but not limited to, the use of fireworks, explosives, the firing of guns or other explosive devices within the city in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance. This is not intended to preclude any existing ordinances prohibiting such acts.\n(12) Powered model mechanical devices.\na.    The flying of model aircraft powered by internal combustion engines, whether tethered or not, or the firing or operating of model rocket vehicles or other similar noise producing devices, within a residential district or quiet zone, or within 500 feet of any residence or quiet zone, in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance. Furthermore, any such activity shall create a noise disturbance per se if conducted between the hours of 10:00 p.m. and 7:00 a.m.\nb.    The flying of model aircraft powered by internal combustion engines, whether tethered or not, or the firing or operating of model rocket vehicles or other similar noise producing devices within a nonresidential district in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance.\n(13) Refuse compacting vehicles.Operating or permitting to be operated any refuse compacting, processing or collection vehicle or parking lot sweeper in any residential district or quiet zone, or within 500 feet of any residence or quiet zone in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance.\n(14) Quiet zoneCreating a noise disturbance on any street adjacent to any school, hospital, clinic, library or other noise sensitive facility.\n(15) Vibration.Using or causing the use of any device that creates any ground vibration which is perceptible without instruments at any point on or beyond the property boundary of the source.\n(16) Stationary nonemergency signaling devices.Sounding or permitting the sounding of any electronically activated or amplified signal from any stationary bell, chime, siren, whistle, or similar device, intended primarily for nonemergency purposes, from any place for more than five minutes during any consecutive 60-minute period which causes a noise disturbance. Except such signaling device is allowed if used as a danger signal, and/or as required by law if vehicle is backing, starting or turning in such a way as to likely cause a collision. (Ordinance 97-04-13, sec. 5, adopted 4/15/97)", summary:"Prohibits allowing, making, or causing any unreasonably loud or disturbing noise offensive to a person of ordinary sensibilities, with a non-exhaustive list of specifically covered noise sources and conditions in subsection (b).", street:["Subsection (b)'s illustrative list covers most real-world noise complaints — check it for the specific source before writing a generic 'loud noise' narrative.","The 'person of ordinary sensibilities' standard is objective — document what a reasonable person, not just the complainant, would find disturbing."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 54-91", name:"Noise — Exemptions and Penalty", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["noise"], level:"Misdemeanor, fine up to $500; each day/each new source a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 54-91. Exemptions.\n(a)    The following sources of potential noise disturbances shall be exempt from the regulations of this article:\n(1)   Safety signals, storm warning sirens or horns and the testing of such equipment, emergency vehicle sirens or horns used when responding to an emergency, and emergency pressure relief valves;\n(2)   Sound caused in the performance of emergency or public service work, including police, fire and public utility operations, acting in the performance of lawful duties to protect the health, safety or welfare of the community;\n(3)   Sounds caused by natural phenomena;\n(4)   Activities conducted on public parks and playgrounds which are approved, sponsored or sanctioned by the city. Activities conducted on public or private school grounds including, but not limited to, school athletic and school entertainment events which are approved, sponsored or sanctioned by the school. Pizza Hut Park shall not be treated as a public park for purposes of gaining an exemption under this article;\n(5)   Those activities listed under section 54-90(b)(2) that are conducted within Pizza Hut Park are exempt so long as they are conducted during the following hours: Sunday-Thursday: From 7:00 a.m. to 11:00 p.m. Friday and Saturday: From 7:00 a.m. to 11:30 p.m. Any activities listed under section 54-90(b)(2) that are conducted within Pizza Hut Park shall not be exempt and shall create a noise disturbance per se if conducted outside of the times listed in this subsection. Any person, firm, corporation, or business entity violating this provision and creating a noise disturbance per se shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction thereof, shall be fined a sum not exceeding $500.00. If there is any form of cessation in the noise disturbance or if a new person, firm, corporation, or business entity becomes the originator of the noise disturbance, the noise disturbance that follows such a cessation or change in the originator shall constitute a separate offense.\n(b)  Penalty.Any person, firm, corporation or business entity violating this section shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction thereof, shall be fined a sum not exceeding $500.00. Except for per se violations in Pizza Hut Park, each continuing day's violation under this section shall constitute a separate offense. Per se violations in Pizza Hut Park, however, will be handled as set forth in subsection (a)(5). The penal provisions imposed under this section shall not preclude the city from filing suit to enjoin the violation. Frisco retains all legal rights and remedies available to it pursuant to local, state and federal law. (Ordinance 97-04-13, sec. 6, adopted 4/15/97; Ordinance 08-08-73, secs. 2, 3, adopted 8/5/08)", summary:"Exempts safety/emergency signals and operations, natural phenomena, and city-sanctioned park/school activities from the noise disturbance prohibition, with a specific carve-out and curfew-style hours for events at Pizza Hut Park. States the general penalty: misdemeanor, fine up to $500, with each continuing day (or new source after a break) a separate offense.", street:["Check this section's exemption list before charging — emergency operations, city-sanctioned school/park events, and natural sounds are not violations regardless of volume.","Pizza Hut Park has its own specific event-hours carve-out (7 a.m.–11 p.m. Sun–Thu, 7 a.m.–11:30 p.m. Fri–Sat) — outside those hours, listed activities there are a per se noise disturbance."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 54-172 – 54-178", name:"Sex Offender Residency Restriction", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["sexoffender"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 54-178", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 54-173. Offenses.\n(a)    It is unlawful for a person who meets the definition of a 'sex offender' to establish a permanent residence or temporary residence within 1,000 feet of any premises where children commonly gather.\n(b)  Culpable mental state is not required. Neither allegation nor evidence of a culpable mental state is required for the proof of an offense defined in this chapter. (Ordinance 08-03-32, sec. 3, adopted 3/4/08)\n\n§ 54-174. Evidentiary matters; measurement.\n(a)    It shall be prima facie evidence that this section applies to a person if that person's record appears on the database and the database indicates that the victim was less than 17 years of age.\n(b)    For the purpose of determining the minimum distance of separation, the requirements shall be measured by following a straight line from the outer property line of the permanent or temporary residence to the nearest property line of the premises where children commonly gather, as described hereinabove, or, in the case of multiple residences on one property, measuring from the nearest property line of the premises to the nearest property line of the premises where children commonly gather, as described herein.\n(c)  A map depicting the prohibited areas shall be maintained by the city. The city shall review the map annually for changes. Said map will be available to the public at the Frisco Police Department. (Ordinance 08-03-32, sec. 4, adopted 3/4/08)\n\n§ 54-175. Affirmative defenses. Affirmative defenses. It is an affirmative defense to prosecution that any of the following conditions apply:\n(1)    The person required to register on the database established the permanent or temporary residence and has complied with all of the sex offender registration laws of the State of Texas, prior to the date of the adoption of this article.\n(2)    The person required to register on the database was a minor when he or she committed the offense requiring such registration and was not convicted as an adult.\n(3)    The person required to register on the database is a minor.\n(4)    The premises where children commonly gather, as specified herein, within 1,000 feet of the permanent or temporary residence of the person required to register on the database, was designated, declared and/or determined, within the sole discretion of the property owner, after the person established the permanent or temporary residence and complied with all sex offender registration laws of the State of Texas.\n(5)    The information on the database is incorrect, and, if corrected, this section would not apply to the person who was erroneously listed on the database.\n(6)    The person was at the time of the violation subject to community services supervision pursuant to V.T.C.A., Texas Code of Criminal Procedure sec. 42.12(13B) and the court reduced or waived the 1,000-foot restriction for a child free zone under V.T.C.A., sec. 42.12(13B)(a)(1)(B) as it applies to the person's residence.\n(7)  It is not a defense to prosecution under this section that a person was allowed by the city to register or verify a residence that is within 1,000 feet of premises where children commonly gather. (Ordinance 08-03-32, sec. 5, adopted 3/4/08; Ordinance 10-02-12, sec. 3, adopted 2/16/10)\n\n§ 54-178. Penalty provision. Any person, firm, corporation, agent or employees thereof who violate any of the provisions of this article shall be guilty of a misdemeanor and upon conviction thereof shall be fined an amount not to exceed $2,000.00 for each offense. Each day that a violation is permitted to exist shall constitute a separate offense. The penal provisions imposed under this article shall not preclude the city from filing suit to enjoin the violation. The city retains all legal rights and remedies available to it pursuant to local, state and federal law. (Ordinance 08-03-32, sec. 8, adopted 3/4/08)", summary:"Unlawful for a person who meets the article's definition of 'sex offender' (required to register due to a conviction involving a minor) to establish a permanent or temporary residence within 1,000 feet of a 'premises where children commonly gather' — parks, schools, day care centers, and qualifying private recreational facilities. No culpable mental state is required for the offense. A person's appearance on the state sex offender database is prima facie evidence the article applies. Several affirmative defenses are available (e.g., the residence predates the qualifying premises, or the person's registration requirement has been satisfied), listed in § 54-175.", street:["Verify the person's status on the Texas DPS Sex Offender Database first — the article makes that record prima facie evidence the residency restriction applies.","The 1,000-foot measurement and 'premises where children commonly gather' definition (§ 54-172) are specific — parks, schools, day cares, and certain private recreational facilities with an entry fee or HOA ownership qualify; not every place children might be present does.","No culpable mental state is required — this is a strict-liability-style residency violation once the elements are met.","Check § 54-175's affirmative defenses (e.g., residence established before the qualifying premises existed) before referring for prosecution."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 54-192 – 54-194", name:"Urinating or Defecating in Public", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["publicconduct"], level:"Misdemeanor, fine up to $500", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 54-192. Urinating or defecating prohibited.\n(a)     A person commits an offense if the person urinates and/or defecates:\n(1)    On public property or in a public place; or\n(2) In public view. (Ordinance 08-07-66, sec. 2(54-140), adopted 7/15/08)\n\n§ 54-193. Defense. It is a defense to prosecution under this article if the person was in a restroom. (Ordinance 08-07-66, sec. 2(54-141), adopted 7/15/08)\n\n§ 54-194. Penalty. Any person, firm, corporation or business entity violating this article shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction thereof, shall be fined a sum not exceeding $500.00. Each continuing day's violation under this article shall constitute a separate offense. The penal provisions imposed under this article shall not preclude the city from filing suit to enjoin the violation. Frisco retains all legal rights and remedies available to it pursuant to local, state and federal law. (Ordinance 08-07-66, sec. 3, adopted 7/15/08)", summary:"Unlawful to urinate or defecate on public property, in a public place, or in public view. It is a defense to prosecution that the person was in a restroom. Punishable as a misdemeanor with a fine up to $500.", street:["The 'in public view' element is independent of being on public property — this can be charged on private property visible to the public.","The restroom defense is narrow and factual — confirm whether an actual restroom was reasonably available and used."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 54-201", name:"Failure to Obey Subpoena", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["publicconduct"], level:"Misdemeanor, fine up to $200", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 54-201. Failure to obey subpoena. Failure to obey a subpoena or produce books, papers, and other evidence as a result of an investigation made by the city council pursuant to section 3.17, city charter, shall constitute a misdemeanor and shall be punishable by a fine not to exceed $200.00. (Ordinance 09-09-52, sec. 2, adopted 9/15/09)", summary:"Failing to obey a city council subpoena, or to produce books, papers, or other evidence in a city council investigation under the city charter, is a misdemeanor punishable by a fine up to $200.", street:["Narrow application — this is about city council investigative subpoenas under the city charter, not a general failure-to-appear or evidence-tampering charge."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 54-211 – 54-213", name:"Electioneering at Polling Locations", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["publicconduct"], level:"Offense; penalty not stated in this section — see Ch. 54 general penalty provision", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 54-211. Purpose. The purpose of this article is to provide reasonable regulations for electioneering on city-owned or controlled property when such property is used as an election polling place. The regulations contained herein are intended to mitigate safety risks, prevent damage to public property and ensure that the public property is sufficiently available for its patrons and city employees and staff who use the facilities other than for election purposes. (Ordinance 15-03-14, sec. 3, adopted 3/17/15)\n\n§ 54-212. Definitions. The following words and phrases as used in this article shall have the meanings as set forth in this section: Electioneering shall mean the posting, use, or distribution of political signs or literature, including the use of tents, chairs, booths, tables or other furniture or devices to post, use or distribute political signs or literature. Electioneering device shall mean tents, chairs, booths, tables or other furniture or devices used to post or distribute political signs or literature. Tent shall mean a tent, canopy, covering or similar item that does not exceed ten (10) feet by ten (10) feet in size and is temporarily erected to provide shelter from the sun and other weather conditions when engaging in electioneering. Voting period shall mean the period beginning the hour the polls open for early voting and ending when the polls close or the last voter has voted on election day, whichever is later. (Ordinance 15-03-14, sec. 3, adopted 3/17/15; Ordinance 2020-10-69 adopted 10/6/20)\n\n§ 54-213. Regulations and exceptions.\n(a)    The following regulations apply to electioneering on the premises of city-owned or controlled property used as a polling place during the voting period.\n(1)   It is an offense for any person to leave any electioneering sign, literature, material, tent or other electioneering device on city-owned or controlled property that is used as a polling place other than during the period beginning on 6:00 p.m. before the voting period begins and ending twenty-four (24) hours after the voting period ends.\n(2)   It is an offense for any person to engage in electioneering on driveways or parking areas on the premises of a polling location or in such areas that the fire chief or his/her designee determines to be unsafe for electioneering or determines will interfere with patrons or city employees and staff who use the areas other than for election purposes. This restriction shall not apply to electioneering signs, literature or materials that are attached to vehicles lawfully parked at the premises of a polling location.\n(3)   It is an offense for any person to attach, place or otherwise affix any electioneering sign, literature, material, tent or other electioneering device to any building, tree, shrub, pole or other improvement on city-owned or controlled property used as a polling location.\n(4)   It is an offense for any person to place any electioneering sign, literature or material on the premises that exceeds four (4) square feet and is more than four (4) feet in height, including any supporting poles.\n(5)   It is an offense for any person to place any electioneering sign, literature, material, tent or other electioneering device within ten (10) feet of a public roadway adjacent to city-owned or controlled property used as a polling location .\n(6)   During the voting period and for thirty (30) minutes before and after the voting period each day, tents and other electioneering devices may be placed on city-owned or controlled property used as a polling location where otherwise permitted under this section and other law on a first-come, first-served basis when space is available. It is an offense for any person to place a tent or other electioneering device that exceeds ten (10) feet by ten (10) feet in size or in a location or manner that violates this section or other law.\n(7)   In addition to imposing any criminal penalty, electioneering signs, literature, materials, tents or other electioneering devices located in violation of this section or other law may be removed and disposed of by the city.\n(8)   The authority to conduct electioneering on city-owned or controlled property under this article is limited to the property on the premises where the voting is conducted and only for the voting period.\n(b)  The regulations set forth in subsection (a) above shall not apply to any city-authorized signs, materials or other messages on city-owned or controlled property. (Ordinance 15-03-14, sec. 3, adopted 3/17/15; Ordinance 2020-10-69 adopted 10/6/20)", summary:"Regulates electioneering (posting, using, or distributing political signs, literature, tents, or furniture) on city-owned or controlled property used as a polling place. Makes it an offense to leave electioneering materials outside the permitted window, electioneer in driveways/parking areas or unsafe/high-traffic zones, affix materials to buildings or trees, exceed size limits on signs or tents, place materials within 10 feet of a public roadway, or use an oversized tent — subject to a first-come, first-served rule during the voting period. Violating materials may also be removed by the city in addition to any criminal penalty.", street:["Six distinct electioneering violations are listed in § 54-213(a) — identify which specific one applies rather than citing the article generally.","The permitted window is narrow: 6 p.m. the evening before voting begins through 24 hours after voting ends.","The city can remove violating materials administratively, separate from and in addition to any criminal charge."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 54-221 – 54-223", name:"Possession of Catalytic Converter", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["catalytic"], level:"Penalty not stated in these sections — see Ch. 54 general penalty provision", lvlClass:"m", kw:"stolen catalytic converter theft cut off exhaust", text:"§ 54-221. Definitions. Catalytic converter. An exhaust emission control device that reduces toxic gases and pollutants from internal combustion engines that has been removed from a vehicle by cutting or some means other than unbolting it from the vehicle; the term includes any material removed from a catalytic converter. Metal recycling entity. Has the meaning assigned by section 1956.001(7) of the Texas Occupations Code. (Ordinance 2022-09-41 adopted 9/6/2022)\n\n§ 54-222. Possession of catalytic converter. It shall be unlawful for any person or entity other than a metal recycling entity to possess a catalytic converter as defined in section 54-221. Each catalytic converter in an individual or entity's possession shall constitute a separate offense. (Ordinance 2022-09-41 adopted 9/6/2022)\n\n§ 54-223. Affirmative defense. It is an affirmative defense to the prosecution for an offense under section 54-222 if the person or entity:\n(1)    Provides the year, make, model and vehicle identification number for the vehicle from which the catalytic converter was removed, a copy of the certificate of title or other documentation indicating that the person or entity has an ownership interest in such vehicle and proof that the catalytic converter was removed from such vehicle; or\n(2)  Presents proof that the possession of the catalytic converter lawfully passed from the owner of the vehicle from which the catalytic converter was removed to the person or entity in possession of the catalytic converter. (Ordinance 2022-09-41 adopted 9/6/2022)", summary:"Unlawful for any person or entity other than a metal recycling entity to possess a catalytic converter that has been removed from a vehicle by cutting or a means other than unbolting it — each converter possessed is a separate offense. An affirmative defense exists if the person can provide the vehicle's year, make, model, and VIN the converter came from, along with other documentation listed in § 54-223.", street:["This targets possession of a cut-off converter itself — it doesn't require proving theft, which is a real charging advantage when a suspect is caught with converters but not caught in the act of cutting them.","Each individual converter in possession is its own separate offense — count them.","The affirmative defense requires the person to produce vehicle identification for the converter's source — a person who can't account for where it came from doesn't get the defense.","This is a city ordinance distinct from any Texas Penal Code or Business & Commerce Code catalytic converter theft/sale provisions — check state law separately if theft can be proven."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 58-92", name:"Parks — General Provisions (Hours, Conduct, Prohibited Items)", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parks"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 58-97 (up to $500, higher for fire-related violations)", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 58-92. General provisions. The city hereby adopts the following general provisions:\n[Subsections (1)-(2), department establishment and director appointment, omitted — internal administration, not patrol-relevant.]\n(3)    Park names.It is appropriate to name or rename certain city parks in honor and recognition of outstanding individuals who served the community well, and it is further appropriate to name other city parks with a geographical name, park names should be familiar to the majority of citizens, easy to recall, unique and lasting.\na.    Parks shall be named by outstanding and/or predominate physical characteristics of the land such as, among other characteristics: 1.    Streams, rivers, lakes and creeks; 2.    Landmark significance; 3.    Historic significance; and/or 4.    Street name identity.\nb.    If a name is applied to park facilities such as recreational buildings, swimming pools, sports fields or play structures, those shall be named either: 1.    By identification with the park in which it lies; 2.    In honor of an individual or group when total contributions of fifty percent (50%) or more of the total cost of acquisition and development of facilities are donated to the city; or 3.    When considering the naming of a park or park facilities in honor of a person, the person should have made a major contribution to the city and/or the parks and recreation system, or the person should be known for some other significant accomplishment.\n(4)    Park hours.Parks shall be open for the public every day of the year during designated hours, except for maintenance or unusual and unforeseen emergencies. A variation in park hours may be permitted by the director.\na.    Hours of neighborhood park use shall normally be from thirty (30) minutes before sunrise to thirty (30) minutes after sunset.\nb.    Hours of community park or game field or playing field use shall normally be from thirty\n(30) minutes before sunrise to 12:00 midnight.\nc.    Except as authorized by the parks and recreation director, it shall be unlawful for any person(s) to be or remain upon and/or in any park after park closing times, as such times are posted on a sign located on park property. If no sign with listed closing times is posted on park property, it shall be unlawful for any person(s) to be or remain upon and/or in that park during a period beginning at 12:00 midnight and ending thirty (30) minutes before sunrise, except as authorized in writing by the parks and recreation director.\n(5)    Indoor facility and outdoor facility hours.It shall be unlawful for any person, other than city authorized personnel, to enter upon the premises of any city indoor facility and outdoor facility other than during the hours the facility is officially open.\n(6)    Swimming, boating and fishing in parks.\na.    It shall be unlawful for any person to utilize any fountain, creek, pond, lake, stream or any other body of water in any park in the city to, among other things, swim in, boat in, wade in, or pollute any fountain, creek, pond, lake, stream or any other body of water in any park in the city unless such activity(ies) is/are specifically authorized and permitted by the director in writing and/or any other regulation and policy.\nb.    Electric or gas powered radio controlled watercraft are allowed in bodies of water located within city parks, RC controlled watercraft operators are prohibited from disturbing or becoming a nuisance to any other park patrons or wildlife.\nc.    Fishing shall be permitted only from the banks of any creek, pond, lake or other body of water in any park. No trotlines, throw lines, fish traps or nets shall be permitted. Fish may not be cleaned in any park. Other fishing regulations apply as outlined by the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department.\nd.    This subsection shall not apply to any municipally owned or operated swimming pools or boat rental operations, as applicable.\n(7)    Disrupting any department-sponsored events or any special events or programs.It shall be unlawful for any person to do any of the following acts:\na.    To willfully interfere with, disrupt or prevent the orderly conduct of any supervised play, amusement program, fully or in part sponsored events or any special events conducted by the department or the city in any park or other location in or on any public property within the city.\nb.    To participate in any activity which will create a danger to the public or which may be considered a public nuisance or to engage in physical violence.\nc.    To remain in any building, swimming pool, playground or park in or on any public property within the city after being advised by the supervisor of the department to leave such building, swimming pool, playground or park located in or on any public property within the city.\nd.    To disturb in any manner any legitimate facility uses including, but not limited to, rentals, picnics, meetings, classes, games, practices, meets, tournaments, exhibitions, camps, special events or other such uses.\n(8)    Recreational riding devices in parks.Recreational riding devices shall be governed by safe riding practices and consideration for use of parks by others. Where special parking provisions have been made for bicycles, parking shall be limited to that area. Recreational riding devices shall be prohibited in playgrounds, flowerbeds, pedestrian-only sidewalks, tennis courts, athletic courts, picnic pavilions, stairs, guard and hand rails, benches, picnic tables, elevated surfaces, painted concrete, laminated surfaces and/or any other areas designated by the city.\n(9)    Overnight camping or parking of vehicles.Overnight camping shall be allowed for one (1) night only in Warren Park and Frisco Commons for up to thirty (30) individuals, with written permission from the director. No individual, organization or individual representing or a party to an organization shall be allowed to overnight camp for more than one (1) night. Each person shall observe and obey all park rules and regulations and restore their campsite area to its original condition. It shall be unlawful to park a vehicle overnight on any park property.\n(10) Fires.Fires shall be permitted only in enclosed fireplaces or grills provided for this purpose. It shall be unlawful to leave a park area without extinguishing a fire. After use, coals shall be thoroughly extinguished with water and cooled and disposed of in a trash receptacle. Privately owned grills are only permitted on concrete surfaces located in parks. During city directed burn bans, the use of fire is not permitted.\n(11) Plants and shrubs.It shall be unlawful to damage, cut, carve, mark, remove, transplant, break, pick, or in any way injure, damage, or deface any plants, trees, shrubs, turf and/or other personal property within or upon any park. It shall further be unlawful to plant into the ground any type of plant, tree, shrub and/or turf in any park, without prior written approval of the director.\n(12) Property damage.It shall be unlawful to damage, deface or remove personal property within or upon any park.\n(13) Glass at parks.It shall be unlawful to possess on the premises of any park area any glass beverage containers. It shall also be unlawful to willfully break any glass container in any park area.\n(14) Animals at athletic fields.It shall be unlawful for a person to allow any animal, for which they are solely or jointly responsible for controlling, on any athletic field, concession/restroom area, and/or plaza or playground areas within any park, with the exception of licensed or authorized service animals.\na.    It shall also be unlawful for a person to allow any animal, with the exception of authorized service animals, for which they are solely or jointly responsible for controlling, within seventy-five feet (75') of any athletic field, concession, restroom, playground or plaza areas within any park unless the animal is located completely on a paved walking trail that is not more than ten feet (10') wide and remains on the walking trail while within seventy-five feet (75') of any athletic field, concession or plaza areas within any park.\nb.    For purposes of this subsection, \"plaza\" shall mean the entire paved portion in the center of a 4-plex or 5-plex of any athletic field/facility. A plaza shall not be considered to be a walking trail. \"Playground\" shall mean the entire safety surface area around and under playground equipment.\n(15) Charging of fees.It shall be unlawful for a person, on behalf of themself/itself and/or any other person, excluding city departments, to:\na.    Charge admission(s) or any type of fee(s) to attend an activity at a park or city controlled facility without the prior written permission from the director;\nb.    Seek on-site donation(s) to attend an activity at a park or city controlled facility without the prior written permission from the director; and/or\nc.    Promote, advertise, solicit and/or, in any other way, encourage another to, among other things, participate in, engage in, purchase and/or join in, among other things, a cause, service, business, event, function, activity and/or product, for or not-for-profit, at a park or city controlled facility without the prior written permission from the director.\n(16) Sale of goods.It shall be unlawful to offer any goods, food, drinks, confections, merchandise or services for sale within parks, parkways, or other recreational facilities, or on public streets and rights-of-way within three hundred feet (300') of the boundary of the same, except in commercial areas where property zoned for retail and commercial building has a certificate of occupancy for such business purposes or unless specifically authorized by the director in writing.\n(17) Firearms, fireworks, etc.\na.    It shall be unlawful for any person to carry a handgun in a park, except those persons who are duly licensed by the State of Texas to carry a handgun in accordance with the provisions of chapter 411, Texas Government Code, as it currently exists or may be amended.\nb.    It shall be unlawful for any person to carry or discharge firearms (unless permitted under subsection a. of this section), fireworks (unless permitted under subsection c. of this section), air guns, bows and arrows, slingshots or any device which would or could project any object which would create a fire hazard or any danger to the public in a park, except with joint written approval of the director and the city's fire chief or police chief.\nc.    A third-party tenant or licensee of a stadium facility located in a park that is used as the home field for a professional sports team is exempt from the requirements of subsection a. of this section in regards to fireworks only, provided all other applicable laws, ordinances and regulations are complied with.\n(18) Authority to prescribe additional rules and regulations.The city council shall have the right, power and authority by resolution, ordinance or otherwise to prescribe additional reasonable rules and regulations or repeal regulations for the maintenance and operation of parks. To carry out the intent of this article, the city council hereby authorizes the department to establish additional, reasonable rules, regulations, policies and/or guidelines for the maintenance, use and operation of parks, and in doing so, the department may, among other things, erect signs and/or notices, as the department deems necessary, in order to inform the public of such rules, regulations, policies and/or guidelines. All rules, regulations, policies and/or guidelines established by the department, as authorized by this subsection, shall be subject to the same enforcement provisions of this article as though they were set forth verbatim herein.\n(19) Liability of city.The city shall not be held liable or bound for any loss or damage claimed by reason of a loss or damage to personal property taken or in any way by reason of any personal injury or death of any person or animal entering a park.\n(20) Aircraft on park property.It shall be unlawful for any person to ascend, descend, operate, or launch any aircraft, except in areas or at times specifically designated for this purpose, which must be evidenced by a special permit, issued by the director, or a facilities use agreement. Electric or gas powered radio controlled aircraft may be operated only in designated areas of designated parks.\n(21) Metal detectors.It shall be prohibited for any person to use or operate metal detectors in any park.\n(22) Alcoholic beverages and illegal narcotics.\na.    The display, consumption or possession of illegal narcotics is prohibited in each and every park located within the city.\nb.    The sale, consumption, possession or display of any alcoholic beverage is prohibited in parks, unless authorized in accordance with this subsection.\nc.    The director may provide advance written authorization for the sale (for consumption on the premises) and/or consumption, possession and display of alcoholic beverage within designated parks provided that the person requesting the authorization and all other persons engaging in the sale (for consumption on the premises) and/or consumption and possession of alcoholic beverages comply with all applicable conditions and other requirements imposed by the director in connection with such authorization. The director is entitled to impose conditions and other requirements in connection with such requests and authorizations. It is unlawful for a person to violate a condition or other requirement imposed by the director under this subsection.\n(23) Park general restrictions.It shall be unlawful for any person to do any of the acts specified below, except as otherwise provided, in all indoor facilities owned, leased, or otherwise controlled by city:\na.    To enter any unauthorized portion of any facility, except with permission of the facility supervisor.\nb.    To fraudulently use a swimming pool pass or recreation center identification card.\nc.    To violate Ordinance 95-04-11, as it currently exists or may be amended, prohibiting the use of in-line skates, skates, skateboards, bicycles, motorized or nonmotorized vehicles and any other type of recreational or nonrecreational product that may destroy the surfaces of tennis courts or any other type of painted concrete or laminate surfaces.\nd.    To loiter within twenty-five feet (25') of a public restroom and for any person over the age of eight (8) years to use the restrooms and washrooms designated for the opposite gender.\ne.    To hit golf balls, except in areas specifically designated for this purpose.\nf.    To use loudspeakers, amplifiers, or microphones, except with written approval of the parks and recreation director.\ng.    To the use of in-line skates, skates, skateboards, bicycles, motorized or nonmotorized vehicles and any other type of recreational or nonrecreational product that may destroy the surfaces of tennis courts or any other type of painted concrete or laminate surfaces.\n(24) Amusement apparatus.The use of any amusement apparatus on the premises of any park is subject to the prior written approval of the director. Additionally, the director may, in his/her sole discretion, impose additional conditions for the use of amusement apparatus on any premises of any park including, but not limited to, liability insurance in amounts to be determined by the director.\n(25) Dog park.The parks and recreation board has established dog park rules, which may be amended at any time. A current list of rules are posted at the dog park and at the city's website. The rules are enforceable by the police department. (Ordinance 03-06-44, sec. 6, adopted 6/3/03; Ordinance 05-07-51, secs. 3-6, adopted 7/5/05; Ordinance 06-06-55, sec. 2, adopted 6/6/06; Ordinance 14-10-60 adopted 10/21/14; Ordinance 16-03-21, sec. 2, adopted 3/1/16; Ordinance 2024-09-39 adopted 9/17/2024)", summary:"The core park-conduct rulebook: park hours (open daily from 30 minutes before sunrise to midnight unless posted otherwise), indoor/outdoor facility hours, swimming/boating/fishing rules, disrupting sponsored events, recreational riding devices, overnight camping/parking, fires restricted to enclosed fireplaces/grills, damaging plants or property, glass containers, animals at athletic fields, unauthorized fee-charging or sales, firearms and fireworks, aircraft, metal detectors, alcohol and illegal narcotics, general park restrictions, amusement apparatus, and dog park rules.", street:["Park hours (30 minutes before sunrise to midnight) function as the closest thing this code has to a park curfew — after-hours presence in a park is chargeable on its own.","Firearms, fireworks, alcohol, and illegal narcotics in parks are each separately addressed here — check the specific subsection rather than citing 'general park violation.'","Fires are restricted to enclosed fireplaces/grills — an unauthorized open fire in a park is a violation independent of any burn-ban or fire-code charge.","Dog park rules are separately posted and enforceable by the police department per subsection (25) — check current posted rules at the specific dog park."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 58-95", name:"Parks — Traffic Generally", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parks"], level:"Penalty via § 58-97 general penalty provision", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 58-95. Traffic generally. The city hereby adopts the following general traffic provisions:\n(1)    Use of vehicles.\na.    It shall be unlawful for any person to violate Ordinance 95-04-11, as it currently exists or may be amended.\nb.    It shall be unlawful for any person to drive any vehicle on park roads at a rate of speed in excess of that which is reasonable and prudent under the conditions and circumstances then prevailing, taking into account the conditions of the roadways and other motor and pedestrian traffic therein, and in no event shall any person drive in or through any park property at a rate of speed in excess of twenty (20) miles per hour unless otherwise posted.\nc.    It shall be unlawful for any person to ride, use or operate any horse, motorcycle, motor scooter or any other vehicle in or upon any park, except on the designated roadway, parking areas or equestrian trail.\nd.    No person is allowed to drive within a park or unauthorized areas, or without written approval of the director. Parking on any grass areas is prohibited unless designated as an overflow parking area. Vehicles in violation may be towed at the owner's expense.\ne.    No person shall drive within a park or on park fields, trails and unauthorized roadways. No person shall park a vehicle in unauthorized areas.\n(2)    Traffic signs.It shall be unlawful for any person to fail to comply with the directions of any sign. The existence of any sign purporting to direct or regulate vehicular or pedestrian traffic shall be prima facie evidence that the same was posted by or at the direction of the director.\n(3)  Traffic control.Traffic pattern, parking, no-parking zones and no-loitering areas, among any other areas, may be designated in the vicinity of special civic, recreational and sporting events for safety and crowd control in coordination with the city's police and fire departments. (Ordinance 03-06-44, sec. 10, adopted 6/3/03; Ordinance 14-10-60 adopted 10/21/14)", summary:"Adopts general traffic and vehicle-use provisions applicable within city parks, including restrictions tied to the city's general traffic ordinance.", street:["Use alongside § 90 (Traffic and Vehicles) — this section applies traffic rules specifically within park property, it doesn't replace the citywide traffic code."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 58-96", name:"Parks — Enforcement", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parks"], level:"Procedural authority — not an offense", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 58-96. Enforcement. The city hereby adopts the following rules and regulations regarding the enforcement of this article:\n(1)    Enforcement.\na.    The director and/or the city's police department shall, in connection with their duties, diligently enforce the provisions of this article, as it exists or may be amended, or any other ordinances applicable to parks and recreation usage, as it/they exist or may be amended.\nb.    The director and/or the police department shall have the authority to eject from areas or facilities any person acting in violation of this article, as it exists or may be amended, or any other ordinances applicable to parks and recreation usage, as it/they exist or may be amended.\n(2)    Expulsion from parks.\na.    Any person charged with violating any rule or regulation of the department, this article, as it exists or may be amended, any other ordinances applicable to parks and recreation usage, as it/they exist or may be amended, and/or any other state, local or federal law, may be expelled from any park, provided a hearing is conducted before the director, allowing the person charged to be given the opportunity to present his/her response to such charge(s). Upon a finding of grounds for expulsion, any person, who is expelled from any park by the director and who thereafter comes onto any park property, shall be guilty of a misdemeanor and upon conviction shall be fined as hereinafter provided. The expulsion shall be for a length of time as the director shall dictate, but the expulsion shall not exceed ninety (90) days. If the expulsion is determined to exceed ninety (90) days, the board must approve the expulsion at its next regularly scheduled meeting.\nb.    The person expelled from a park may appeal, in writing, the decision of the director to the board provided the appeal is made within ten (10) days of the decision of the director. The board shall hear the appeal at its next regularly scheduled meeting, if reasonably possible. The board's ruling shall be final.\nc. Any person may be immediately expelled from any park should he/she violate any rule or regulation of the department, this article, as it exists or may be amended, any other ordinances applicable to parks and recreation usage, as it/they exist or may be amended, and/or any other state, local or federal law, and such violation is deemed by the person charged with enforcing ordinances and/or laws. In his/her reasonable discretion, to be an immediate threat to the health, safety and/or welfare of any other person utilizing any park and/or an immediate threat to the integrity of any park. Such person shall not be allowed to return to any park unless and until the threat(s), described in the previous sentence, have been totally eliminated, as reasonably determined by the person charged with enforcing ordinances and/or laws. (Ordinance 03-06-44, sec. 12, adopted 6/3/03; Ordinance 14-10-60 adopted 10/21/14)", summary:"Establishes enforcement authority and procedures for the Parks and Recreation article, directing the director and/or police department to diligently enforce its provisions.", street:["Confirms Frisco PD has direct, independent enforcement authority over park rules alongside the parks director — you don't need parks staff present to act."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 58-97", name:"Parks — Penalty Provision", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parks"], level:"Misdemeanor, fine up to $500 (higher for fire-related violations — see full text)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 58-97. Penalty provision. Any person violating this article shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction thereof shall be subject to a fine not to exceed the sum of five hundred dollars ($500.00), unless the violation relates to fire safety, zoning or public health and sanitation, including dumping and refuse, in which the fine shall not exceed the sum of two thousand and no/100 dollars ($2,000.00). Each continuing day's violation under this article shall constitute a separate offense. The penal provisions imposed under this article shall not preclude the city from filing suit to enjoin the violation. The city retains all legal rights and remedies available to it pursuant to local, state and federal law. (Ordinance 03-06-44, sec. 13, adopted 6/3/03; Ordinance 14-10-60 adopted 10/21/14)", summary:"The Parks article's general penalty clause: violations are a misdemeanor fined up to $500, except fire-related violations carry a distinct, higher penalty structure set out in this section.", street:["Fire-related park violations are carved out for a higher penalty than the standard $500 cap — check the full text for the specific amount before charging an open-fire violation."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 90-1", name:"Obedience to Traffic Officers", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Penalty not stated in this section — see general Traffic Code penalty provision", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 90-1. Obedience to traffic officers. No person shall willfully fail or refuse to comply with the lawful order or direction of a police officer or fire department official given to direct or control traffic.", summary:"No person shall willfully fail or refuse to comply with the lawful order or direction of a police officer or fire department official given to direct or control traffic.", street:["This is the local ordinance basis for a failure-to-obey-a-traffic-officer charge — willfulness is an element, so document the refusal, not just non-compliance."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 90-60 – 90-62", name:"Motor-Assisted Scooters, Mini-Motorbikes, and Pocket Bikes", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Penalty stated within § 90-61/90-62 — see full text for specific fine", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 90-60. Definitions. The following words, terms and phrases, when used in this article, shall have the meanings ascribed to them in this section, except where the context clearly indicates a different meaning: Adult means any individual 18 years of age or older. Child means any individual under 18 years of age, but does not include a licensed minor, as defined below. Helmet means properly fitted protective headgear that is not structurally damaged and that conforms to the standards of the American National Standards Institute, the American Society for Testing and Materials, the Snell Memorial Foundation or any federal agency having regulatory jurisdiction over bicycle helmets, as applicable, at the time of the manufacture of the helmet. Licensed minor means any individual who is 16 or 17 years of age and has in his possession a valid license issued to him by the state, or the state of the licensed minor's residence, for the operation of a motorcycle or motor vehicle on public streets and highways. Motor assisted scooter shall have the same meaning assigned by V.T.C.A., Transportation Code sec. 551.351, as it exists or may be amended, and includes a self-propelled device with at least two wheels in contact with the ground during operation; a braking system capable of stopping the device under typical operating conditions; a gas or electric motor 40 cubic centimeters or less; a deck designed to allow a person to stand or sit while operating the device; and the ability to be propelled by human power alone. Parent means the natural or adoptive parent or court-appointed guardian or conservator of a child. Pocket bike or mini-motorbike shall have the same meaning assigned by the V.T.C.A., Transportation Code sec. 551.301, as it exists or may be amended, and includes a self-propelled vehicle that is equipped with an electric motorscooter or internal combustion engine having a piston displacement of less than 50 cubic centimeters, is designed to propel itself with not more than two wheels in contact with the ground, has a seat or saddle for the use of the operator, is not designed for use on a highway, and is ineligible for a certificate of title under V.T.C.A., Transportation Code ch. 501, as it exists or may be amended; but does not include a moped, motorcycle, electric bicycle, motor-driven cycle, motorized mobility device, electric personal assistive mobility device or a neighborhood electric vehicle as those are defined in the Texas Transportation Code, as it exists or may be amended. Public way or public property means real property owned, leased or controlled by a political subdivision of the state, a governmental entity or agency, or similar entity, or any property that is publicly-owned or publicly-maintained or dedicated to public use, including, but not limited to, a path, trail, walkway, sidewalk, alley, street or highway, and a public park facility. Wearing a helmet means that the person has a helmet fastened securely to his head with the straps of the helmet securely tightened in the manner intended by the manufacturer to provide maximum protection. (Ordinance 03-11-96, sec. 2, adopted 11/4/03; Ordinance 05-08-61, sec. 3, adopted 8/3/05)\n\n§ 90-61. Restrictions and prohibitions for motor assisted scooters, mini-motorbike or pocketbike, penalty for violation.\n(a)    Restrictions and prohibitions on locations of use.\n(1)   It is unlawful for any child to operate or ride a motor assisted scooter on any public way or public property within the city, except on paths and trails set aside for the exclusive operation of bicycles. It is unlawful for any adult or licensed minor to operate or ride a motor assisted scooter on any path, trail, walkway, alley, sidewalk or public park facility within the city, except on paths and trails set aside for the exclusive operation of bicycles.\n(2)   It is unlawful for a parent to allow or permit a child to operate or ride a motor assisted scooter on any public way or public property within the city, except on paths and trails set aside for the exclusive operation of bicycles.\n(3)   It is unlawful for any child, licensed minor or adult to operate or ride a minimotorbike or pocketbike on any public way or public property within the city.\n(4)   It is unlawful for a parent to allow or permit a child or licensed minor to operate or ride a mini-motorbike or pocketbike on any public way or public property within the city.\n(5)   It is presumed that a parent allowed a child or licensed minor to operate or ride a motor assisted scooter, mini-motorbike or pocketbike in a restricted or prohibited area.\n(6)   It is unlawful for any adult or licensed minor to operate or ride a motor assisted scooter on any public way or public property for which the posted speed limit is more than 35 miles per hour. The motor assisted scooter may cross a road or a street at an intersection where the road or street to be crossed has a posted speed of more than 35 miles per hour.\n(7)   It is a defense to prosecution that the motor assisted scooter, mini-motorbike or pocketbike was not being operated upon public property or a public way at the time of the alleged offense.\n(b)    Penalty.\n(1)   A person who violates any provision of subsection (a), above, shall be guilty of a Class C misdemeanor and upon conviction shall be fined an amount not exceeding $500.00.\n(2)The purpose of this section is to promote safety and discourage the use of motor assisted scooters, mini-motorbikes and pocketbikes in unsafe areas. The courts may consider deferred dispositions under the TexasCode of Criminal Procedure, as it exists or may be amended, whenever the circumstances warrant deferred dispositions. (Ordinance 03-11-96, sec. 3, adopted 11/4/03; Ordinance 05-08-61, sec. 4, adopted 8/3/05)\n\n§ 90-62. Helmets required, penalty for failure to wear helmet.\n(a)    Helmet required.\n(1)   It is unlawful for any child or licensed minor to operate or ride a motor assisted scooter unless the child or licensed minor is wearing a helmet.\n(2)   It is unlawful for a parent to allow or permit a child or licensed minor to operate or ride a motor assisted scooter unless the child or licensed minor is wearing a helmet.\n(3)   It is presumed that a parent allowed a child or licensed minor to operate or ride a motor assisted scooter without wearing a helmet.\n(4)   It is a defense to prosecution that the motor assisted scooter was not being operated upon public property or a public way at the time of the alleged offense.\n(b)    Penalty.\n(1)   A person who violates any provision of subsection (a), above, requiring helmets, shall be guilty of a Class C misdemeanor and upon conviction shall be fined an amount not exceeding $50.00 upon the first conviction and an amount not exceeding $100.00 upon the second and each subsequent conviction.\n(2)   The municipal court shall dismiss a charge against a child, licensed minor and/or parent for a first offense under subsection (a) upon receiving proof that:\na.    The defendant acquired a helmet for the child or licensed minor who was operating or riding the motor assisted scooter in violation of subsection (a); and\nb.    The defendant acquired the helmet on or before the tenth day after receiving the citation of the violation.\n(3)   If the charge against a person is dismissed under subsection (b)(2), a later conviction for a violation of subsection (a) shall be considered a second or subsequent conviction for purposes of subsection (b)(1).\n(4)The purpose of this section is to promote safety and encourage the use of helmets. The courts may consider deferred dispositions under the Texas Code of Criminal Procedure, as it exists or may be amended, whenever the circumstances warrant deferred dispositions. (Ordinance 03-11-96, sec. 4, adopted 11/4/03; Ordinance 05-08-61, sec. 5, adopted 8/3/05)", summary:"Defines motor-assisted scooters, mini-motorbikes/pocket bikes, and related terms (cross-referencing state Transportation Code definitions), sets restrictions on where children and licensed minors may operate them, and requires helmets for children and licensed minors operating a motor-assisted scooter, with stated penalties for violations.", street:["A 'licensed minor' (16-17 with a valid motorcycle/vehicle license) is treated differently from a 'child' under 18 without one — check which category applies before charging.","Helmet and location restrictions are two independent violations — a child riding without a helmet in a permitted location is still a separate violation from riding in a restricted location.","Terms are defined by cross-reference to Transportation Code §§ 551.301 and 551.351 — use the state definitions to confirm the device qualifies."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 90-83 – 90-84", name:"Parking Regulations; Presumption of Registered Owner", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Penalty via posted/adopted parking regulations — see specific signage or ordinance", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 90-83. Parking limits and regulations. Regulations concerning parking, including but not limited to specified locations, conditions and time limits, shall be as established from time to time by ordinance. Such regulations in effect on the date of adoption of this Code are ratified, reaffirmed, and reserved from repeal.\n\n§ 90-84. Presumption. In a prosecution for an offense under this article involving the stopping, standing, or parking of an unattended motor vehicle, it is presumed that the registered owner of the vehicle is the person who stopped, stood, or parked the vehicle at the time and place the offense occurred.", summary:"Parking locations, conditions, and time limits are set from time to time by ordinance and posted signage, rather than stated in one fixed section. In any parking prosecution involving an unattended vehicle, the registered owner is presumed to be the person who parked it.", street:["This section is a pointer, not a fixed rule — always check current posted signage or the specific parking ordinance for the actual limit in force at that location.","The registered-owner presumption means you don't need to identify the driver at the time of the violation to cite an unattended vehicle — the registration is enough to shift the burden."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 90-223", name:"Commercial Truck Routes — Unlawful Acts and Exemptions", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Penalty not stated in this section — see general Traffic Code penalty provision", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 90-223. Unlawful acts/exemptions.\n(a)     It shall be unlawful to operate a commercial truck on any road, street or highway in the city except upon the following described roads, streets and highways located in the city: Street Segment                                 Extent FM 423                                         Entire city limits Spring Creek Parkway                           From Southbound SH 121 Frontage Road to Town and Country Boulevard Dallas Parkway                                 Entire city limits Frisco Street                                  Main Street to Eldorado Parkway Parkwood Drive                                 From Eagan Way to Stonebrook Parkway Preston Road (SH 289)                          Entire city limits Independence Parkway                           From Southbound SH 121 Frontage Road to Lebanon Road 3.    Editor's Note-Ordinance 10-02-09, Secs. 2-7, Adopted Feb. 2, 2010, Repealed The Former Art. VIII, Secs. 2-221-2-225, And Enacted A New Art. VIII As Set Out Herein. The Former Art. VIII Pertained To Commercial Truck Routes And Derived From: Ordinance 08-09-79, Secs. 2-6, 9-2-2008. Street Segment                              Extent Custer Road (FM 2478)                       Entire city limits US 380                                      Entire city limits Eldorado Parkway (FM 2934)                  From FM 423 to Dallas Parkway Eldorado Parkway                            From Dallas Parkway to Preston Road All Stars Avenue                            From Frisco Street to N. County Road Main Street (FM 3537)                       Preston Road to Custer Road (FM 2478) Main Street                                 Dallas Parkway to Frisco Street Stonebrook Parkway                          From Dallas Parkway to Preston Road (SH 289) Lebanon Road                                From Independence Parkway to Southbound SH 121 Frontage Road Southbound SH 121 Frontage Road Entire city limits\n(b)    The provisions of this section shall not apply to:\n(1)   Emergency vehicles operating in response to any emergency call;\n(2)   A vehicle traveling to or from areas served directly by the roads, streets and/or highways listed in this section for the purpose of providing repair or maintenance service or loading or unloading goods, wares or merchandise, provided such vehicle is operated over the shortest possible route, and the operator of such vehicle has in his immediate possession evidence of the local destination and point of origin;\n(3)   An owner and/or operator of a commercial truck driving to and from his residence;\n(4)   Commercial trucks owned and/or operated by and/or on behalf of a governmental entity, a public utility and/or any contractor or materialman, while engaged in the repair, maintenance or construction of roads, streets and/or highways, and/or road, street and/or highway improvements and/or utilities within the city;\n(5)   Commercial trucks owned and/or operated by and/or on behalf of a governmental entity while engaging in and/or performing official, authorized government-related business; and\n(6) Commercial trucks operating upon a city or state officially designated detour. (Ordinance 10-02-09, sec. 5, adopted 2/2/10)", summary:"Unlawful to operate a commercial truck on any city road, street, or highway except on the specifically designated truck-route streets listed in this section, subject to exemptions for emergency vehicles, local deliveries/service by the shortest route with proof of origin/destination, residents driving to/from their own residence, and government/utility/contractor vehicles performing authorized work.", street:["Check the current designated truck-route list in the full text before citing — the routes are specific named street segments, not 'any major road.'","The local-delivery exemption requires the driver to have proof of origin and destination in hand and to be using the shortest route — verify both before writing a citation.","A resident driving a commercial truck to or from their own home is exempt outright."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 90-112 – 90-113", name:"Truck, Trailer, Bus, Semi-Trailer and Commercial Vehicle Parking Prohibited", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Class C misdemeanor — fine up to $500; separate offense each calendar day; vehicle removal after one prior notice", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 90-112. Definitions. Bus, Motor vehicle, Semi-trailer, Trailer, Truck, and Truck tractor are defined by cross-reference to the Texas Transportation Code § 541.201, as amended (a \"light truck\" under § 541.201(7) is excluded from \"Truck\"). Commercial vehicle means every truck-tractor, road tractor, semitrailer, bus, drivable construction equipment, truck or trailer or any other motor vehicle that transports passengers or property with a rated carrying capacity of two (2) tons or more according to the manufacturer's classification; it does not include vehicles carrying or designed to carry fewer than ten (10) passengers, motor homes, recreational vehicles, or vehicles used exclusively to transport personal possessions or family members for nonbusiness purposes.\n\n§ 90-113. Truck, trailer, bus, semi-trailer and commercial vehicle parking prohibited.\n(a) It shall be unlawful for any owner or person in control of a truck, trailer, bus, semi-trailer or commercial vehicle to leave, park or stand, or to permit the leaving, parking or standing of, such truck, trailer, bus, semi-trailer or commercial vehicle, on any public street, highway, alley, parkway, boulevard, right-of-way or other property owned or controlled by any unit of government. It is an affirmative defense to an enforcement action under this section if a person leaves, parks or stands, or permits the leaving, parking or standing of, a truck, trailer, bus, semi-trailer or commercial vehicle in such locations under the following circumstances:\n(1) Trucks, trailers, buses, semi-trailers or commercial vehicles owned or operated by or on behalf of a governmental entity, a public utility or any contractor or materialman thereof, while engaged in the repair, maintenance or construction of improvements to public streets, highways, alleys, parkways, boulevards or rights-of-way or utilities within the city;\n(2) Trucks, trailers, buses, semi-trailers or commercial vehicles owned or operated by or on behalf of a governmental entity while engaging in or performing official, authorized government-related business;\n(3) Passenger buses taking on or discharging passengers at an approved bus stop;\n(4) A truck, trailer, bus, semi-trailer or commercial vehicle parked in a loading zone for the purpose of loading or unloading freight or merchandise to a lawfully zoned business;\n(5) A truck, trailer, bus, semi-trailer or commercial vehicle parked for the purpose of delivering or picking up merchandise to or from a specific designated location or loading or unloading personal property to or from a specific designated location that shall not exceed three (3) hours in any case;\n(6) A truck, trailer, bus, semi-trailer or commercial vehicle experiencing a mechanical defect making it unsafe or impossible to proceed, for such period of time as emergency repairs are made or, if repairs cannot be made within three (3) hours, until a tow truck arrives;\n(7) A truck, trailer, bus, semi-trailer or commercial vehicle owned by a commercial establishment that is legally parked on the street, highway, alley, parkway, boulevard or right-of-way adjacent to where the establishment is located, and not in violation of any signage or other ordinance of the city governing stopping, standing and parking;\n(8) A truck, trailer, bus, semi-trailer or commercial vehicle legally parked adjacent to a building construction site, not in violation of any signage or other ordinance of the city governing stopping, standing or parking, where the construction site has no room to accommodate the vehicle and only while the vehicle is actively engaged in construction activities;\n(9) A vehicle parked on a street, highway, alley, parkway, boulevard or right-of-way in a manner and at a time specified by the city manager, or his or her designee, through the issuance of an approved right-of-way permit and/or traffic control plan; or\n(10) A vehicle parked on a street, highway, alley, parkway, boulevard or right-of-way in a manner made lawful under this article or other law.\n(b) It shall be unlawful for any owner or person in control of a truck, trailer, bus, semi-trailer or commercial vehicle to leave, park or stand, or to permit the leaving, parking or standing of such vehicle, on any vacant lot.\n(c) The city manager, or his/her designee, may temporarily suspend the restrictions imposed by this section in order to accommodate special events held within the city.\n(d) It shall be unlawful for any person to park a truck, trailer, bus, semi-trailer or commercial vehicle in violation of this section. Any violation of any provision of this section, as it exists or may be amended, is a class C misdemeanor. An offense under this section carries a penalty in the form of a fine in an amount not exceeding five hundred dollars ($500.00). A violation of any provision of this section shall constitute a separate violation for each calendar day in which it occurs.\n(e) In addition to any penalty or other remedy found in this section, any truck, trailer, bus, semi-trailer or commercial vehicle that is left, parked or found standing in violation of this section may be removed by or on an order of a city law enforcement officer or the city manager or his or her designee provided that the owner or driver of the vehicle has been given at least one previous notice or citation for parking such vehicle in violation of this section. The owner shall be responsible for the payment of any fees incurred for the towing and/or storage of said vehicle.", summary:"Prohibits parking, standing, or leaving a truck, trailer, bus, semi-trailer, or commercial vehicle on any public street or government-controlled property, subject to ten affirmative defenses (government/utility/contractor work, government business, approved bus stops, loading zones, deliveries not over three hours, mechanical breakdowns, establishment-adjacent legal parking, construction-site parking, permitted right-of-way parking, and otherwise-lawful parking). Class C misdemeanor, up to a $500 fine, with each calendar day a separate offense. A vehicle in violation may be towed, but only after the owner or driver has received at least one prior notice or citation for the same violation.", street:["\"Commercial vehicle\" turns on a two-ton rated carrying capacity — a large pickup or box truck under that threshold is not covered; verify the manufacturer's rating before citing.","The ten affirmative defenses are decision points, not afterthoughts: a delivery under three hours, a genuine breakdown, or establishment-adjacent legal parking each defeats the charge.","Towing requires a prior notice or citation for the same vehicle and violation — a first-time offender can be cited but not towed under this section.","Each calendar day is a separate offense, which matters for chronic overnight commercial parking in neighborhoods."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 90-148 – 90-154", name:"Recreational Vehicle Parking (Residential, Obstruction, School Zones)", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Misdemeanor — fine up to $500; each continuing day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"Note: in the source PDF's two-column export the subsection bodies below were shifted one heading off; they are reassembled here to match each section title and the sequential adopting ordinance sections (Ordinance 00-05-14, secs. 3–9).\n\n§ 90-148. Definitions. \"On-street parking permit\" means written governmental permission authorized by the chief of police (or designee) to park or store a recreational vehicle on a public street within a residential zoning district for a temporary period not to exceed 48 hours prior to a trip or 24 hours following a trip. \"Recreational vehicle\" means any vehicular-type portable structure without permanent foundation, which can be towed, hauled or driven and is primarily designed to serve as temporary living accommodations for recreational, camping or travel use, including but not limited to travel trailers, camping trailers, converted buses and self-propelled motorhomes. \"Visitor on-street parking permit\" means like permission for a visitor from outside Collin/Denton County, not to exceed five days.\n\n§ 90-149. Restricted areas and times.\n(a) It shall be unlawful for any person to park or stand or to allow any recreational vehicle to park or stand upon any public street, highway, alley or public right-of-way between any street and alley within any part of the city classified by the city's Comprehensive Zoning Ordinance No. 93-07-11, or as amended, as a single-family dwelling district, two-family dwelling district, or multifamily dwelling district at any time.\n(b) This section shall not prevent the parking, operating and/or standing of the above-described vehicles and/or trailers upon any public street, highway or alley in any such zones or areas for the purpose of expeditiously loading and unloading passengers, freight or merchandise, or the expeditious delivery of a service or product.\n(c) This section shall not apply to recreational vehicles that have obtained an on-street parking permit in accordance with sections 90-151 and 90-152.\n\n§ 90-150. Parking not to obstruct traffic.\n(a) No person shall park any vehicle upon a public street, alley or highway in a manner or under such conditions as to leave available less than 12 feet of the width of the roadway for free movement of vehicular traffic.\n(b) No person shall park any vehicle upon a street adjacent to a driveway in such a manner or under such conditions as to leave available less than three feet of roadway between the vehicle and the point where the curve return of the driveway connects with the curb.\n\n§ 90-151. School zones. It shall be unlawful to park a recreational vehicle on a public street in a school zone during school hours when school is in session. This section shall not apply to the parking of such vehicles for such time as is actually necessary to load or unload passengers.\n\n§ 90-152. On-street parking permits.\n(a) It shall be an affirmative defense to prosecution for parking or storing a recreational vehicle on public streets within areas zoned for residential uses if a valid \"on-street parking permit\" has been issued to the owner or operator of said vehicle and parking or storage of the vehicle in no way violates any other pertinent state statute, City Code, ordinance, section or provision.\n(b) The chief of police shall have sole authority to issue, deny, revoke or extend any on-street parking permit.\n(c) No more than four on-street parking permits may be issued per calendar year for the same address or street location, unless otherwise approved by the chief of police.\n(d) A \"visitor on-street parking permit\" may only be issued to the host property owner for the exclusive use of visitors from outside of Collin/Denton County, for a maximum of five days.\n\n§ 90-154. Penalty provision. Any person, firm, corporation or business entity violating this division shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction thereof shall be fined a sum not exceeding $500.00. Each continuing day's violation under this division shall constitute a separate offense.", summary:"Governs recreational-vehicle parking on public streets: RVs may not park or stand in single-family, two-family, or multifamily residential districts at any time (loading/unloading and permit holders excepted); no vehicle may be parked so as to leave less than 12 feet of roadway for traffic or less than three feet beside a driveway curb return; and RVs may not park in a school zone during school hours. A valid on-street parking permit (48 hours before / 24 hours after a trip, issued by the chief of police) is an affirmative defense to the residential-parking charge. Division penalty is a misdemeanor up to $500, with each continuing day a separate offense.", street:["The residential-district RV prohibition applies \"at any time\" — no posted sign is required; zoning classification is the element, so confirm the district before citing.","A valid on-street parking permit is an affirmative defense, not an exemption you verify at the curb — check whether one was issued (chief of police holds sole authority) before writing it.","The 12-foot roadway and 3-foot driveway-clearance rules apply to any vehicle, not just RVs, and are useful on obstruction and blocked-driveway complaints.","Loading or unloading passengers, freight, or merchandise is expressly carved out of both the residential and school-zone prohibitions."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 90-159, 90-164, 90-165", name:"Special Event Parking — Permit Required; Offenses", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Misdemeanor — fine up to $500; each day and each vehicle a separate offense; applies only within the limited access zones", lvlClass:"m", text:"This division applies only to property within the special-event \"limited access zones\" defined in § 90-157 (administrative permit-operation requirements in §§ 90-160 – 90-163 are omitted here).\n\n§ 90-159. Accessory special event parking permits required.\n(a) No person shall accept any form of consideration from another person in exchange for allowing that person to park a vehicle on a parcel of land unless:\n(1) An accessory special event parking permit has been issued by the administrator for that parcel of land where the vehicle is to be parked; or\n(2) A certificate of occupancy has been issued by the city expressly allowing commercial parking or an overnight parking facility on that parcel of land where the vehicle is to be parked and: a. the vehicle is parked only on a paved parking surface with marked parking spaces; and b. one vehicle is parked per marked parking space.\n(b) Notwithstanding anything to the contrary, if a vehicle is to be parked in more than one parking space, is parked outside of marked spaces, or spaces are used for tailgating, parking of recreational vehicles, or camping activities, a special event parking permit is required. Also, if a vehicle will be parked on a portion of a parcel of land that is unpaved, a special event parking permit shall always be required.\n\n§ 90-164. Offenses.\n(a) A person commits an offense if that person or their agent:\n(1) Submits false documents, or otherwise makes a false statement of a material fact on an application for any permit submitted under this division;\n(2) Provides special event parking for any vehicle during a special event in violation of this division; each vehicle charged a fee for parking on a parking area during a special event in violation of this division constitutes a separate offense;\n(3) Violates any other provision of this division.\n(b) In the prosecution of an offense under this division, it is presumed that: (1) the applicant and the person named as responsible for operation of the parking area are responsible for parking violations under this division; (2) the owner of the property is responsible for parking violations under this division; and (3) all vehicles parked on property during a special event have been charged a fee for parking if, during a special event, a sign is present indicating parking is available for a fee, or, absent such a sign, if there is signage in the vicinity indicating parking is available for a fee and individuals are directing cars onto the property to park.\n\n§ 90-165. Penalty. An offense under any provision of this division is a misdemeanor punishable by a fine not to exceed $500.00. Each day that a violation is permitted to exist shall constitute a separate offense. Each vehicle parked on a property without a valid accessory special event parking permit shall constitute a separate offense.", summary:"Within the special-event limited access zones, no one may charge a fee to park vehicles on a parcel without an accessory special event parking permit (or a certificate of occupancy expressly allowing commercial parking, with vehicles on paved marked spaces, one per space). Offenses include submitting false permit-application information, providing special-event parking in violation of the division, and violating any other provision. Evidentiary presumptions tie liability to the applicant, the named operator, and the property owner, and presume a fee was charged where fee-parking signage is present. Misdemeanor up to $500, with each day and each vehicle a separate offense.", street:["This targets pop-up paid parking on private lots during events — the offense is charging a fee to park without the required permit, not the parking itself.","The division only applies inside the defined limited access zones (§§ 90-157/158); confirm the property is within a zone before citing.","Each vehicle parked without a valid permit and each day are separate offenses, so a single unpermitted event lot can generate many counts.","Presumptions do the heavy lifting: fee-parking signage plus cars being directed onto the property presumes a fee was charged."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 90-171 – 90-172", name:"Prohibited or Restricted Parking Designated by Signs or Markings; Business Reservation of Public Parking", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Civil parking offense (Transportation Code ch. 682) — civil penalty up to $500; adjudicated administratively", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 90-171. Designation and marking of parking spaces and areas where parking is prohibited or restricted.\n(a) Definitions. \"Parking enforcement officer\" means a city employee whose duties include enforcement of parking violations under this division. \"Public parking places\" means places where a motor vehicle can be legally parked along a public roadway or on city property, whether striped or not, including spaces in public lots and garages, around city-owned buildings, and on the side of public streets where allowed by state law. Parking is never allowed along type A or B thoroughfares as defined by the city's engineering standards.\n(b) Survey. Upon a survey performed by the traffic engineer and approved by the city manager or designee, the traffic engineer shall cause public parking places in which parking is prohibited or limited to be maintained and marked off. All such spaces or areas shall be clearly indicated by appropriate signs or markings.\n(c) Signs or markings. In areas designated as prohibited or limited parking areas, public parking places may be prohibited or limited in any manner consistent with the traffic engineer's survey. The area shall be designated with clearly distinguished markings or signs at both ends of the prohibited or limited area and at reasonable intervals, indicating what vehicles may park there, for how long, and any other restrictions.\n(d) Applicable periods. Any prohibition or time limit shall apply on such days and hours as prescribed by the traffic engineer and approved by the city manager or designee.\n(e) Violations. It shall be unlawful for any person to park a vehicle in violation of this section. Any violation by a person, firm, entity or corporation of any provision of this division, as it exists or may be amended, is a civil offense, pursuant to chapter 682 of the Texas Transportation Code. A civil offense under this division carries a civil penalty in the form of a fine in a sum not exceeding five hundred dollars ($500.00). Each continuing day's violation under this division shall constitute a separate offense. Payment of fines will be made to the city's police department or its designee for parking violations under this division.\n(f) Presumptions. Whenever any vehicle stands in a public parking space in violation of this section, such fact shall be prima facie evidence that the vehicle has been parked illegally and that the registered owner and/or operator did knowingly cause, allow or permit such vehicle to be parked in such location. A registered vehicle owner is not liable if the operator assumes responsibility, or if the owner files an affidavit with supporting documentation establishing that the vehicle was sold or stolen before the violation, or that the registered owner is deceased and no operator has been served or claimed responsibility.\n\n§ 90-172. Prohibited reservation of public parking place by business. It shall be unlawful for a business to reserve a public parking place for the exclusive use of its customers, unless said business is granted an exception by the city. This exception must be in writing from the city manager or his/her designee, must be maintained by the business, contained on the premises, and provided when requested by city employees.", summary:"Parking contrary to signs or pavement markings established under the traffic engineer's survey is a civil offense under Chapter 682 of the Texas Transportation Code, carrying a civil penalty up to $500 with each continuing day a separate offense, adjudicated administratively rather than as a criminal charge. A registered-owner presumption applies, rebuttable by the operator assuming responsibility or by affidavit showing prior sale, theft, or the owner's death. Separately, a business may not reserve a public parking place for its customers' exclusive use without a written city exception kept on the premises.", street:["These are civil parking penalties adjudicated through the administrative hearing process (§ 90-174), not criminal citations — the disposition and burden differ from a Class C charge.","Enforceability depends on the signs or markings actually being posted at both ends and at intervals per the engineer's survey; a bare unmarked restriction is weak.","The registered-owner presumption lets you cite an unattended vehicle by plate, but the owner can rebut with a sale/theft/deceased affidavit.","A business roping off public parking for its own customers is itself unlawful absent a written city exception — ask to see the exception on the premises."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 90-175", name:"Reserved Parking — Temporary Events (Placard Required)", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Misdemeanor — fine up to $500; each continuing day a separate offense; towing authorized after citation", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 90-175. Temporary events.\n(a) Designation. The curbside parking spaces located on the south side of Hall of Fame Lane from Gridiron Road to a point one thousand (1,000) feet east of Gridiron Road, the east side of Gridiron Road from Hall of Fame Lane to a point six hundred (600) feet south of Hall of Fame Lane, and the west side of Gaylord Parkway from Hall of Fame Lane to a point five hundred (500) feet south of Hall of Fame Lane, as depicted in exhibit A to Ordinance 19-01-01, are hereby reserved for the parking of vehicles associated with temporary events that have displayed on the front windshield dash or other approved location an identification placard approved by the city manager or designated representative. As used in this section, \"temporary event\" means an event held at The Star that lasts no more than seven (7) consecutive days.\n(b) Violations. It is unlawful for any person to cause, allow or permit any vehicle registered in the name of or operated by such person to be parked in any space hereby reserved for temporary event parking under this section unless there is displayed on the front windshield dash of such vehicle or other approved location a valid identification placard approved by the city manager or designated representative.\n(c) Presumptions. Whenever any vehicle stands in a parking space reserved for temporary event parking under this section and such vehicle does not have a valid identification placard displayed as required, such fact shall be prima facie evidence that the vehicle has been parked illegally and that the registered owner and/or operator did knowingly cause, allow or permit such vehicle to be parked in such location.\n(d) Penalty. Any person who violates any provision of this section shall be guilty of a misdemeanor, and on conviction, shall be fined in an amount not exceeding five hundred dollars ($500.00). Each continuing day's violation shall constitute a separate offense.\n(e) Towing authorized. Upon determination that a vehicle is illegally parked in violation of any provision of this section, an authorized official, after issuance of a citation, may cause such illegally parked vehicle to be removed and stored at a vehicle storage facility at the registered owner's or operator's expense in accordance with other law.", summary:"Reserves specific curbside spaces near The Star (defined segments of Hall of Fame Lane, Gridiron Road, and Gaylord Parkway) for vehicles displaying a valid city-approved temporary-event placard; a \"temporary event\" is one at The Star lasting no more than seven consecutive days. Parking in a reserved space without a displayed valid placard is a misdemeanor up to $500, each day a separate offense, with a registered-owner presumption and authority to tow after a citation is issued.", street:["The offense is the missing placard, not the parking — look for a valid city-approved placard on the front dash before acting.","Applies only to the specifically described reserved segments near The Star; confirm the vehicle is in a designated reserved space.","Towing is authorized here after a citation is issued, without the prior-notice requirement that applies to commercial-vehicle parking."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 90-177 – 90-179", name:"Traffic-Control Devices; Driver Obedience", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Misdemeanor — fine up to $500", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 90-177. Traffic-control devices are authorized, placed or erected as provided.\n(a) The city manager, or designated representative, shall be authorized to place, erect and maintain such traffic control devices which he deems to be warranted in accordance with provisions or requirements of the \"Manual of Uniform Traffic-Control Devices\" or as may be required by ordinances of the city.\n(b) All existing traffic-control devices which have been placed or erected in general compliance with this article are hereby approved and ratified, and shall be considered as having been legally placed and/or erected.\n(c) Traffic-control devices which are determined by the city manager, or designated representative, or the city council, to be no longer needed for the safety or welfare of the citizens of the city may be caused to be removed.\n(d) All traffic-control devices authorized, placed, or erected by the state highway department on state highways are adopted by the city council.\n\n§ 90-178. Driver obedience to traffic signals. The driver of any vehicle shall obey the instructions of any official traffic-control device applicable thereto placed in accordance with this article, unless otherwise directed by a police officer.\n\n§ 90-179. Violation; penalty. Any person violating any of the provisions of this article shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction thereof, shall be fined in the sum not more than $500.00.", summary:"Authorizes the city to place and maintain official traffic-control devices consistent with the Texas MUTCD, ratifies existing devices as legally placed, and requires drivers to obey any official traffic-control device applicable to them unless directed otherwise by a police officer. Violation of the article is a misdemeanor punishable by a fine up to $500.", street:["This is the local-ordinance basis for a disobey-a-traffic-control-device charge; a device presumed legally placed under (b) forecloses the \"the sign wasn't valid\" defense.","A police officer's direction overrides the device — your directions to a driver control over a signal or sign.","Most signal and device offenses will be charged under the Transportation Code; this ordinance is the municipal alternative where that fits the situation."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 90-201 – 90-209", name:"Automated Red Light Enforcement (Photographic — Civil)", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Civil penalty $75 (plus $25 late) — automated, imposed by mail on the vehicle owner; not a criminal conviction", lvlClass:"p", text:"This is a civil, camera-based program administered by the police department; the notice, hearing, and appeal procedures (§§ 90-203 – 90-207) are administrative and are summarized rather than reproduced in full.\n\n§ 90-202. Imposition of civil penalty for violations.\n(a) The city council finds that a vehicle that proceeds into an intersection when the traffic control signal for that vehicle's direction of travel is emitting a steady red signal damages the public and is operated in violation of the instructions of that traffic-control signal.\n(b) Except as provided in subsection (c), the owner of a motor vehicle is liable for a civil penalty of $75.00 if, while facing only a steady red signal displayed by an electrically operated traffic-control signal located in the city, the vehicle is operated in violation of the instructions of that traffic-control signal, as specified by V.T.C.A., Transportation Code sec. 544.007(d).\n(c) An owner who fails to timely contest or pay the civil penalty shall be subject to a late payment penalty of $25.00.\n\n§ 90-204. Presumption. It is presumed that the owner of the motor vehicle committed the violation alleged in the notice of violation if the vehicle depicted in the recorded image belongs to the owner. The presumption is rebutted by evidence that the vehicle was being test driven, was rented or leased to another, or was owned by a person other than the one named in the notice.\n\n§ 90-208. Effect of liability; exclusion of civil remedy.\n(a) The imposition of a civil penalty under this article is not a conviction and may not be considered a conviction for any purpose.\n(b) The implementation of a photographic traffic signal enforcement system by the city under this article does not prohibit a peace officer from arresting a violator of V.T.C.A., Transportation Code sec. 544.007(d) as provided by V.T.C.A., Transportation Code ch. 543, if the peace officer personally witnesses the violation, or from issuing the violator a citation and notice to appear as provided by V.T.C.A., Transportation Code ch. 543.\n(c) The city may not impose a civil penalty under this article on the owner of a motor vehicle if the operator of the vehicle was arrested or was issued a citation and notice to appear by a peace officer for the same violation recorded by the system.\n(d) If the owner fails to timely pay the civil penalty: (1) an arrest warrant may not be issued for the owner; and (2) the imposition of the civil penalty may not be recorded on the owner's driving record.", summary:"A photographic red-light enforcement program: the registered owner of a vehicle that runs a steady red signal captured by the system is liable for a $75 civil penalty (plus a $25 late penalty), imposed by mailed notice and adjudicated administratively. It is expressly not a criminal conviction, carries no arrest warrant and no driving-record entry for nonpayment, and a registered-owner presumption applies (rebuttable by test-drive, rental/lease, or non-ownership). Critically, the program does not limit an officer who personally witnesses a red-light violation from arresting or citing under Transportation Code ch. 543 — but the city may not also impose the civil penalty for the same incident an officer has already cited.", street:["This is a civil, mail-based penalty on the vehicle owner — not something an officer issues on patrol, and nonpayment yields no warrant and no driving-record entry.","Your independent authority is preserved: if you personally witness the red-light violation you may cite or arrest under Transportation Code ch. 543 — and doing so blocks the civil camera penalty for that same incident.","Liability runs to the registered owner by presumption; a driver's identity at the time isn't required for the civil penalty."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 90-236 – 90-246", name:"Towing / Wrecker Regulations (Agreement, Dispatch, Reporting)", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Regulatory duties on wrecker operators — penalty not stated in this article; see the city's general penalty provision", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 90-238. Providing for non-consent towing by the city. No person shall provide wrecker service to the city without first executing an agreement therefore with the city. Provided, however, nothing in this section shall prohibit the city from utilizing the services of noncontract wreckers for towing services originating outside the corporate limits of the city.\n\n§ 90-242. Dispatch by police generally. It shall be unlawful for any wrecker operator or driver to proceed to the scene or site of a wreck, motor vehicle accident or collision, or follow any ambulance or police car which is traveling in response to a report of a wreck, motor vehicle accident or collision, unless such wrecker has been duly, legally dispatched to the scene or site by the city police department or has been requested to come to the scene by a party involved in the wreck, motor vehicle accident or collision.\n\n§ 90-244. Private property tows. A wrecker operator that intends to remove a motor vehicle from a parking facility in accordance with V.T.C.A., Transportation Code ch. 684 may not tow a motor vehicle to a vehicle storage facility more than 15 miles outside of the city corporate limits.\n\n§ 90-245. Tow truck operator and vehicle storage facility's duty to report after towing or accepting unauthorized vehicle. A tow truck operator towing a motor vehicle and a vehicle storage facility accepting a motor vehicle that is towed under this chapter shall, within 30 minutes after towing from the parking facility or receiving the motor vehicle, report to the city police department in which the parking facility is located: (1) a general description of the motor vehicle; (2) the state and number of the motor vehicle's license plate, if any; (3) the vehicle identification number of the motor vehicle, if it can be ascertained; (4) the location from which the motor vehicle was towed; and (5) the name and location of the vehicle storage facility where the motor vehicle is being stored. The report must be made by telephone or delivered personally or by facsimile.\n\n§ 90-246. Reports to city police department of towing pursuant to lienholder's request. When a wrecker operator tows a motor vehicle pursuant to a lienholder's request incident to a lawful repossession, the operator shall make a verbal report to the city police department within 30 minutes of picking up the motor vehicle, including the license plate number, the VIN, the year/make/model/color, the requesting lienholder's contact information, the wrecker's plate and driver's Texas driver's license number, and the tow origin, date/time, and storage location.", summary:"Regulates wrecker/tow operators in the city: no one may provide wrecker service to the city without a written agreement; a wrecker operator may not proceed to a wreck scene or chase an ambulance or police car responding to a wreck unless dispatched by Frisco PD or requested by a party to the wreck; private-property tows may not go to a storage facility more than 15 miles outside the city; and both non-consent tows (within 30 minutes of towing) and lienholder-repossession tows (within 30 minutes of pickup) must be reported to the police department with the vehicle and storage details.", street:["The dispatch rule (§ 90-242) is the patrol-relevant one: a wrecker that self-responds to a crash scene or follows a responding unit without dispatch or a party's request is acting unlawfully.","Repossession tows must be reported to PD within 30 minutes — the absence of a report is a red flag when a vehicle is reported \"stolen\" that was actually repossessed.","Private-property tows are capped at 15 miles outside city limits for the storage destination.","Penalty is not stated in this article; charge through the city's general penalty provision or the applicable Transportation Code chapter."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 90-255 – 90-257", name:"Operation of Golf Carts on Public Streets", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Operating conditions — penalty not stated in this article; see the city's general penalty provision", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 90-255. Definitions. \"Golf cart\" means a motor vehicle designed by the manufacturer primarily for transporting persons on a golf course. \"Public safety personnel\" means any employee or officer of a governmental law enforcement agency or the city fire department. \"Public street\" means a publicly-owned or dedicated road, street, drive, or other right-of-way for the use of vehicles within the corporate boundaries of the City of Frisco.\n\n§ 90-256. Golf carts permitted and restricted. A person, other than public safety personnel, may operate a golf cart on a public street if:\n(a) The maximum speed limit on the public street is 35 miles per hour or less;\n(b) The person has a valid drivers license;\n(c) The person maintains current financial responsibility for the golf cart, as required of other passenger vehicles in V.T.C.A., Texas Transportation Code sec. 601.051;\n(d) The person complies with all applicable federal, state, and local laws and ordinances;\n(e) The golf cart has the following equipment: (1) headlamps; (2) tail lamps; (3) reflectors; (4) parking brake; (5) mirrors; and (6) a slow-moving vehicle emblem; and\n(f) While the golf cart is in motion, the driver and every passenger in a golf cart is seated in a seat designed to hold passengers. No person may stand or ride in the lap of the driver and/or other passenger of a golf cart while it is moving.\n\n§ 90-257. Public safety personnel. Public safety personnel may operate a golf cart on any public street without any further restrictions when the golf cart is used in the performance of his/her duties.", summary:"A person (other than public-safety personnel on duty) may operate a golf cart on a public street only where the posted speed limit is 35 mph or less, the operator holds a valid driver's license and maintains financial responsibility, the cart is equipped with headlamps, tail lamps, reflectors, a parking brake, mirrors, and a slow-moving-vehicle emblem, and all occupants are seated in passenger seats while moving. Public-safety personnel operating in the performance of their duties are exempt from these restrictions.", street:["Each condition is a checkpoint: speed-limit ceiling of 35 mph, valid license, financial responsibility, the six equipment items, and everyone seated — a failure on any one is a basis to act.","The slow-moving-vehicle emblem and lighting are the equipment items most often missing on street-driven golf carts.","On-duty public-safety personnel are exempt; a golf cart used for personal errands is not.","Penalty is not stated in this article — charge through the city's general penalty provision."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 90-300 – 90-302", name:"Temporary Moratorium on Shared Mobility Services (Scooter/Bike Share)", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Operator prohibition during moratorium — removal and impoundment; $50 impound fee per device", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 90-300. Definitions and exclusions. An \"operator\" is any entity that began operating a shared mobility service in the city on or after December 1, 2018. A \"shared mobility service\" is any service that displays, offers, or places for rent on public property one or more GPS-equipped bicycles or tricycles, electric bicycles or tricycles, motor-assisted scooters, or other similar personal transportation devices that may be locked and unlocked with or without a docking station, and that began operating in the city on or after December 1, 2018. The article does not apply to a moped or motorcycle, a motorized mobility device, an electric personal assistive mobility device, or a neighborhood electric vehicle.\n\n§ 90-301. Temporary moratorium.\n(a) An immediate, temporary moratorium on shared mobility services in the city is hereby imposed until the date the city council adopts a new ordinance governing shared mobility services.\n(b) During the temporary moratorium, it shall be unlawful for any operator to park or place a bicycle or tricycle equipped with GPS, electric bicycle or tricycle, motor-assisted scooter or other similar personal transportation device on public property or other public area or in a manner that impedes access or ingress to, egress from or use of public property or other public area.\n\n§ 90-302. Removal and impoundment.\n(a) During the moratorium, the city may remove and impound any GPS-equipped bicycle or tricycle, electric bicycle or tricycle, motor-assisted scooter or other similar personal transportation device owned or controlled by a shared mobility services operator that is found in any public property or other public area within the city.\n(b) After impoundment, the city shall send a notice of impoundment via email or U.S. mail to the owner of the impounded property, if known or clearly ascertainable from external markings.\n(c) The owner of the impounded property shall be subject to an impoundment fee of fifty dollars ($50.00) per device. The impoundment fee shall be assessed against and collected from the owner as a condition of retrieval.\n(d) The city may dispose of an impounded device in a manner consistent with state law if the owner does not satisfy all conditions related to the impoundment within thirty (30) calendar days from the date of impoundment.", summary:"Imposes an ongoing temporary moratorium on shared mobility services (dockless scooter- and bike-share) until the city council adopts a governing ordinance. During the moratorium it is unlawful for an operator to park or place shared-mobility devices on public property or where they impede public access, and the city may remove and impound any operator-owned device found on public property, charging a $50-per-device impound fee and disposing of unclaimed devices after 30 days. The prohibition runs against operators, not individual riders, and excludes mopeds, motorcycles, and certain mobility/assistive devices.", street:["The prohibition runs against the shared-mobility operator (the company), not a private individual riding their own scooter.","The remedy is removal and impoundment of the devices with a $50-per-device fee — not a rider citation.","Confirm the device belongs to a shared-mobility operator (external markings/branding) before impounding; personally owned and certain assistive devices are excluded."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 1-2", name:"Definitions and Rules of Construction (Code-Wide)", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["general"], level:"Definitions / rules of construction — reference; not an offense. Applies across the entire Frisco code.", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 1-2. Definitions and rules of construction.\nIn the construction of this Code and of all ordinances and resolutions adopted by the city council, the following rules shall be observed, unless such construction would be inconsistent with the manifest intent of the city council:\nGenerally. Words shall be construed in their common and usual significance, unless the contrary is clearly indicated.\nBoards, committees, commissions, officers, employees, and departments. Any reference to city boards, committees, commissions, officers, employees or departments shall be construed to mean the boards, committees, commissions, officers, employees or departments, respectively, of the City of Frisco, Texas.\nCharter. The term \"Charter\" shall mean the Charter of the City of Frisco, Texas, as printed in this volume.\nCity. The term \"city\" shall mean the City of Frisco in the Counties of Collin and Denton, in the State of Texas.\nCity council. Whenever the term \"city council\" is used, it shall mean the city council of Frisco, Texas.\nCode. The term \"Code\" means this Code of Ordinances, City of Frisco, Texas.\nComputation of time. Whenever a notice is required to be given or an act to be done a certain length of time before any proceeding shall be had, the day on which such notice is given or such act is done shall not be counted in computing the time, but the day on which such proceeding is to be had shall be counted unless it is a Saturday, Sunday, or a legal holiday.\nCounty. The term \"county\" shall mean the Counties of Collin and Denton, Texas.\nDelegation of authority. Whenever a section or provision appears requiring the head of a department or some other city officer or employee to do some act or perform some duty, it shall be construed to authorize the head of the department or other officer or employee to designate, delegate and authorize subordinates to perform the required act or perform the duty, unless the terms of the provision or section specify otherwise.\nGender. A word importing the masculine gender only shall extend and be applied to females and to firms, partnerships, associations, corporations, and other legal entities, as well as to males.\nHighway. The term \"highway\" shall include any street, alley, highway, avenue, public place or square, bridge, viaduct, tunnel, underpass, overpass, and causeway within the city, dedicated or devoted to public use.\nJoint authority. Words purporting to give authority to three or more officers or other persons shall be construed as giving such authority to a majority of such officers or other persons, unless it is otherwise declared.\nMonth. The term \"month\" shall mean a calendar month.\nNumber. Any word importing the singular number shall include the plural, and any word importing the plural number shall include the singular.\nOath. The term \"oath\" shall be construed to include an affirmation in all cases in which, by law, an affirmation may be substituted for an oath, and in such cases the terms \"swear\" and \"sworn\" shall be equivalent to the terms \"affirm\" and \"affirmed.\"\nOr; and. The term \"or\" may be read \"and\", and the term \"and\" may be read \"or\", if the sense requires it.\nOwner. The term \"owner,\" applied to a building or land, shall include any part owner, joint owner, tenant in common, tenant in partnership, joint tenant or tenant by the entirety of the whole or of a part of such building or land.\nPerson. The term \"person\" shall extend and be applied to associations, corporations, firms, partnerships, other legal entities and bodies politic and corporate, as well as to individuals.\nPreceding; following. The terms \"preceding\" and \"following\" mean next before and next after, respectively.\nResidence. The term \"residence\" means domicile that is one's fixed home and fixed place of habitation to which one intends to return after any temporary absence. It is determined by common-law rules, as enunciated by courts of the state, except as otherwise provided. A person does not lose his residency status by leaving to go to another place for temporary purposes only; a person does not acquire residency status in a place by coming for temporary purposes, within the intention of making that place the person's home. A person who is an inmate in a penal institution, or who is involuntarily placed in a hospital or eleemosynary institution does not, under such circumstances, acquire residence at the place where the institution is located.\nShall. The term \"shall\" always means mandatory and never means permissive.\nSidewalk. The term \"sidewalk\" shall mean any portion of the street between the curb, or the lateral line of the roadway and the adjacent property line, intended the use of pedestrians.\nSignature; subscription. The terms \"signature\" and \"subscription\" shall include a mark when a person cannot write.\nState. The term \"state\" shall be construed to mean the State of Texas.\nStreet. The term \"street\" shall include any highway, alley, street, avenue, public place or square, bridge, viaduct, underpass, overpass, tunnel and causeway in the city, dedicated or devoted to public use.\nTense. Words used in the past or present tense include the future, as well as the past and present.\nTex. Admin. Code. This term refer to the Texas Administrative Code.\nVernon's Ann. Civ. St. The term \"Vernon's Ann. Civ. St.\" means the latest edition or supplement or Vernon's Annotated Civil Statutes.\nV.T.C.A. The term \"V.T.C.A.\" refers to the latest edition or supplement of Vernon's Texas Code Annotated.\nWritten; in writing. The terms \"written\" and \"in writing\" shall be construed to include any representation of words, letters or figures, whether by printing or otherwise.\nYear. The term \"year\" shall mean a calendar year. (Ordinance 99-06-13, sec. 2, adopted 6/1/99)", summary:"The code-wide definitions and rules of construction that govern every Frisco ordinance unless a specific chapter defines a term itself. Notable officer-relevant terms: \"person\" (includes corporations, partnerships, associations, and other entities, not just individuals); \"highway\" and \"street\" (both broad — any street, alley, avenue, public square, bridge, viaduct, underpass, overpass, tunnel, or causeway dedicated to public use); \"sidewalk\" (the portion between the curb/roadway edge and the property line); \"shall\" (always mandatory, never permissive); \"residence\" (fixed home and place of habitation); and \"computation of time\" (exclude the first day, count the last unless a weekend or legal holiday).", street:["These definitions apply across the entire Frisco code — when any other ordinance uses \"person,\" \"street,\" \"highway,\" \"sidewalk,\" or \"shall,\" this section supplies the meaning unless that ordinance defines the term itself.","\"Person\" includes corporations, partnerships, associations, and other legal entities — not just individuals — so entity liability under a city ordinance traces back to this definition.","\"Highway\" and \"street\" are both defined broadly to reach alleys, avenues, public squares, bridges, underpasses, and overpasses dedicated to public use; \"sidewalk\" is the portion between the curb or roadway edge and the property line.","\"Shall\" is always mandatory, never permissive — useful when an ordinance duty is disputed. \"Computation of time\" excludes the first day and counts the last, unless it falls on a Saturday, Sunday, or legal holiday."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 1-12", name:"General Penalty (Code-Wide Default)", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["general"], level:"Misdemeanor — code-wide default where no specific penalty is stated: up to $2,000 (fire/safety/zoning/public health/sanitation) or up to $500 (all others); capped at the state-law maximum; each day a separate offense.", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 1-12. General penalty.\nWhenever in this Code or in any city ordinance or in any rule, regulation or order promulgated by any city officer or agency under authority vested in such officer or agency any act is prohibited or is made or declared to be unlawful or an offense or a misdemeanor, where no specific penalty is provided, the violation of any provision of this Code or of any specific ordinance, regulation, rule or order that governs or regulates fire, safety, zoning, public health or sanitation, including the dumping of refuse, shall be punished by a fine not exceeding $2,000.00. The violation of any other provision of this Code or any other ordinance, rule, regulation or order shall be punished by fine not exceeding $500.00, unless otherwise specifically stated in this Code. If the maximum penalty provided by this Code for any offense is greater than the maximum penalty for such violation provided by state law, the maximum penalty for such violation shall be that accorded under state law. Except where provided otherwise in this Code, each day an offense shall continue shall constitute a separate offense.", summary:"The code-wide default penalty for any Frisco ordinance violation that does not state its own penalty: a fine up to $2,000 for violations governing fire, safety, zoning, public health, or sanitation (including refuse dumping), and up to $500 for all other violations. If the city's maximum would exceed the maximum state law provides for the same violation, the state-law maximum controls. Each day a violation continues is a separate offense unless the code provides otherwise.", street:["This is the fallback penalty that every \"penalty not stated in this section\" entry in the guide points to — the two tiers are up to $2,000 (fire, safety, zoning, public health, or sanitation) and up to $500 (everything else).","The state-law cap is a real limit: if a city violation's maximum here would exceed what Texas law allows for the same violation, the state maximum controls — don't cite a fine above the state ceiling.","Each day a continuing violation persists is a separate offense unless a specific section says otherwise."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances § 1-13", name:"Violations of Code or Ordinance; Culpable Mental State", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["general"], level:"Rule of construction — reference; not itself an offense. Governs whether a culpable mental state must be proven for a city ordinance offense.", lvlClass:"p", text:"Note: in the source PDF's two-column export, subsection (a) was displaced under the § 1-15 heading; the subsections are reassembled here in their correct § 1-13 order.\n\n§ 1-13. Violations of Code or ordinance; culpable mental state.\n(a) In any prosecution filed under a provision of this Code or any ordinance of the city which expressly requires proof that the actor engaged in conduct intentionally, knowingly, recklessly, or with criminal negligence, then a person does not commit an offense unless he is shown to have engaged in such conduct as the definition of the offense requires.\n(b) Whenever in this Code or in any ordinance of the city an act or a failure to act is prohibited, or is made or declared to be unlawful, or an offense, or a misdemeanor, and such provision does not expressly require proof of a culpable mental state, proof of a culpable mental state is not required for conviction of such offense, it being the intent of the city council to dispense with the requirement of any culpable mental state in prosecutions filed under such provisions of this Code and other ordinances of the city; provided, however, that if such offense is punishable by a fine exceeding the amount authorized by V.T.C.A., Penal Code sec. 12.23, a person does not commit such offense unless he is shown to have recklessly engaged in such conduct as the definition of the offense requires.\n(c) Proof of a higher degree of culpability than that charged constitutes proof of the culpability charged.", summary:"For city ordinance offenses: if a provision expressly requires a culpable mental state (intentional, knowing, reckless, or criminal negligence), that mental state must be proven. If a provision does not expressly require one, no culpable mental state is required for conviction — except that where the offense is punishable by a fine exceeding the amount authorized by Texas Penal Code § 12.23, the person must be shown to have acted at least recklessly. Proof of a higher degree of culpability than charged satisfies the charged culpability.", street:["Most Frisco ordinance offenses are effectively strict liability — no intent needs to be proven unless the specific section spells out a mental state.","The exception is higher-fine offenses: where the fine can exceed the Penal Code § 12.23 ceiling, the city must show at least recklessness. This tracks the state-law limit on strict-liability fines.","This is the rule behind the \"culpable mental state is not required\" language you'll see inside individual chapters (e.g., the Animals article § 14-21(e) and the Sex Offender Residency article § 54-173(b))."] },
  { ord:"Frisco Code of Ordinances §§ 2-19, 2-76", name:"Removal from Public Meetings; Resisting Removal Unlawful", city:"Frisco, TX", cats:["publicconduct"], kw:"city council meeting board commission committee disrupt disruption remove removal resist trespass presiding officer public comment", level:"Offense (resisting removal) — no penalty stated in-section; defaults to the § 1-12 general penalty (up to $500). Also authorizes a peace officer to remove a disruptive person on the presiding officer's order.", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 2-19 governs conduct at City Council meetings; § 2-76 contains identical rules for board, commission, and committee meetings. The officer-relevant subsections (§ 2-19(4)–(6), mirrored verbatim in § 2-76(4)–(6)) are reproduced below.\n\n§ 2-19. Rules of procedure for the conduct of public testimony at City Council meetings.\n(4) Members of the public shall not engage in any of the following in the meeting room during a City Council meeting:\n(A) Any conduct that impedes or disrupts the orderly conduct of the meeting, including shouting, unruly behavior, distracting side conversations, speaking out when another person is talking, booing, hissing, foot stomping, parading, singing, displaying a prop or other similar conduct;\n(B) Defamation, obscenity, threats of violence or other expressive conduct that is not protected by the First Amendment to the United States Constitution;\n(C) Audible use of phones, pagers, radios, computers or other electronic equipment in a manner that impedes or disrupts the orderly conduct of the meeting;\n(D) Approaching nearer the City Council than the front of the speaker's podium without leave of the presiding officer; or\n(E) Displaying or causing to be displayed any sign, placard, poster or banner within the meeting room.\n(5) The rules in this section shall be enforced against individuals participating in meetings in the following manner:\n(A) The presiding officer will request that a person who is violating a rule cease the violation;\n(B) If the violation continues, the presiding officer will warn the person that he or she will be required to leave the meeting room if the violation continues;\n(C) If the violation continues, the presiding officer will order the person to leave the meeting room or building for the duration of the meeting; and\n(D) If the person does not leave the meeting room or building, the presiding officer may order any peace officer to remove the person from the meeting room or building for the duration of the meeting.\n(6) It is unlawful for any person to intentionally or knowingly resist removal from the meeting room or building by the presiding officer or a peace officer under subsection (5).\n\n(§ 2-76(4)–(6) applies the same prohibited-conduct list, the same escalation procedure, and the same resisting-removal offense to meetings of the city's boards, commissions, and committees.)", summary:"At City Council meetings (§ 2-19) and at board, commission, and committee meetings (§ 2-76), members of the public may not engage in disruptive conduct — shouting or other disruption, unprotected defamation/obscenity/threats, disruptive use of electronic devices, approaching past the speaker's podium, or displaying signs. Enforcement escalates: the presiding officer asks the person to stop, warns them, then orders them to leave; if they do not leave, the presiding officer may order any peace officer to remove them for the duration of the meeting. It is unlawful to intentionally or knowingly resist that removal.", street:["Your removal authority here is triggered by the presiding officer's order — once the chair orders a disruptive person removed and they won't leave, you're authorized to remove them for the rest of the meeting.","The chargeable offense is resisting that removal, done intentionally or knowingly — the disruption itself is handled through the escalation steps, but resisting the peace-officer removal is the unlawful act under subsection (6).","No penalty is stated in these sections; it defaults to the § 1-12 general penalty (up to $500). A separate state disrupting-a-meeting or resisting offense may also apply depending on the conduct — verify the state citation before settling on a single charge.","The prohibited-conduct list and the resisting-removal offense are identical for council meetings (§ 2-19) and board/commission meetings (§ 2-76) — the meeting type doesn't change your authority or the offense."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 8.02.001 – 8.02.005", name:"Nuisances", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["noise"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 8.02.005; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $2,000 for public-health/sanitation nuisances, otherwise up to $500), each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 8.02.001. Definitions.\nNuisance means any condition or state of real or personal property located within the limits of the town, whether on public or private property, which presents a risk or hazard of injury, illness or loss of life or is unreasonably unsightly or produces any sound or odor which is or may be unreasonably offensive or unhealthful or which presents a clear and present danger of injury or damage to personal property. The term \"nuisance\" shall include, but shall not be limited to, dangerous or dilapidated structures; junk piles; properties of any nature infested with insects or other vermin; open storage or possession of hazardous or noxious chemicals or other substances; the carrying on of any activity which produces unreasonable amounts of dust, sound, or offensive odors, excluding bona fide industrial activities taking place within an area zoned for industrial use.\nOwner includes, without limitation, the owner, occupier, lessee, tenant, bailee or any other person, firm or entity in possession or control of any real or personal property which constitutes a nuisance or upon which a nuisance exists.\n\n§ 8.02.002. Prohibited.\nNo nuisance shall be created, maintained, or allowed to exist anywhere within the town limits. Unless specifically stated otherwise, any nuisance as defined within this article is hereby declared a nuisance if it exists within the corporate limits of the town or within 5,000 feet of such limits. It shall further be unlawful for a person who owns, manages, or controls a property to allow such property to be used in a manner that violates this section. (Ordinance 85-1, § 3, adopted 1/8/1985; Ordinance 2026-12 adopted 3/10/2026)\n\n§ 8.02.003. Notice to remove or abate.\nIf a nuisance should exist in violation of this article, the owner shall be given a written notice stating the general nature and approximate location of the nuisance and ordering that it be removed or abated within ten days after such notice is received; provided, however, that if such nuisance constitutes a clear and present hazard to the health or safety of any person, a lesser period may be provided in such notice.\n\n§ 8.02.005. Penalty for failure to comply.\nThe failure of any owner to comply with the terms of any notice given under this article shall be a misdemeanor punishable by a fine as provided in § 1.01.009 of this Code. Each and every day any such owner fails to comply with any such notice shall constitute a separate offense. (Ordinance 85-1, § 6, adopted 1/8/1985)", summary:"Defines and prohibits nuisances anywhere within the town or within 5,000 feet of the town limits. A nuisance is broadly defined to include conditions presenting a risk of injury/illness, unreasonably unsightly conditions, or unreasonably offensive sound or odor — expressly including dangerous or dilapidated structures, junk piles, vermin infestation, open storage of hazardous substances, and activities producing unreasonable dust, sound, or odor. The chargeable offense is an owner's failure to comply with a written abatement notice (§ 8.02.005): a misdemeanor, fine set by the § 1.01.009 general penalty, each day a separate offense.", street:["The chargeable offense is failure to comply with the abatement notice, not merely the existence of the nuisance — an owner generally gets a written 10-day notice first (shorter if it's a clear and present hazard).", "'Owner' is defined broadly and reaches occupiers, tenants, and anyone in possession or control — not just the deed holder.", "Fine tier depends on the nuisance: public-health-and-sanitation nuisances fall under the § 1.01.009 $2,000 ceiling; others default to $500. Each day is a separate offense.", "The nuisance reaches 5,000 feet beyond the town limits, not just inside them."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 8.03.001", name:"Carrying of Firearm in Municipal Court; Discharge of Firearm", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["firearms"], level:"§ 8.03.001(a) carrying in municipal court: Class A misdemeanor (or other category per state law). § 8.03.001(b)/(c) unlawful discharge: Class C misdemeanor", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 8.03.001. Carrying of firearm; discharge of rifle, handgun or shotgun.\n(a) It shall be unlawful for any person, other than a peace officer, to carry a firearm into the municipal court or any room or office utilized by the municipal court.\n(b) It shall be unlawful for any person to discharge a firearm in the town limits or the extraterritorial jurisdiction of the town, except:\n1. Within a properly secured and permitted indoor or outdoor firearms range, constructed and maintained in accordance with National Rifle Association specifications and standards and any standards prescribed by town ordinance or upon a range owned and operated by a governmental entity;\n2. The discharge of blanks during government-sanctioned celebrations or athletic events; or\n3. As otherwise may specifically be permitted for other purposes under the laws of the state.\n(c) It shall be unlawful for any person to discharge a compressed air weapon in the town limits or the extraterritorial jurisdiction of the town in a manner that causes the projectile to be propelled upon, across or into a public street, alley or other public thoroughfare or to be propelled across the property line of the property from which the projectile originated its propelling motion, except as may be specifically permitted under the laws of the state.\n(d) This section shall not be construed to prohibit any peace officer from discharging a firearm in the performance of his/her duty, nor to prohibit any person from discharging a firearm when lawfully defending person or property or as specifically allowed by the laws of the state.\n(e) For purposes of this section, the term \"firearm\" shall mean any type of handgun, shotgun, rifle, pistol and all percussion weapons. For purposes of this section, the term \"compressed air weapon\" shall mean BB gun, air rifle, pellet gun, bow and arrow or other instrument in which the projectile is propelled by compressed air.\n(f) Any person violating the provisions of § 8.03.001(a) shall be deemed guilty of a class A misdemeanor or other category of offense as provided by state law and, upon conviction thereof, shall be punished in accordance with the V.T.C.A., Penal Code, as it exists or may be amended. Any person violating the provisions of § 8.03.001(b) or § 8.03.001(c) shall be deemed guilty of a class C misdemeanor and, upon conviction thereof, shall be punished in accordance with the Texas Penal Code. (Ordinance 06-107, adopted 10/10/2006; Ordinance 2024-05, § 3, adopted 2/27/2024)", summary:"Two distinct prohibitions. (a) Carrying a firearm into the municipal court or any room/office used by the municipal court — unlawful for anyone other than a peace officer, penalized as a Class A misdemeanor (or other category under state law). (b)/(c) Discharging a firearm (or a compressed-air weapon across a public thoroughfare or property line) within the town limits or its ETJ, with narrow exceptions for permitted ranges, government-sanctioned blank fire, and state-authorized purposes — penalized as a Class C misdemeanor. Peace officers acting in the line of duty and persons lawfully defending person or property are expressly excepted.", street:["Two different penalty levels in one section: municipal-court carry is a Class A misdemeanor; unlawful discharge is a Class C. Identify which subsection applies.", "The discharge prohibition (b) extends into the town's ETJ, not just the corporate limits.", "'Compressed air weapon' (c) — BB gun, air rifle, pellet gun, even bow and arrow — is an offense only when the projectile crosses a public thoroughfare or the originating property's line.", "Lawful self-defense of person or property and peace-officer duty discharge are express exceptions under (d)."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 8.05.001 – 8.05.008", name:"Junked Vehicles", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["publicconduct"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 8.05.003; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense; court orders abatement on conviction", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 8.05.002. Nuisance declared.\nA junked vehicle, including part of a junked vehicle, that is visible at any time of the year from a public place or public right-of-way: (1) Is detrimental to the safety and welfare of the public; (2) Tends to reduce the value of private property; (3) Invites vandalism; (4) Creates a fire hazard; (5) Is an attractive nuisance creating a hazard to the health and safety of minors; (6) Produces urban blight adverse to the maintenance and continuing development of the town; and (7) Is a public nuisance. (Ordinance 04-117, § 3, adopted 12/21/2004)\n\n§ 8.05.003. Offense.\na. A person commits an offense if the person allows or maintains a junked vehicle in any place, whether on private or public property, in view of the public or on a public right-of-way.\nb. An offense under this section is a misdemeanor punishable by a fine as provided in § 1.01.009 of this Code. A separate offense occurs each and every day the violation described in subsection (a) continues.\nc. The court shall order abatement and removal of the public nuisance on conviction of this offense. (Ordinance 04-117, § 4, adopted 12/21/2004)\n\n§ 8.05.004. Authority to abate nuisance; procedures. [summarized]\nBefore abatement, an authorized town employee must give notice — by certified mail (five-day return receipt) to the last known registered owner, any lienholder of record, and the property owner/occupant (or adjacent owner if the vehicle is on the right-of-way); or by posting on the vehicle if the owner's address is unknown; or by hand delivery. The notice must state the nature of the nuisance, that the vehicle must be removed by the 10th day after the notice was mailed, and that any hearing request must be in writing and received before that period expires. A junked vehicle abated under this article must be removed to a scrapyard, motor vehicle demolisher, or suitable site; once removed it may not be reconstructed or made operable. Notice to the Texas Department of Transportation is required within five days after removal.", summary:"Declares a junked vehicle (or junked-vehicle part) visible from a public place or right-of-way to be a public nuisance, and makes it an offense to allow or maintain one in view of the public, on private or public property. The offense is a misdemeanor (fine per § 1.01.009, up to $500), each day a separate offense, and the court must order abatement and removal on conviction. Abatement is preceded by a defined notice-and-hearing process (§ 8.05.004): certified-mail, posted, or hand-delivered notice to the owner/lienholder/property owner, a 10-day removal window, and a written hearing-request opportunity.", street:["Two elements matter: the vehicle must meet the code's 'junked vehicle' definition AND be visible from a public place or right-of-way. Visibility is what converts it from a private matter to a chargeable nuisance.", "Abatement requires the notice-and-hearing process first; the criminal offense and the administrative removal are separate tracks.", "On conviction the court is required to order abatement and removal — removal is not discretionary at that point."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 8.06.001 – 8.06.009", name:"Noise Control", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["noise"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 8.06.009, fine up to $500, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 8.06.005. Specific noise disturbance prohibited.\n(a) No person shall allow, make or cause to be made any unreasonably loud or disturbing noise in the town which is offensive to the sensibilities of a reasonable, prudent adult person, renders the enjoyment of life or property uncomfortable, interferes with public peace and comfort, or causes a noise disturbance as defined herein. Such action is hereby declared to be a public nuisance and a violation of this article.\n(b) The following list includes, but is not limited to, activities which can create unreasonably loud or disturbing noises in violation of this article, unless an exemption exists pursuant to section 8.06.006 or a permit of variance was first obtained as provided in section 8.06.007:\n(1) Animals. Owning, keeping, possessing, or harboring any animal which, by frequent or habitual noisemaking, unreasonably disturbs the peace, comfort or repose of the citizens of the town, or causes a noise disturbance.\n(2) Radios, television sets, musical instruments, loudspeaking amplifiers and similar devices — including operating any such sound device within a residential district or quiet zone, or within 500 feet of any residence or quiet zone, in such a manner as to cause a noise disturbance; operating such devices in a nonresidential area so as to cause a noise disturbance; using such devices to attract attention to a cause, demonstration, performance, show, sale, or display; and operating such devices on trucks or moving vehicles to attract attention so as to cause a noise disturbance.\n\n§ 8.06.006. Exemptions. [summarized] Includes certain school, government, religious, and permitted activities, emergency work, and other categories set out in the article.\n\n§ 8.06.009. Penalty.\nAny person, firm or corporation violating any provision of this article, as amended, shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction therefor, shall be fined in a sum not exceeding $500.00, and each and every day such violation continues shall be considered a separate offense; provided, however, such penal provision shall not preclude a suit to enjoin such violation. (Ordinance 2026-12 adopted 3/10/2026)", summary:"Prohibits unreasonably loud or disturbing noise that is offensive to a reasonable, prudent adult, renders enjoyment of life or property uncomfortable, interferes with public peace, or causes a defined 'noise disturbance' — declaring such noise a public nuisance. Enumerates (non-exclusively) violating activities including habitual animal noise and the use of radios, TVs, musical instruments, and amplifiers within a residential district/quiet zone or within 500 feet of a residence, or to attract attention, or mounted on vehicles. Subject to listed exemptions (§ 8.06.006) and permits of variance (§ 8.06.007). Penalty: misdemeanor, up to $500, each day a separate offense.", street:["The core standard is the 'reasonable, prudent adult person' — this is a subjective-disturbance ordinance, not a fixed decibel threshold, so document why the noise was unreasonable in context.", "The 500-foot-from-a-residence trigger for sound devices is the concrete measurement to anchor a residential-noise call.", "Check § 8.06.006 exemptions and whether a § 8.06.007 variance permit was issued before citing — several categories (emergency work, certain permitted events) are carved out.", "Habitual animal noise is covered here as well as under Chapter 2 — either can be the charging vehicle depending on the facts."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 8.07.001 – 8.07.006", name:"Sex Offender Residency Restriction", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["sexoffender"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 8.07.006, fine up to $500, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 8.07.002. Residency requirements.\nIt is unlawful for a person who is required to register as a sex offender under Chapter 62 of the Texas Code of Criminal Procedure, because of a victim who was younger than 17 years of age, to establish a permanent residence or temporary residence within 2,000 feet of any premises where children commonly gather. A 'premises where children commonly gather' includes a school, licensed day-care facility, playground, public or private youth center, public swimming pool, video arcade facility, or park, as such terms are defined in the town's comprehensive zoning ordinance.\n\n§ 8.07.003. Evidentiary matters; measurements.\nFor the purpose of determining the minimum distance of separation, the requirement shall be measured by following a straight line from the outer property line of the permanent or temporary residence to the nearest property line of the premises where children commonly gather; in the case of multiple residences on one property, measuring from the nearest property line of the premises to the premises where children commonly gather. A map depicting the prohibited areas shall be maintained by the town.\n\n§ 8.07.004. Culpable mental state.\nNeither allegation nor evidence of a culpable mental state is required for the proof of an offense defined by this article.\n\n§ 8.07.005. Affirmative defenses. [summarized] Includes that the residence was established before the article's adoption, that the person was a minor when the offense was committed and not convicted as an adult, that the person is a minor, that the premises where children commonly gather was established after the person's residence, and that the database information is incorrect.\n\n§ 8.07.006. Penalty.\nAny person who violates this article shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction therefor, shall be fined in a sum not exceeding $500.00, and each and every day a violation continues shall constitute a separate offense.", summary:"Makes it unlawful for a person required to register as a sex offender (due to an offense involving a victim under 17) to establish a permanent or temporary residence within 2,000 feet of a 'premises where children commonly gather' — schools, licensed day cares, playgrounds, youth centers, public pools, video arcades, or parks. Distance is measured property-line to property-line. No culpable mental state is required. Affirmative defenses are available (§ 8.07.005), including that the residence predates the article or the qualifying premises. Penalty: misdemeanor, up to $500, each day a separate offense.", street:["Prosper's buffer is 2,000 feet — double Frisco's 1,000-foot restriction. Do not carry over the Frisco number; verify against the town-maintained prohibited-areas map.", "Verify the person's registration status and that the qualifying offense involved a victim under 17 — that under-17 element is what triggers this article.", "No culpable mental state is required (§ 8.07.004) — this is a strict-liability-style residency violation once the elements are met.", "Check § 8.07.005 affirmative defenses (e.g., residence established before the qualifying premises existed) before referring for prosecution."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 8.08.001 – 8.08.004", name:"Restrictions in Public Access Parking Areas and Parks", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["parks"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 8.08.004, fine up to $500, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 8.08.002. Purpose.\nThe purpose of this article is to make it unlawful for any person to use in-line skates, skates, skateboards, bicycles, motorized or non-recreational products ('uses') in public access areas located in the town or on any other type of concrete or laminate surfaces in town in a manner that damages, defaces, or destroys those surfaces.\n\n§ 8.08.003. Posting.\nThe town shall erect signs advertising the prohibition in § 8.08.002 on all town-owned and/or maintained property. The town may also post signs on other public access areas at the property owner's discretion and expense.\n\n§ 8.08.004. Penalty.\nAny person violating this article shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction thereof shall be fined in the sum of not more than $500.00. Each continuing day's violation under this article shall constitute a separate offense. Furthermore, no penalty imposed pursuant to this section shall operate to prohibit the town from seeking reimbursement for expenses incurred in connection with replacing the surfaces which result from a violation of this article. The town retains all legal rights and remedies available to it pursuant to local, state, and federal law. The provisions of this article do not prohibit the authorized use of bicycles, or any other vehicles used while engaged in police patrols by police personnel. (Ordinance 09-062, adopted 5/26/2009)", summary:"Makes it unlawful to use in-line skates, skates, skateboards, bicycles, or motorized/non-recreational products in public access areas or on concrete or laminate surfaces in a manner that damages, defaces, or destroys those surfaces. The town must post signs stating the prohibition on town-owned/maintained property. Penalty: misdemeanor, up to $500, each day a separate offense, plus the town may separately seek reimbursement for surface-replacement costs. Authorized police-patrol use of bicycles and other vehicles is exempt.", street:["The offense is surface-damaging use (skating/skateboarding/biking that damages, defaces, or destroys concrete or laminate surfaces) — not skating or biking as such. Damage to the surface is the element.", "Posting is contemplated by the ordinance; note whether the prohibition was signed at the location.", "Reimbursement for surface-replacement costs is a separate civil remedy on top of the criminal fine.", "Police-patrol use of bicycles and vehicles is expressly exempt."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 8.09.001 – 8.09.002", name:"Dumping of Trash on Public or Private Property", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["publicconduct"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 8.09.002, fine up to $2,000, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 8.09.001. Dumping of trash on public or private property.\nAny person who places, throws, drops, dumps, deposits, or discards any garbage, trash, waste, rubbish, refuse, debris, or other deleterious substance on any public property, or on any private property of another without consent of the property owner, including the placing, throwing, dropping, dumping, depositing, or discarding of any such substance in a trash receptacle or dumpster on any private property of another without consent of the property owner, shall, upon conviction, be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor. (Ordinance 2024-06, § 2, adopted 1/9/2024)\n\n§ 8.09.002. Penalty.\nAny person or business violating any provision of this article, or as amended, shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction therefor, shall be fined in a sum not to exceed $2,000.00, and each and every day a violation continues shall constitute a separate offense. (Ordinance 2024-06, § 2, adopted 1/9/2024)", summary:"Makes it a misdemeanor to place, throw, dump, deposit, or discard garbage, trash, waste, rubbish, refuse, debris, or other deleterious substance on public property, or on another's private property without the owner's consent — expressly including dumping into a trash receptacle or dumpster on another's private property without consent. Penalty: misdemeanor, up to $2,000 (the § 1.01.009 public-health/sanitation tier), each day a separate offense.", street:["Note the $2,000 ceiling — dumping falls in the public-health/sanitation penalty tier, not the ordinary $500 tier. This is a recently adopted (2024) ordinance.", "The offense expressly includes using someone else's dumpster or trash receptacle without consent — a common fact pattern that this section specifically reaches.", "On another's private property, lack of the owner's consent is an element; on public property, the act alone suffices."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 8.10.001 – 8.10.005", name:"Solicitation of Vehicle Occupants on Public Roadways", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["solicitation"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 8.10.005, fine up to $500, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 8.10.001. Definitions. [key terms]\nSolicitation means any conduct or act whereby a person: (1) orally or in writing asks for a ride, employment, goods, services, financial aid, monetary gifts, or any article representing monetary value, for any purpose; (2) orally or in writing sells or offers for sale goods, services, or publications; (3) distributes without remuneration goods, services, or publications; or (4) solicits signatures on a petition or opinions for a survey. Public property includes any property open or devoted to public use or owned by the town, and any area dedicated to public use for sidewalk, street, highway, or other transportation purposes, including any curb, median, parkway, shoulder, sidewalk, alley, drive, or public right-of-way. Roadway and vehicle have the meanings given in Chapter 541, Texas Transportation Code.\n\n§ 8.10.002. Offense.\nA person commits an offense if, while occupying any public property adjacent to any public roadway in the town, he knowingly conducts a solicitation directed to, or intended to attract the attention of, the occupant of any vehicle stopped or traveling on the roadway. An offense occurs when the solicitation is made, whether or not an actual employment relationship is created, a transaction is completed, or an exchange of money, goods, or services takes place. (Ordinance 2024-38 adopted 5/28/2024)\n\n§ 8.10.003. Defense to prosecution.\nIt is a defense to prosecution under section 8.10.002 that the person was: (1) summoning aid or requesting assistance in an emergency situation; or (2) a law enforcement officer in the performance of official duties.\n\n§ 8.10.005. Penalty.\nAny person violating any provision of this article, or as amended, shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction therefor, shall be fined in a sum not to exceed $500.00, and each and every day a violation continues shall constitute a separate offense. (Ordinance 2024-38 adopted 5/28/2024)", summary:"Makes it an offense to knowingly conduct a solicitation, while occupying public property adjacent to a public roadway, that is directed to or intended to attract the attention of an occupant of a vehicle stopped or traveling on the roadway. 'Solicitation' is broadly defined (asking for rides, employment, money, or goods; selling or offering goods/services/publications; distributing them; or gathering petition signatures or survey opinions). The offense is complete when the solicitation is made, regardless of whether any transaction results. Defenses: summoning aid in an emergency, or a law enforcement officer performing official duties. Penalty: misdemeanor, up to $500, each day a separate offense.", street:["The offense is the roadway-directed solicitation itself, complete when made — no exchange of money or completed transaction is required.", "'Solicitation' is defined broadly and includes non-commercial conduct like petition signatures and survey opinions, not just panhandling or sales.", "Emergency aid-summoning and on-duty law enforcement are express defenses (§ 8.10.003).", "Location element: the person must be on public property adjacent to a public roadway, directing the solicitation at vehicle occupants on the roadway. Recently adopted (2024)."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 2.01.005", name:"Interference with Animal Control Officer", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 2.01.005. Interference with Animal Control Officer.\nIt shall be unlawful for any person to interfere with an Animal Control Officer while engaged in the performance of his or her duties. A person interferes with an Animal Control Officer if he or she:\n(1) Releases or causes an animal to be released after an Animal Control Officer has impounded the animal; or\n(2) Physically constrains the movement of an Animal Control Officer or his or her vehicle or equipment by:\nA. Placing any part of the person or person's property in the way of the Animal Control Officer's progress in the performance of the officer's duties;\nB. Taking or moving the Animal Control Officer's equipment, causing a time delay in the Animal Control Officer's ability to use the equipment; or\n(3) Intentionally or knowingly fails or refuses to provide an Animal Control Officer with the person's full name, date of birth, and mailing address when the Animal Control Officer has identified himself or herself as an Animal Control Officer, is investigating a violation or possible violation of a provision of this chapter, and requests this information from the person. For purposes of this subsection, a person fails or refuses to provide the information required if the person provides inaccurate, incorrect, or incomplete information.", summary:"Makes it unlawful to interfere with an Animal Control Officer performing their duties — defined as releasing an impounded animal, physically constraining the officer or their vehicle/equipment (blocking their progress or moving their equipment to cause delay), or intentionally/knowingly refusing to provide one's full name, date of birth, and mailing address when the officer has identified themselves and is investigating a chapter violation. Providing inaccurate, incorrect, or incomplete information counts as a refusal.", street:["The failure-to-identify prong (3) is a specific, chargeable refusal: when an ACO has identified themselves and is investigating a chapter violation, refusing or giving false/incomplete name, DOB, or address is the offense.", "Releasing an animal the ACO has already impounded is a distinct violation under (1)."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 2.02.001 – 2.02.002", name:"Restraint of Animals; Leash Requirement", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense; each animal a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 2.02.001. Restraint of animals.\n(a) It shall be unlawful for an owner or person in control of an animal to fail to keep the animal under restraint as defined in this chapter.\n(b) It shall be unlawful for an owner to fail or refuse to control, restrain, or otherwise allow, either by conduct, omission, or condition of premises, his or her animal to become a public nuisance by being at-large or running at-large.\n(c) It shall be unlawful for a person to use a chain, rope, tether, leash, cable, or other device to attach a dog to a stationary object or trolley system.\n(d) It is an affirmative defense to a violation of subsection (c) that the dog tethering: (1) is during a lawful animal event, veterinary treatment, grooming, training, or law enforcement activity; (2) is required to protect the safety or welfare of a person or the dog, and the owner maintains direct physical control; or (3) occurs on the owner's premises while the dog is within the owner's direct physical control and prevented from advancing within 15 feet of the edge of any public street.\n(e) The affirmative defenses in (d) are only available if: the device is attached to a properly fitted collar/harness (not directly around the neck), does not exceed 1/20 of the dog's body weight, allows reasonable unobstructed range of motion without entanglement, and the dog has access to adequate shelter and clean water.\n(f) A person commits an offense if the person fails to comply with this section. If a person fails to comply with respect to more than one animal, the conduct with respect to each animal constitutes a separate offense.\n(g) This section does not prohibit a person from walking a dog with a handheld leash.\n\n§ 2.02.002. Secure animals on a leash.\nIt shall be unlawful for an owner or person in control of an animal to fail to keep the animal under restraint as defined in this chapter. Restraint includes: the animal secured by a standard leash no longer than ten feet or a retractable leash no longer than 16 feet and of sufficient strength to control the animal while being walked; a specially trained service dog used by a blind or deaf individual; and other conditions of restraint set out in this section.", summary:"Requires owners to keep animals under restraint and makes it unlawful to allow an animal to run at-large and become a public nuisance. Prohibits unattended tethering of a dog to a stationary object or trolley system (subsection (c)), subject to affirmative defenses for supervised, brief, or activity-related tethering that also meets welfare conditions (proper collar, weight limit, range of motion, shelter, water). 'Restraint' includes a standard leash up to 10 feet or a retractable leash up to 16 feet. Each animal not under restraint is a separate offense; walking a dog on a handheld leash is expressly allowed.", street:["Two common charges here: at-large/running-at-large (b) and unlawful unattended tethering (c). The tethering ban has real affirmative defenses — check whether the owner was present and in direct control before citing (c).", "Leash limits are concrete: 10 ft standard, 16 ft retractable. A longer or insufficient-strength leash defeats the restraint compliance.", "Each unrestrained animal is a separate offense — count them.", "Service dogs for the blind/deaf and normal handheld-leash walking are carved out."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 2.03.002 – 2.03.005", name:"Dangerous Animals — Finding, Owner Requirements", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Violation of requirements is a misdemeanor (§ 2.03.007); fine per § 1.01.009 (up to $500). Owner must carry $100,000 liability insurance and register the animal.", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 2.03.002. Finding of an animal as dangerous. [summarized]\nEstablishes the process by which an animal is determined dangerous (a defined term in § 2.01.001), including sworn-complaint procedures, service on the owner, and a requirement that the owner deliver the animal to Animal Control for impoundment within five days of being served. Separate provisions address animals that caused the death of or serious bodily injury to a person by attacking, biting, or mauling.\n\n§ 2.03.003. Requirements for owner of dangerous animal.\nAn owner of an animal determined to be dangerous must, among other requirements: (1) Register the dangerous animal with Animal Control; (2) Keep the animal in a secure enclosure as defined in § 2.01.001, and post signs on all four sides of the enclosure in one-inch letters warning of a dangerous animal; (3) Further secure the dangerous animal with a muzzle in a manner that prevents it from biting any person or animal when outside the enclosure; and (4) Obtain and maintain liability insurance in an amount of at least $100,000.00 to cover damages resulting from an attack by the dangerous animal. Additional provisions address destruction of the animal if it makes an unprovoked attack or escapes the enclosure on its own.\n\n§ 2.03.004. Failure to comply with requirements. [summarized]\nAn owner who does not comply with § 2.03.003 or an order issued under it must deliver the animal to Animal Control, and a hearing process (with impoundment timelines) determines whether the owner has complied and paid all impound and care costs.\n\n§ 2.03.005. Registration of a dangerous animal. [summarized]\nSets the registration requirement and procedure for a dangerous animal with Animal Control.", summary:"Sets the framework for animals determined 'dangerous.' Once an animal is found dangerous, the owner must register it with Animal Control, keep it in a secure enclosure signed on all four sides, muzzle it whenever it is outside the enclosure, and carry at least $100,000 in liability insurance for attack damages. Failure to comply with these requirements (or with an order issued under the article) is an offense under § 2.03.007. The article includes impoundment, hearing, and destruction procedures for non-compliance or unprovoked attacks/escapes.", street:["The four owner requirements are the checklist on scene for a known dangerous animal: registered, secure signed enclosure, muzzled when out, and $100,000 insurance. Any failure is chargeable under § 2.03.007.", "'Dangerous animal' is a defined term (§ 2.01.001) and generally requires a prior finding — confirm the animal has actually been determined dangerous before applying these owner requirements.", "Escape from the enclosure on the animal's own, or an unprovoked attack, can trigger destruction procedures separate from the criminal charge."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 2.03.006", name:"Attack by Dangerous Animal", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Class C misdemeanor; Class A misdemeanor if the attack causes death or serious bodily injury. Plus civil penalty up to $10,000 and possible court-ordered destruction.", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 2.03.006. Attack by dangerous animal.\n(a) A person commits an offense if the person is the owner of a dangerous animal and the animal makes an unprovoked attack on a person or another animal outside the animal's enclosure and causes bodily injury to the person or other animal.\n(b) An offense under this section is a class C misdemeanor, unless the attack causes the death of or serious bodily injury to a person, in which event the offense is a class A misdemeanor.\n(c) If a person is found guilty of an offense under this section, the court may order the dangerous animal destroyed by Animal Control or a licensed veterinarian.\n(d) In addition to criminal prosecution, a person who commits an offense under this section is liable for a civil penalty not to exceed $10,000.00. The Town Attorney may file suit in a court of competent jurisdiction to collect the penalty. Penalties collected under this subsection shall be retained by the town.", summary:"Makes it an offense for the owner of a dangerous animal if the animal makes an unprovoked attack outside its enclosure and causes bodily injury to a person or another animal. The offense is a Class C misdemeanor, elevated to a Class A misdemeanor if the attack causes the death of or serious bodily injury to a person. On conviction the court may order the animal destroyed, and — in addition to criminal prosecution — the owner is liable for a civil penalty up to $10,000 collectible by the Town Attorney.", street:["Elements: owner of a (already-determined) dangerous animal + unprovoked attack + outside the enclosure + bodily injury. All four matter.", "Penalty escalates on the injury: Class C by default, Class A if the person suffers death or serious bodily injury.", "The $10,000 civil penalty and possible destruction order are separate consequences on top of the criminal charge."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 2.05.001 – 2.05.002", name:"Rabies Vaccination Required", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 2.05.001. Rabies vaccination.\n(a) Vaccinations required. Every owner of a dog, cat, or ferret over four months of age must have the animal immunized against rabies by injection of anti-rabies vaccine, and must have the animal revaccinated at the interval following the initial vaccination, and thereafter revaccinated against rabies at a minimum of at least once every three years with a rabies vaccine licensed by the appropriate authority.\n(b) Every owner of a dog, cat, or ferret immunized against rabies shall procure a rabies vaccination certificate from the veterinarian administering the vaccine.\n(c) The provisions restricting the use and sale of rabies vaccine set forth in the state statute enacting the 'Rabies Control Act' are adopted by reference.\n(d) It shall be unlawful for a person to administer, sell, or distribute rabies vaccine for animals in a manner not authorized by this section or state law.\n\n§ 2.05.002. Domestic animals that exhibit rabies symptoms or reasonably indicate rabies symptoms. [summarized]\nAddresses handling of a dog, cat, or ferret that has rabies or symptoms that could reasonably indicate rabies, or that bites, scratches, or otherwise creates a condition that may expose or transmit rabies to a human — including quarantine/observation for the period during which transmission to a human could have occurred, or longer as the local rabies authority directs.", summary:"Requires every owner of a dog, cat, or ferret over four months of age to have the animal vaccinated against rabies and revaccinated on schedule (at least every three years with a licensed vaccine), and to obtain a rabies vaccination certificate. Makes it unlawful to administer, sell, or distribute animal rabies vaccine in an unauthorized manner. Section 2.05.002 governs animals showing rabies symptoms or that bite/scratch in a way that may expose a human, including quarantine/observation requirements.", street:["The four-months-of-age threshold and the current-vaccination requirement are the enforcement hooks — an unvaccinated dog/cat/ferret over four months is the violation.", "A current rabies vaccination tag also serves as the animal's town registration (§ 2.04.001) and must be produced to an ACO, peace officer, or rabies authority on request.", "A bite or scratch that may expose a human triggers the § 2.05.002 quarantine/observation process — coordinate with the local rabies control authority; don't release the animal prematurely."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 2.07.001", name:"Unlawful Acts — Cruelty and Prohibited Treatment", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 2.07.001. Unlawful acts enumerated. [key subsections]\nIt shall be unlawful for a person to:\n(a) Treat an animal in an inhumane manner;\n(b) Knowingly own, harbor, train, or possess any animal for the purpose of animal fighting (this subsection shall not apply to guard dogs in lawful use);\n(c) Mutilate any animal;\n(d) Cause an animal to fight another animal;\n(e) Operate a motor vehicle transporting an animal in a cruel or unsafe manner (as specified);\n(f) Tether a dog in a manner that violates the restraint provisions;\n(g)–(h) Confine an animal in a cruel or dangerous manner (e.g., in a way that endangers its health or in an unattended vehicle under dangerous conditions);\n(i) Crop a dog's ears or dock a tail other than as permitted;\n(j)–(l) Sell, barter, give away, or offer as a prize/inducement certain live animals as specified;\n(m) Use steel jaw or leg-hold traps as specified;\n(n) Beat, starve, overwork, or otherwise abuse an animal;\n(o) As an owner or person having care and control, fail to provide an animal with proper food, water, shelter, or care.\n(Subsections summarized; see the full section for exact text of each prohibited act.)", summary:"Enumerates prohibited acts of animal cruelty and mistreatment, including inhumane treatment; animal fighting (owning/training/possessing animals for fighting, or causing animals to fight); mutilation; unsafe transport; cruel tethering or confinement (including in dangerous unattended-vehicle conditions); unauthorized ear-cropping/tail-docking; giving live animals as prizes; certain traps; beating, starving, or overworking an animal; and failing to provide proper food, water, shelter, or care. Guard dogs in lawful use are excepted from the animal-fighting subsection.", street:["This is the local cruelty/neglect catch-all covering distinct prohibited acts from inhumane treatment and fighting to neglect.", "Failure to provide proper food, water, shelter, or care (o) is the common neglect hook on a welfare-check call.", "Unattended-animal-in-vehicle and cruel-tethering conditions are specifically reachable here.", "Confirm which lettered subsection fits the facts; the section is a list of distinct prohibited acts."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 2.07.003 – 2.07.004", name:"Guard Dogs; Keeping of Livestock", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 2.07.003. Guard dogs.\n(a) All guard dogs shall be registered with Animal Control prior to being used as guard dogs.\n(b) A guard dog that commits an unprovoked bite upon a human being (other than a person committing a crime who is bitten by a guard dog protecting life or property) is subject to the dangerous-animal provisions of this chapter.\n(c) The state statute referring to guard dog companies and restrictions on the use of guard dogs is adopted by reference.\n\n§ 2.07.004. Keeping of livestock. [summarized]\nRegulates the keeping of livestock within the town — including minimum lot-size/area requirements, distance/setback requirements from residences and property lines, sanitation, and the number and type of livestock permitted. Keeping livestock in violation of these requirements is unlawful. (See § 2.07.005 for impounding of livestock, and § 2.07.006 for the restricted keeping of fowl, rabbits, and guinea pigs.)", summary:"Requires guard dogs to be registered with Animal Control before use and subjects a guard dog that makes an unprovoked bite on a human (except a person committing a crime bitten while the dog protects life or property) to the chapter's dangerous-animal provisions; the state guard-dog-company statute is adopted by reference. Section 2.07.004 regulates the keeping of livestock within town (area, setback, sanitation, and number/type limits), with companion sections on impounding livestock (2.07.005) and restricted keeping of fowl, rabbits, and guinea pigs (2.07.006).", street:["An unregistered guard dog in use is a violation; a guard dog's unprovoked bite on a non-suspect pushes it into the dangerous-animal track (§ 2.03).", "Livestock-in-town complaints turn on the area/setback/number limits in § 2.07.004 — the keeping is lawful only within those parameters.", "Fowl, rabbits, and guinea pigs have their own restricted-keeping rules (§ 2.07.006) separate from livestock."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 12.01.003", name:"Engine (Jake) Brakes Prohibited", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Offense — misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense (§ 12.01.002)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 12.01.003. Engine (jake) brakes.\n(a) Definitions. Engine brake means any device used to slow a vehicle by slowing the engine, also commonly called an engine brake, compression brake, jake brake, or dynamic brake, regardless of manufacturer. Vehicle means a device that can be used to transport or draw persons and/or property on a highway or street, including but not limited to a car, truck, trailer, truck-tractor, semitruck, tractor-trailer, 18-wheeler, or motorcycle.\n(b) Unlawful use; offense established; nuisance established. It shall be unlawful for the driver of any vehicle to use or operate or cause to be used or operated within the town limits any engine brake. A person commits an offense by violating any provision of this section. The use of an engine brake is hereby declared to be a nuisance.\n(c) Signs. The Town Manager or designee shall be responsible for installing signs and/or markings to properly notify the public that the use of engine brakes is prohibited within the town, and/or shall cooperate with and assist the Texas Department of Transportation in installing such signs and/or markings.\n(d) Enforcement. The police chief, or his/her authorized representative, is authorized to issue citations to any driver or owner of a vehicle who has violated this section.\n(e) Defense established. It shall be a defense to prosecution for an offense established by this section if the use of engine brakes was necessary to avoid imminent danger to persons or property. (Ordinance 05-05, adopted 1/25/2005; Ordinance 2024-73 adopted 11/12/2024)", summary:"Makes it unlawful for the driver of any vehicle to use an engine brake (also called a compression brake, jake brake, or dynamic brake) within the town limits, and declares such use a nuisance. Applies to all vehicles, including cars and motorcycles, not just heavy trucks. The town posts signs advising of the prohibition. It is a defense that use of the engine brake was necessary to avoid imminent danger to persons or property.", street:["The prohibition applies town-wide to any vehicle, not only to trucks — though the practical target is heavy-truck compression braking.", "The imminent-danger defense (e) is the key exception: engine braking to avoid a collision or other imminent danger is not chargeable.", "Signage is contemplated but the offense is the use within town limits; note whether the location was posted.", "Recently amended (2024)."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 12.01.004", name:"Motor Vehicle Idling Restriction", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Offense — misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense (§ 12.01.002)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 12.01.004. Motor vehicle idling. [summarized]\nRestricts idling of motor vehicles, adopting the Texas Commission on Environmental Quality (TCEQ) Idling Limitation Rule (30 TAC § 114.512) as approved and implemented by the Town Council. 'Idle' means operating an engine that is not engaged in gear, running at the manufacturer-specified released-accelerator RPM, with no load on the engine. The section sets out exceptions, including (among others): idling necessary to power a heater or air conditioner under defined conditions; certain mechanical operations (idling up to a maximum of 30 minutes); vehicles meeting specified low-emissions criteria; and other categories consistent with the TCEQ rule. Commercial passenger transportation (buses/motor coaches over 10 passengers) is defined and addressed within the section.", summary:"Restricts extended idling of motor vehicles by adopting the TCEQ Idling Limitation Rule as approved by the Town Council, with 'idle' defined as an engine running out of gear, at released-accelerator RPM, under no load. The section provides exceptions — including idling needed to power a heater or air conditioner under stated conditions, certain mechanical operations (up to 30 minutes), and low-emissions vehicles — mirroring the state rule. Commercial passenger transportation vehicles are specifically defined and covered.", street:["This adopts the TCEQ state idling rule locally — the practical target is prolonged heavy-vehicle/commercial idling, not brief passenger-car idling.", "Multiple exceptions apply (heater/AC, mechanical operations up to 30 minutes, low-emissions vehicles) — confirm none applies before citing.", "'Idle' has a specific definition (out of gear, released-accelerator RPM, no load) — the vehicle must actually be idling as defined."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 12.04.001", name:"U-Turns", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Offense — misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense (§ 12.01.002)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 12.04.001. U-turns.\nIt shall be unlawful for the driver of any vehicle to turn such vehicle so as to proceed in the opposite direction (a 180-degree turn or U-turn) on any street posted with a sign or signs indicating that such a movement is prohibited. U-turns shall be permitted when not so posted. It shall be further unlawful for the driver of any vehicle to make a U-turn in any event unless such movement can be made in safety and without interfering with other traffic. (Ordinance 85-19, adopted 9/13/1985)", summary:"Makes it unlawful to make a U-turn (a 180-degree turn to proceed in the opposite direction) on any street posted prohibiting the movement; U-turns are permitted where not posted. Additionally makes it unlawful to make a U-turn anywhere unless the movement can be made safely and without interfering with other traffic.", street:["Two independent violations: (1) a U-turn where posted against it, and (2) an unsafe or traffic-interfering U-turn anywhere, even where not posted.", "The 'made in safety and without interfering with other traffic' standard is the catch-all that applies regardless of signage."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 12.04.002 – 12.04.003", name:"Driving Off Pavement; Driving Upon or Over Curb", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Offense — misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense (§ 12.01.002)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 12.04.002. Driving off pavement or main-traveled portion of roadway.\nNo person shall operate a motor vehicle off the pavement or main-traveled portion of any roadway within the town except as necessary to enter or leave the roadway at an intersection, driveway, or other lawful point of access, or as otherwise permitted by law.\n\n§ 12.04.003. Driving upon or over curb.\nNo person shall operate a motor vehicle upon or over any curb of any street within the town. (Ordinance 85-19, § 10(h), adopted 9/13/1985)", summary:"Two related prohibitions: operating a motor vehicle off the pavement or main-traveled portion of a roadway (§ 12.04.002), except as needed to lawfully enter or leave the roadway; and operating a motor vehicle upon or over any curb of a street within the town (§ 12.04.003).", street:["Driving over a curb is a discrete, observable offense under § 12.04.003 — useful on its own or alongside a reckless-driving or evading investigation.", "Driving off the main-traveled portion of the roadway (§ 12.04.002) has an exception for lawfully entering/leaving at an intersection or driveway."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 12.04.005", name:"Concrete Trucks; Leakage of Concrete", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Offense — misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense (§ 12.01.002)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 12.04.005. Concrete trucks and leakage of concrete.\nIt shall be unlawful to operate any ready-mix concrete truck along the streets of the town unless the truck is equipped with a chute enclosure, or some other mechanism, which precludes the leakage of concrete and other debris from leaking or escaping from the truck. Among the requirements: (3) it shall have no parts which may become clogged with concrete; and the truck must otherwise be maintained so as to prevent concrete or debris from escaping onto the roadway.", summary:"Makes it unlawful to operate a ready-mix concrete truck on town streets unless it is equipped with a chute enclosure or other mechanism that prevents concrete and debris from leaking or escaping, with related maintenance requirements (including no parts that may become clogged with concrete).", street:["The offense is operating the concrete truck without adequate leakage-prevention equipment — a fresh concrete trail or spatter on the roadway from an unenclosed chute is the observable indicator.", "Targets the roadway-damage and hazard from escaping concrete; the equipment requirement is on the truck, so the violation attaches to operating it in that condition."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 12.05.003", name:"Parking of Commercial Motor Vehicles", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Offense — misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense (§ 12.01.002)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 12.05.003. Parking of commercial motor vehicles.\nParking of commercial motor vehicles shall comply with the following:\n(1) It shall be unlawful for any person to park or store, or allow to be parked or stored, any commercial motor vehicle upon any public street, alley, parkway, boulevard, public place, or public right-of-way. This subsection shall not apply to street construction equipment, or to vehicles parked in a designated loading zone while in the act of loading or unloading, or as otherwise excepted.\n(2) It shall be unlawful for any person to park or store, or allow to be parked or stored, any commercial motor vehicle upon property within any residentially zoned district or any property used for residential purposes, within the corporate limits of the town. This subsection shall not prevent the parking or standing of a commercial motor vehicle for a reasonable period while actively engaged in a delivery, service, or similar activity at that location.", summary:"Prohibits parking or storing a commercial motor vehicle (1) on any public street, alley, parkway, boulevard, public place, or public right-of-way; and (2) on property within a residentially zoned district or used for residential purposes. Exceptions include street construction equipment, vehicles in a designated loading zone actively loading/unloading, and commercial vehicles temporarily present while actively engaged in delivery or service at the location.", street:["Two distinct violations: commercial vehicle parked on the public right-of-way (1) and commercial vehicle parked/stored at a residence or in a residential district (2).", "The key exception is active use — a commercial vehicle actively loading/unloading or making a delivery/service call is generally not violating; overnight or ongoing storage is the target.", "Confirm the vehicle meets the code's 'commercial motor vehicle' definition before citing."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 12.08.003", name:"Truck Routes", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Offense — misdemeanor per § 12.08.006 (penalty provision); fine per § 1.01.009 (up to $500), each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 12.08.003. Approved and prohibited truck routes/exemptions. [summarized]\nRequires commercial motor vehicles operating in the town to proceed only over designated truck routes, except when accessing an origin or destination in the town not located on a truck route — in which case the vehicle must leave the truck route at the nearest point to the destination and return to the truck route by the shortest possible route. Where a business enterprise operating or utilizing the commercial motor vehicle is located on or adjacent to a truck route, the vehicle must operate only over that truck route; if the business is not on or adjacent to a truck route, the vehicle must reach it by the shortest possible route. The article also provides for establishing 'no truck route(s)' (§ 12.08.004) and posting of restrictions (§ 12.08.005).", summary:"Requires commercial motor vehicles in the town to travel only on designated truck routes, leaving the route only to reach an origin or destination not on a truck route and then by the shortest possible path back. Provides for designating 'no truck routes' and posting restrictions. Penalty provision is § 12.08.006.", street:["A commercial truck off the designated truck route without a local origin/destination justification is the violation — the shortest-route-to-destination rule is the exception, not a general license to leave the route.", "Note whether truck-route or no-truck-route restrictions were posted (§ 12.08.005).", "Turns on the 'commercial motor vehicle' definition and the designated-route map — confirm both."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 12.09.001 – 12.09.003", name:"Speed — Reasonable and Prudent; Prima Facie Limits", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Offense — misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense (§ 12.01.002)", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 12.09.001. Reasonable and prudent speed.\nA person shall not operate a vehicle upon a public street, highway, or alley in the town at a speed greater than is reasonable and prudent under the circumstances then existing, having regard to the actual and potential hazards, and shall use due care. A person shall operate a vehicle at an appropriate reduced speed if approaching or crossing an intersection or railroad grade crossing, and in other stated circumstances.\n\n§ 12.09.002. Prima facie speed limits.\n(a) A person shall not operate a vehicle upon a public street, highway, or alley in the town at a speed greater than the limits established, the established limits being prima facie evidence that the speed is not reasonable and prudent and that the speed is unlawful. The following maximum speed limits are established: (1) 45 miles per hour for streets and highways located outside an urban district; (2) 30 miles per hour for streets and highways located in an urban district; (3) 25 miles per hour for two-lane undivided streets located in a residential/defined district; and (4) 15 miles per hour for alleys and for two-way streets less than 18 feet wide, as specified.\n\n§ 12.09.003. Speed limits on specific streets. [summarized]\nEstablishes altered prima facie speed limits on specific named streets/segments within the town, as set out in the section's schedule.", summary:"Sets the general speed rule (no speed greater than is reasonable and prudent, with reduced speed at intersections and rail crossings) and establishes prima facie maximum limits: 45 mph outside an urban district, 30 mph within an urban district, 25 mph on two-lane undivided residential streets, and 15 mph in alleys and on narrow (<18 ft) two-way streets. Exceeding a prima facie limit is prima facie evidence the speed is unreasonable and unlawful. Section 12.09.003 sets altered limits on specific named streets.", street:["The prima facie limits are the default charging speeds where a segment isn't otherwise posted: 45 outside urban, 30 urban, 25 two-lane residential, 15 alleys/narrow streets.", "Specific named streets carry altered posted limits under § 12.09.003 — check whether the segment has its own established limit before applying the default.", "Exceeding the prima facie limit is prima facie evidence the speed was unlawful, but § 12.09.001's reasonable-and-prudent standard can independently support a charge at or below a posted limit given conditions."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 4.02.002", name:"Sale of Alcoholic Beverages Near a Church, School, or Public Hospital", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["alcohol"], level:"Offense — misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 4.02.002. Sale of alcoholic beverages near a church, school or public hospital.\nIt shall be unlawful to sell alcoholic beverages where the place of business is within 300 feet of a church, public or private school, or public hospital, except as provided by the Texas Alcoholic Beverage Code. The sale of alcoholic beverages is also prohibited within 1,000 feet of a private school if the Town Council adopts by resolution a request from the private school. The measurement of the distance between the place of business where alcoholic beverages are sold and the church or public hospital shall be along the property lines of the street fronts and from front door to front door, and in a direct line across intersections. For a public or private school, the measurement is from the nearest property line of the school to the nearest property line of the place of business, in a direct line.", summary:"Makes it unlawful to sell alcoholic beverages from a place of business within 300 feet of a church, public or private school, or public hospital (except as allowed by the TABC), and within 1,000 feet of a private school where the Town Council has adopted the school's request by resolution. Specifies how the distances are measured (property line/front-door to front-door for churches and hospitals; nearest-property-line to nearest-property-line for schools).", street:["The core distance is 300 feet from a church, school, or public hospital; a private school can extend it to 1,000 feet only if the Town Council adopted its request by resolution.", "Measurement method differs by protected use — church/hospital is front-door-to-front-door along street fronts; school is nearest-property-line to nearest-property-line.", "TABC exceptions apply — a state permit or TABC provision may authorize a sale the 300-foot rule would otherwise bar."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 6.02.063 – 6.02.065", name:"Smoking Prohibited in Certain Public Areas", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["smoking"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 6.02.065, fine up to $2,000, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 6.02.063. Smoking prohibited in certain public areas. [key subsections]\n(a) Owners/operators of regulated areas must, among other things, provide conspicuous signage indicating nonsmoking areas.\n(b) Workplace prohibition. Nothing in this article shall prohibit an employer from designating an entire workplace as nonsmoking.\n(c) Smoking prohibited. A person commits an offense if he/she smokes in an area designated as nonsmoking pursuant to this article.\n\n§ 6.02.065. Penalty.\nAny person violating any provision of this article shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction thereof shall be fined a sum not exceeding $2,000.00. Each continuing day's violation shall constitute a separate offense.", summary:"Prohibits smoking in areas designated as nonsmoking under the article; a person commits an offense by smoking in such a designated nonsmoking area. Regulated owners/operators must post conspicuous nonsmoking signage, and employers may designate an entire workplace as nonsmoking. Penalty: misdemeanor, up to $2,000 (the public-health/sanitation tier), each day a separate offense.", street:["The offense is smoking in an area designated nonsmoking under the article — the designation (and typically signage) is what makes a given area chargeable.", "Note the $2,000 ceiling — this sits in the public-health penalty tier, not the ordinary $500 tier.", "An employer may lawfully designate an entire workplace nonsmoking; the whole premises can therefore be a nonsmoking area."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 6.03.002 – 6.03.006", name:"Regulation of Weeds, Rubbish, Brush (12-Inch Limit)", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["noise"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 6.03.006; fine per § 1.01.009 public-health/sanitation tier (up to $2,000), each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 6.03.002. Regulation of weeds, rubbish, brush, and other objectionable matter. [key subsections]\n(a) The owner or occupant of any property (occupied or unoccupied) shall not keep, store, allow, maintain, or permit rubbish, brush, or other objectionable, unsightly, or unsanitary matter on the property.\n(b) The owner or occupant of any property within the town shall not allow, maintain, or permit grass, weeds, brush, or other unsightly vegetation to grow to a height greater than 12 inches. (Provisions address uncultivated/agricultural properties and adjacent parcels of different ownership.)\n\n§ 6.03.005. Authority to immediately abate dangerous weeds. [summarized] Authorizes immediate abatement where weeds present a danger, following the article's procedures.\n\n§ 6.03.006. Penalty for violation.\nA violation of this article is a misdemeanor punishable by a fine as provided in § 1.01.009 of this Code (up to $2,000 for public-health and sanitation violations), and each day a violation continues is a separate offense.", summary:"Prohibits an owner or occupant from allowing grass, weeds, brush, or other unsightly vegetation to exceed 12 inches in height, and from keeping rubbish, brush, or other objectionable/unsanitary matter on the property (occupied or unoccupied). Provides for immediate abatement of dangerous weeds. Penalty: misdemeanor, fine in the § 1.01.009 public-health/sanitation tier (up to $2,000), each day a separate offense.", street:["The concrete standard is the 12-inch height limit on grass/weeds/brush — the common code-compliance measurement on an overgrown-lot complaint.", "Applies to occupied and unoccupied property alike, and reaches the owner or the occupant.", "Public-health/sanitation tier — up to $2,000, each day a separate offense; enforcement typically runs through code compliance with notice/abatement."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 5.04.001 – 5.04.007", name:"Fireworks Prohibited", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["firearms"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 5.04.007; fine per § 1.01.009 fire-safety tier (up to $2,000), each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 5.04.003. Prohibited.\nIt shall be unlawful for any person to manufacture, assemble, store, transport, receive, keep, sell, offer or have in their possession with the intent to sell, use, discharge, cause to be discharged, ignite, detonate, fire or otherwise set in action any fireworks of any description within the town.\n\n§ 5.04.004. Exceptions.\nThis article shall not apply to signal flares and torpedoes of the railroad for use in railroad operation; to certain items sold in hardware/other stores as specified; nor to signal flares or rockets for lawful signaling purposes; and the Town Council may adopt reasonable rules for permitted public displays.\n\n§ 5.04.005. Permit and bond for public display. [summarized] Public fireworks displays require a permit and bond as set out in the article.\n\n§ 5.04.006. Public nuisance. Fireworks kept, stored, or used in violation of this article are declared a public nuisance.\n\n§ 5.04.007. Penalty for violation.\nA violation of this article is a misdemeanor punishable by a fine as provided in § 1.01.009 of this Code (up to $2,000 for fire-safety violations), each day a separate offense.", summary:"Broadly prohibits fireworks within the town — manufacturing, storing, transporting, keeping, selling or possessing with intent to sell, using, or discharging fireworks of any description. Exceptions cover railroad signal devices, certain lawfully sold items, and signal flares/rockets, and the Town Council may permit public displays (which require a permit and bond). Fireworks kept or used in violation are a public nuisance. Penalty: misdemeanor, fire-safety tier (up to $2,000), each day a separate offense.", street:["The prohibition is broad: possession, sale, storage, transport, and discharge of fireworks anywhere in town are all reachable, not just discharge.", "Permitted public displays are the main lawful exception — check for a § 5.04.005 permit and bond before treating a display as a violation.", "Fire-safety tier — up to $2,000. Fireworks in violation are also a declared public nuisance, supporting abatement."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 1.09.003 – 1.09.004", name:"Park and Facility Hours", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["parks"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 1.09.026, fine up to $500 (up to $2,000 for public-health/sanitation violations), each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 1.09.003. Park hours.\n(a) Hours of general neighborhood park use shall normally be from 30 minutes before sunrise to 30 minutes after sunset. Hours of general community park or game or playing field use shall normally be from 30 minutes before sunrise to 10:00 p.m. Parks shall be open for the hours posted, and it is unlawful to be present in a park outside of the posted or established hours except as authorized.\n\n§ 1.09.004. Community center/recreational facility hours. [summarized] Establishes the hours of operation for community centers and recreational facilities; presence outside authorized hours is regulated as set out in the section.", summary:"Sets park hours — neighborhood parks generally from 30 minutes before sunrise to 30 minutes after sunset, and community parks/playing fields from 30 minutes before sunrise to 10:00 p.m. — and makes it unlawful to be present in a park outside the posted or established hours except as authorized. Section 1.09.004 sets community-center and recreational-facility hours.", street:["The default closing is 30 minutes after sunset for neighborhood parks and 10:00 p.m. for community parks/fields — presence after hours is the common after-dark park-closure charge.", "Hours are 'normally' as stated but can be posted differently — go by the posted hours at the specific park.", "Penalty routes through § 1.09.026 (up to $500, or $2,000 for sanitation-type violations)."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 1.09.012", name:"Glass Containers in Parks and Pools Prohibited", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["parks"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 1.09.026, fine up to $500, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 1.09.012. Glass or glass beverage containers and other dangerous items.\nIt shall be unlawful to possess on the premises of any swimming pool, recreational center, or any other park area any glass beverage containers. It shall also be unlawful to willfully break any glass container in any swimming pool, recreation center, or any park area.", summary:"Makes it unlawful to possess glass beverage containers on the premises of any swimming pool, recreation center, or other park area, and unlawful to willfully break any glass container in those areas.", street:["Two offenses: possession of glass beverage containers in a pool/rec-center/park area, and willfully breaking any glass container there.", "Straightforward, observable park-safety violation — no intent required for the possession prong."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 1.09.015", name:"Leaving a Child Under Seven Unattended in a Park", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["parks"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 1.09.026, fine up to $500, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 1.09.015. Unlawful to leave child under age seven unattended.\nIt shall be unlawful for a parent, guardian, or other adult having care, custody and/or control of a child to abandon or in any way leave unattended a child (under seven years of age) in any park or other recreational area of the town.", summary:"Makes it unlawful for a parent, guardian, or other adult with care, custody, or control of a child under seven years of age to abandon or leave that child unattended in any park or recreational area of the town.", street:["Applies specifically to children under seven left unattended in a park or recreational area — the age threshold and the location are the elements.", "Runs to any adult with care, custody, or control, not only a parent."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 1.09.017", name:"Firearms, Fireworks, and Projectiles in Parks", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["parks"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 1.09.026, fine up to $500, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 1.09.017. Firearms, fireworks, etc.\nIt shall be unlawful for any person to discharge firearms, and carry or discharge fireworks, air guns, bows and arrows, slingshots or any other weapon or device that may create a fire hazard or any hazard or danger to the public in a park, except with joint written approval of the Parks and Recreation Department and as otherwise permitted. Nothing in this section shall be construed to contravene the applicable state statute regulating the carrying or use of firearms.", summary:"Makes it unlawful in a park to discharge firearms and to carry or discharge fireworks, air guns, bows and arrows, slingshots, or any other weapon or device that may create a fire hazard or danger to the public, except with joint written approval of the Parks and Recreation Department. The section expressly does not contravene applicable state law on the carrying or use of firearms.", street:["The section is careful not to override state firearm-carry law — read the firearms prong as reaching discharge and hazardous devices, not lawful carry that state law protects.", "Fireworks, air guns, bows and arrows, and slingshots in a park are the clearly chargeable items here absent Parks Department approval.", "The unifying element is creating a fire hazard or danger to the public in the park."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 3.16.002", name:"Location of Pools and Spas", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["general"], level:"Offense — misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 3.16.002. Location of pools and spas.\nPools and spas located in districts zoned as Agricultural, Single-Family, Townhome, and Two-Family shall be subject to the following: (1) Pools and spas shall have a required minimum side yard setback of three feet; (2) Pools and spas shall have a required minimum backyard setback of three feet; (3) No pool or spa is allowed in the required front yard of any lot; and additional placement requirements as set out in the section. The town's adopted swimming pool and spa code (§ 3.16.001) governs barrier and safety requirements.", summary:"Sets placement requirements for pools and spas in Agricultural, Single-Family, Townhome, and Two-Family zoning districts: a minimum three-foot side-yard setback, a minimum three-foot backyard setback, and no pool or spa in a required front yard. Barrier and safety requirements are governed by the adopted swimming pool and spa code (§ 3.16.001).", street:["Placement standards: 3-foot side and rear setbacks, and no pool/spa in a required front yard, in the listed residential/agricultural districts.", "Pool-barrier and enclosure safety requirements live in the adopted pool/spa code (§ 3.16.001), not this placement section — check there for fence/gate/self-latching requirements on an unsecured-pool complaint."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances § 3.19.001", name:"Fence Regulations", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["general"], level:"Offense — misdemeanor; fine per § 1.01.009 general penalty (up to $500), each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"§ 3.19.001. General regulations.\nFences in all zoning districts shall meet the following requirements (key provisions):\n(1) Permit. A fence permit must be obtained from the town; it is unlawful for any person to install, cause to be installed, or permit installation of a fence, or to make alterations, additions, or changes to a fence, without first procuring a permit. A permit is not required for repairs not exceeding 16 linear feet of the fence area over a 12-month period.\n(2) Drainage easements. No fence shall be constructed in a manner that obstructs a drainage easement, subject to the Building Official's determination.\n(Additional provisions govern height, materials, and location; see the full section.)", summary:"Sets general fence requirements in all zoning districts. Installing a fence, or making alterations/additions/changes to one, without first obtaining a town fence permit is unlawful (repairs under 16 linear feet over a 12-month period are exempt from the permit requirement). Additional provisions govern drainage-easement obstruction, height, materials, and location.", street:["The chargeable hook is installing or materially altering a fence without a permit; minor repairs (under 16 linear feet in 12 months) are exempt.", "Height, material, and location limits also live in this section — an over-height or prohibited-material fence can violate independent of the permit issue.", "Fence complaints are typically code-compliance matters; confirm the specific requirement (permit, height, easement) before citing."] },
  { ord:"Prosper Code of Ordinances §§ 3.12.001 – 3.12.013", name:"Vacant and Substandard Structures", city:"Prosper, TX", cats:["general"], level:"Enforcement runs through securing/abatement process; violations chargeable per § 1.01.009 (up to $2,000 for public-health/safety). Primarily code-compliance, not a patrol offense.", lvlClass:"p", text:"§ 3.12.003. Securing vacant structures. [summarized]\nRequires the owner of a vacant structure that is open and accessible, or otherwise meeting the article's criteria, to secure it against unauthorized entry, and authorizes the town to act where the owner fails to do so.\n\n§ 3.12.005. Substandard declaration. [summarized]\nProvides for declaring a structure substandard where it fails to meet minimum standards (e.g., dilapidation, structural hazard, or conditions dangerous to health or safety), triggering the article's inspection, notice, hearing, and repair/removal/demolition process.\n\n§§ 3.12.006 – 3.12.013 [summarized]\nSet out inspections, notice of violation, application of standards, hearing, appeal, notice of repair/removal/demolition, demolition/removal/repair expenses, and assessment of a lien to recover the town's costs.", summary:"Governs vacant and substandard structures: requires owners to secure open/accessible vacant structures against unauthorized entry (§ 3.12.003), and provides for declaring a structure substandard (§ 3.12.005) with a full inspection, notice, hearing, appeal, and repair/removal/demolition process (§§ 3.12.006–3.12.013), including recovery of the town's costs by lien. This is primarily an administrative code-compliance framework rather than a patrol charging section.", street:["Primarily a code-compliance/abatement process, not a patrol offense — the practical patrol relevance is an unsecured open vacant structure (§ 3.12.003), which bears on trespass/criminal-activity calls.", "A 'substandard' or 'dangerous' structure designation carries a notice-and-hearing process before repair, removal, or demolition.", "Costs of abatement can be assessed as a lien against the property (§ 3.12.013)."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances § 70-2", name:"Residency Requirements of Sex Offenders", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["sexoffender"], level:"Misdemeanor; fine up to $500, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 70-2. Residency requirements of sex offenders.\n(b) Residency requirements.\n(1) It is unlawful for a person to establish a permanent or temporary residence within 1,000 feet of any premises where children commonly gather if the person is required to register on the Texas Department of Public Safety sex offender database because of a victim who was younger than 17 years of age.\n(2) For purposes of this section, premises where children commonly gather includes a school, licensed day-care facility, playground, public or private youth center, public swimming pool, video arcade facility, or other premises where children commonly gather, as defined herein.\n(c) Evidentiary matters; measurements.\n(2) For the purposes of determining the minimum distance separation, the requirement shall be measured by following a straight line from the outer property line of the permanent or temporary residence to the nearest property line of the premises where children commonly gather; in the case of multiple residences on one property, measuring from the nearest property line of the premises to the nearest property line of the premises where children commonly gather.\n(3) A map depicting the prohibited areas shall be maintained by the town.\n(d) Culpable mental state. Neither allegation nor evidence of a culpable mental state is required for the proof of an offense defined by this section.\n(e) Affirmative defenses include: the person established the residence and complied with sex-offender registration before this section's adoption; the person was a minor when the offense was committed and not convicted as an adult; the person is a minor; or the premises where children commonly gather opened after the person established residence.", summary:"Makes it unlawful for a person required to register on the Texas DPS sex offender database (because of a victim under 17) to establish a permanent or temporary residence within 1,000 feet of a 'premises where children commonly gather' — schools, licensed day cares, playgrounds, youth centers, public pools, video arcades, and similar. Distance is measured property-line to property-line, with a town-maintained prohibited-areas map. No culpable mental state is required. Affirmative defenses (§ 70-2(e)) include a residence predating the section or the qualifying premises.", street:["Little Elm's buffer is 1,000 feet (same as Frisco; note Prosper's is 2,000 — don't cross-apply between cities).", "Verify DPS registration status and that the qualifying offense involved a victim under 17 before applying the restriction.", "No culpable mental state required — strict-liability-style residency violation once elements are met.", "Check the § 70-2(e) affirmative defenses (residence predating the section or the qualifying premises) before referral. Little Elm pairs this with a separate child-safety-zone offense (§ 70-3)."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances § 70-3", name:"Child Safety Zones", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["sexoffender"], level:"Misdemeanor; fine up to $500, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 70-3. Child safety zones.\n(1) It shall be unlawful for a person who is required to register on the Texas Department of Public Safety sex offender database (because of a victim who was younger than 17 years of age) to go in, on, or within 1,000 feet of a premises where children commonly gather. A person required to register may enter into the 1,000-foot zone surrounding premises where children commonly gather only under the limited circumstances specified in this section (e.g., to transport a resident child, to attend to certain personal or governmental business, or with authorization), and additional provisions address when a registrant is otherwise within the 1,000-foot zone.\n(Definitions of 'premises where children commonly gather' and the measurement method parallel § 70-2. Affirmative defenses and culpable-mental-state provisions apply as set out in the article.)", summary:"Makes it unlawful for a person required to register on the DPS sex offender database (victim under 17) to go in, on, or within 1,000 feet of a premises where children commonly gather, subject to limited specified exceptions for entering the 1,000-foot zone (such as transporting a resident child or attending to necessary business). This is a presence/loitering restriction distinct from the § 70-2 residency restriction.", street:["This is the going-near / presence offense — distinct from the § 70-2 residency restriction. A registrant physically present within 1,000 feet of a child-gathering premises can violate this even if they don't live there.", "Limited exceptions allow entering the 1,000-foot zone (e.g., transporting a resident child or necessary business) — confirm none applies before citing.", "Same 1,000-foot measurement and 'premises where children commonly gather' definition as § 70-2."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances § 70-4", name:"Public Urination or Defecation", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["publicconduct"], level:"Misdemeanor; fine up to $500", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 70-4. Public urination or defecation.\n(a) A person commits an offense if the person urinates or defecates:\n(1) On public property or in a public place; or\n(2) In public view.\n(b) For the purpose of this section, public place means any place to which the public or a substantial group of the public has access, including but not limited to streets, sidewalks, parks, and the common areas of buildings and facilities.\n(c) It is a defense to prosecution under this section if the person was in a restroom.", summary:"Makes it an offense to urinate or defecate on public property, in a public place, or in public view. 'Public place' is broadly defined as anywhere the public or a substantial group has access. It is a defense to prosecution that the person was in a restroom.", street:["The 'in public view' element is independent of being on public property — this can be charged for conduct on private property visible to the public.", "The restroom defense is the primary carve-out; confirm whether a restroom was actually used."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 70-54 – 70-60", name:"Noise Control", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["noise"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 70-59, fine up to $500, each a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 70-55. Loud or disturbing noises; specific instances. [key provisions]\nNo person shall make, continue, or cause to be made or continued any unreasonably loud or disturbing noise which is offensive to the ordinary sensibilities of the residents of the town, or which renders the enjoyment of life or property uncomfortable or interferes with public peace and comfort. The following (among others) can create unreasonably loud or disturbing noises in violation of the article, unless exempt under § 70-56 or permitted under § 70-57: operating sound-production or -reproduction devices (radios, TVs, musical instruments, loudspeakers, amplifiers) within a residential district or quiet zone, or within 500 feet of any residence or quiet zone, so as to cause a noise disturbance; operating power equipment (excluding construction equipment) within a residential area or within 500 feet of any residence during restricted hours; and other enumerated activities.\n\nSec. 70-56. Exemptions. [summarized] Includes certain governmental, emergency, school, religious, and permitted activities.\n\nSec. 70-59. Penalty.\nAny person violating any provision of this article shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction thereof shall be punished by a fine not to exceed $500.00, and a separate offense shall be deemed committed each day.\n\nSec. 70-60. Injunctive relief. The town may seek injunctive relief in addition to any penalty.", summary:"Prohibits unreasonably loud or disturbing noise offensive to ordinary sensibilities, that renders enjoyment of life or property uncomfortable, or interferes with public peace — enumerating (non-exclusively) violating activities such as sound devices operated within a residential district/quiet zone or within 500 feet of a residence, and power equipment used near residences during restricted hours. Subject to exemptions (§ 70-56) and variance permits (§ 70-57). Penalty: misdemeanor, up to $500, each day a separate offense, with injunctive relief available.", street:["The core standard is the 'ordinary sensibilities of residents' — a subjective-disturbance ordinance, not a fixed decibel limit, so document why the noise was unreasonable in context.", "The 500-foot-from-a-residence trigger for sound devices and power equipment is the concrete measurement to anchor a residential-noise call.", "Check § 70-56 exemptions and whether a § 70-57 variance permit was issued before citing."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 70-21 – 70-25", name:"Litter in Public Places and from Vehicles", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["publicconduct"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 70-25, fine up to $500, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 70-22. Throwing or depositing litter in public places prohibited.\nA person commits an offense if he throws or deposits litter in or upon any public place within the town, except in public or private trash receptacles in a manner that prevents the litter from being carried away or deposited by the elements.\n\nSec. 70-23. Receptacles. [summarized] Addresses placement and use of trash receptacles.\n\nSec. 70-24. Throwing or depositing litter from vehicles prohibited.\n(a) A person in a motor vehicle or on a bicycle commits an offense if he throws or deposits litter from such vehicle or bicycle onto a public place or onto private property.\n(b) A person operating a motor vehicle commits an offense if he allows litter to be blown or to fall from the vehicle in a manner that litters a public place.\n\nSec. 70-25. Penalty.\nA violation of this article shall be punished by a fine not to exceed the sum of $500.00, and each day shall be deemed to constitute a separate offense.", summary:"Prohibits throwing or depositing litter in any public place except in proper receptacles (§ 70-22), and prohibits throwing or depositing litter from a motor vehicle or bicycle onto a public place or private property, or allowing litter to blow or fall from a vehicle (§ 70-24). Penalty: misdemeanor, up to $500, each day a separate offense.", street:["The vehicle-litter offense (§ 70-24) is the practical traffic-stop hook — tossing litter from a car or bicycle, or an unsecured load letting litter blow out.", "'Litter' is defined by reference to garbage, refuse, and rubbish; the receptacle exception requires the litter be secured against the elements."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 70-102 – 70-109", name:"Graffiti; Possession of Graffiti Paraphernalia", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["publicconduct"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 70-109, fine up to $500, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 70-104. Unlawful to apply; prohibition of defacement.\nIt is unlawful for any person to apply graffiti to any trees, structures, or other real or personal property, whether public or private, without the consent of the owner.\n\nSec. 70-105. Possession of graffiti paraphernalia on school property by minors prohibited.\n(a) It is unlawful for any minor to have in his or her possession any graffiti paraphernalia while on any school property, grounds, or facilities. It is an affirmative defense that the possession of felt-tip markers by minors attending, or with permission to be on, the school property was for legitimate school-related purposes.\n\nSec. 70-106. Possession of graffiti paraphernalia prohibited in designated places.\nIt is unlawful for any person to possess graffiti paraphernalia in or on designated public places (such as public facilities, parks, or rights-of-way) where signs prohibiting such possession are posted, as specified.\n\nSec. 70-108. Graffiti declared public nuisance. Graffiti is declared a public nuisance subject to abatement.\n\nSec. 70-109. Penalties. A violation is a misdemeanor punishable by a fine not to exceed $500.00, each day a separate offense.", summary:"Makes it unlawful to apply graffiti to any public or private property without the owner's consent (§ 70-104), and criminalizes possession of graffiti paraphernalia by minors on school property (§ 70-105, with an affirmative defense for legitimate school use of markers) and by any person in posted designated places (§ 70-106). Graffiti is declared a public nuisance subject to abatement. Penalty: misdemeanor, up to $500, each day a separate offense.", street:["Three distinct offenses: applying graffiti (§ 70-104), a minor possessing graffiti paraphernalia on school property (§ 70-105), and possession in a posted designated place (§ 70-106).", "The school-property paraphernalia offense has an affirmative defense for legitimate school use of markers — check that before citing a student.", "The designated-places offense (§ 70-106) depends on the area being posted; note whether signage was present."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 70-126 – 70-135", name:"Discharging and Carrying Firearms and Projectile Weapons", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["firearms"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 70-135, fine up to $500 for each offense, each a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 70-130. Discharging and carrying firearms and projectile weapons. [key subsections]\n(a) It shall be unlawful for any person, other than a peace officer, to carry a firearm in any town building or other municipal property, unless the person is duly licensed by the state to carry a concealed handgun and pursuant to state law may carry a concealed handgun in that building or on that property. It shall be unlawful for any person to carry a firearm or prohibited weapon (as defined under state law) into a prohibited place.\n(b) It shall be unlawful for any person to discharge any gun, pistol, rifle, firearm, or bow and arrow of any kind within the town limits, except: within a properly permitted/licensed shooting facility or range as provided in this article; in the lawful defense of person or property; by a peace officer in the discharge of official duty; or as otherwise permitted by state law.\n\nSec. 70-127. Permit required; §§ 70-128 – 70-134 address application, issuance, government shooting facilities, renewal/revocation, appeal, and exceptions.\n\nSec. 70-135. Penalty.\nAny person violating this article shall be deemed guilty of a misdemeanor, and upon conviction thereof shall be fined any sum not in excess of $500.00 for each offense, plus court costs, each a separate offense.", summary:"Regulates firearms and projectile weapons: prohibits carrying a firearm in a town building or on municipal property (except a state-licensed concealed handgun carried where state law allows, and except peace officers), and prohibits discharging any gun, firearm, or bow and arrow within the town limits — with exceptions for permitted ranges/shooting facilities, lawful defense of person or property, peace officers on duty, and as otherwise permitted by state law. A permit scheme (§§ 70-127 – 70-134) governs authorized shooting facilities. Penalty: misdemeanor, up to $500 per offense.", street:["Two hooks: unlawful carry in a town building/municipal property (state-licensed concealed carry where permitted is excepted), and unlawful discharge within town limits.", "Discharge exceptions are the key defenses: permitted range, lawful self-defense of person or property, and on-duty peace officer.", "The section is written to respect state concealed-carry law — apply the carry prohibition consistently with state carry rights."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 70-150 – 70-156", name:"Restricted Smoking Materials (Synthetic Cannabinoids)", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["smoking"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 70-156, fine up to $500", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 70-151. Restricted smoking materials; purpose. [summarized] Defines 'restricted smoking materials' (synthetic cannabinoid/chemical smoking products and similar substances) and states the public-health purpose.\n\nSec. 70-152. Sale, delivery, offer or gift. It shall be unlawful for any person to sell, deliver, offer, or give restricted smoking materials within the corporate limits of the town.\n\nSec. 70-153. Use or possession of restricted smoking material. It shall be unlawful for any person to have in their possession or to use restricted smoking materials within the corporate limits of the town.\n\nSec. 70-154. Use or possession of restricted smoking paraphernalia. It shall be unlawful for any person to have in their possession restricted smoking paraphernalia. It is a violation if a person is found in possession of paraphernalia showing traces of restricted smoking material (as established by testing).\n\nSec. 70-155. Defenses to prosecution. [summarized] Includes limited circumstances such as authorized medical or governmental handling.\n\nSec. 70-156. Offenses and penalties. A violation is a misdemeanor infraction, punishable by a fine not to exceed $500.00.", summary:"Prohibits the sale/delivery/offer/gift (§ 70-152), and the use or possession (§ 70-153), of 'restricted smoking materials' — synthetic cannabinoid/chemical smoking products — within the town, and prohibits possession of restricted smoking paraphernalia, including paraphernalia showing traces of the material on testing (§ 70-154). Limited defenses apply (§ 70-155). Penalty: misdemeanor, up to $500.", street:["This is the local synthetic-cannabinoid ('K2'/'spice') ordinance — it reaches possession and use, not just sale, and covers paraphernalia that tests positive for traces.", "Confirm the substance fits the § 70-151 'restricted smoking materials' definition; these ordinances turn on that defined term.", "Paraphernalia with tested traces is independently chargeable under § 70-154."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 70-206 – 70-211", name:"Smoking Prohibited in Certain Public Places", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["smoking"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 70-211, fine up to $500", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 70-207. Smoking prohibited in certain public places.\nA person commits an offense in violation of this article if he smokes, or uses an e-cigarette or liquid nicotine, in most public places and enclosed places of employment within the town, except in places specifically identified in § 70-208 as places where smoking is not prohibited.\n\nSec. 70-208. Places where smoking is not prohibited. [summarized] Lists exceptions (e.g., certain outdoor areas, private residences, and other specified locations).\n\nSec. 70-209. Posting of signs. Owners/operators must post required no-smoking signage.\n\nSec. 70-210. Enforcement. [summarized]\n\nSec. 70-211. Offenses and penalties. A person who violates this article is guilty of a misdemeanor infraction, punishable by a fine not to exceed $500.00.", summary:"Prohibits smoking — including use of e-cigarettes or liquid nicotine — in most public places and enclosed places of employment within the town, except in the locations listed in § 70-208. Owners/operators must post no-smoking signage. Penalty: misdemeanor, up to $500.", street:["The prohibition expressly includes e-cigarettes and liquid nicotine, not just combustible tobacco.", "Check § 70-208 for the location exceptions before citing — the offense turns on the place being one where smoking is prohibited under the article.", "This is distinct from the § 70-150 restricted-smoking-materials (synthetic drug) offense — different article, different subject."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances § 70-181", name:"Compliance with Officer's Order; Obstruction of Duty", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["publicconduct"], level:"Misdemeanor; fine up to $500", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 70-181. Compliance with order of officer required; obstruction of duty prohibited.\n(a) A person commits an offense if the person fails or refuses to comply with an order or direction of a peace officer that is lawfully given in the discharge of the officer's official duty.\n(b) A person commits an offense if the person knowingly obstructs, prevents, or interferes with a peace officer engaged in the discharge of the officer's official duty.\n(c) It is a defense to prosecution under this section that the peace officer's order or direction, or the duty being performed, is unlawful.", summary:"Makes it an offense to fail or refuse to comply with a peace officer's lawful order or direction given in the discharge of official duty (a), or to knowingly obstruct, prevent, or interfere with a peace officer engaged in official duty (b). It is a defense that the officer's order or the duty being performed was unlawful (c).", street:["Two prongs: failure to comply with a lawful order/direction (a), and knowingly obstructing/interfering with an officer's duty (b).", "The lawfulness of the order or duty is built into the offense — the (c) defense means an unlawful order can't ground the charge.", "This is a town-ordinance obstruction hook; the order or duty being obstructed must be lawful and within official duty."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances § 18-115", name:"Restraint of Animals", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor; fine up to $500 (§ 18-46), each animal/day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 18-115. Restraint of animals.\n(a) It shall be unlawful for an owner or person in control of an animal to fail to keep the animal under restraint in a securely enclosed area, or under the immediate control of the owner, so as to protect the public and other animals — except for animals owned or under the control of the owner on the owner's own premises.\n(b) It shall be unlawful for an owner to fail or refuse to exercise proper care and control of an animal to prevent it from becoming a public nuisance by running at-large.\n(Restraint methods, including leash requirements, are defined in section 18-1.)", summary:"Requires owners to keep animals under restraint — securely enclosed or under the owner's immediate control — to protect the public and other animals, and makes it unlawful to allow an animal to run at-large and become a public nuisance. Restraint methods and leash requirements are defined in § 18-1.", street:["Core hooks: animal not under restraint (a) and running at-large as a public nuisance (b).", "'Restraint' and leash specifics are defined in § 18-1 — check that definition for the applicable leash/enclosure standard.", "Applies to the owner or the person in control of the animal."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 18-158 – 18-163", name:"Dangerous Animals (Other Than Dogs) — Requirements", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Violation is a misdemeanor (§ 18-162); fine up to $500 (§ 18-46). Owner must register, secure, muzzle, and carry $100,000 liability insurance.", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 18-159. Finding of an animal as 'dangerous'. [summarized] Establishes the process for determining an animal (other than a dog) to be dangerous.\n\nSec. 18-160. Requirements for owner of dangerous animal.\nAn owner of an animal determined dangerous must, among other requirements: (1) Register the dangerous animal with the animal services officer; keep the animal under the owner's immediate control or in a 'secure enclosure' as defined in § 18-1 (and, if not in a secure pen, dangerous dogs shall be securely leashed/muzzled as specified); (4) Obtain liability insurance coverage or show financial responsibility in an amount of at least $100,000.00 to cover damages to a person, and provide proof of the required liability insurance. Additional signage and confinement requirements apply.\n\nSec. 18-161. Failure to comply with requirements; Sec. 18-162. Violations. [summarized] A person who owns or controls a dangerous animal commits an offense by failing to comply with any requirement of this division or an order issued under it.\n\nSec. 18-163. Defense. [summarized] Provides a defense for veterinarians, peace officers, and shelter/government personnel acting within official duties.", summary:"Sets requirements for the owner of an animal (other than a dog) determined dangerous: register it with the animal services officer, keep it under immediate control or in a secure enclosure (with leash/muzzle requirements when not penned), meet signage and confinement requirements, and carry at least $100,000 in liability insurance or financial responsibility. Failure to comply is an offense (§ 18-162). Defenses exist for veterinarians, peace officers, and shelter/government personnel (§ 18-163).", street:["Owner checklist for a determined-dangerous animal: registered, secured (enclosure or immediate control), muzzled/leashed when not penned, signed, and $100,000 insurance. Any failure is chargeable under § 18-162.", "'Dangerous animal' generally requires a prior finding (§ 18-159) — confirm the determination before applying these requirements.", "Note Little Elm splits dangerous DOGS into a separate division (§§ 18-180–189) — this division covers dangerous animals other than dogs."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 18-180 – 18-189", name:"Dangerous Dogs — Determination, Requirements, Attack", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Attack (§ 18-171/analog) is a Class C misdemeanor; Class A if serious bodily injury or death. Owner requirements violation is a misdemeanor (up to $500, § 18-46).", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 18-180. Dangerous dog determination; Sec. 18-181. Dangerous dog incident; Sec. 18-182. Reporting of incident; Sec. 18-183. Hearing for dangerous dog determination. [summarized] Establish the process by which a dog is determined dangerous, including incident reporting and a hearing.\n\nSec. 18-184. Failure to comply; Sec. 18-185. Destruction of dog; Sec. 18-186. Failure to surrender dog. [summarized] Address non-compliance, destruction, and surrender.\n\nSec. 18-187. Additional requirements for owners of a dangerous dog.\nAn owner of a registered dangerous dog must comply with registration, secure-enclosure, restraint, insurance, and notification requirements — including notifying the office and any new owner/keeper if the dog is sold or moved.\n\nSec. 18-188. Culpable mental state. Neither allegation nor evidence of a culpable mental state is required to prove an offense under this division.\n\nAttack provision. A person commits an offense if the person is the owner of a dangerous dog and the dog makes an unprovoked attack on a person or another animal outside the dog's enclosure and causes bodily injury; the offense is a Class C misdemeanor, unless the attack causes serious bodily injury or death, in which event it is a Class A misdemeanor.", summary:"Establishes a separate dangerous-dog framework: a determination process with incident reporting and a hearing (§§ 18-180–183), consequences for non-compliance including destruction and surrender (§§ 18-184–186), and owner requirements (registration, secure enclosure, restraint, insurance, and notification on sale/move) (§ 18-187). No culpable mental state is required (§ 18-188). An unprovoked attack by a dangerous dog outside its enclosure causing bodily injury is a Class C misdemeanor, elevated to Class A on serious bodily injury or death.", street:["Little Elm tracks dangerous DOGS separately from other dangerous animals — this division (18-180+) is the dog-specific one, mirroring the state Health & Safety Code dangerous-dog process.", "Attack penalty escalates on injury: Class C by default, Class A if serious bodily injury or death.", "No culpable mental state required (§ 18-188).", "On sale or relocation of a registered dangerous dog, the owner must notify the office and the new keeper (§ 18-187)."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 18-141 – 18-142", name:"Rabies Reporting; Bite Quarantine", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor; fine up to $500 (§ 18-46)", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 18-141. Reporting of rabies cases or suspected rabid animal required; confinement of animals.\nRequires reporting of rabies cases or a suspected rabid animal and provides for confinement of animals as specified.\n\nSec. 18-142. Procedure when animal has bitten person or animal; exceptions thereto; quarantine fees.\nEstablishes the procedure when an animal has bitten a person or another animal — including quarantine/observation for the period during which rabies transmission could have occurred (or longer as directed), exceptions, and applicable quarantine fees. (State rabies law is adopted by reference in § 18-140.)", summary:"Requires reporting of rabies cases or suspected rabid animals and confinement as specified (§ 18-141), and sets the procedure when an animal bites a person or another animal — quarantine/observation, exceptions, and quarantine fees (§ 18-142). State rabies law is adopted by reference (§ 18-140).", street:["A bite that may expose a person triggers the § 18-142 quarantine/observation process — don't release the animal prematurely; coordinate with the rabies/animal-services authority.", "Reporting a suspected rabid animal is itself required under § 18-141.", "State rabies law is adopted by reference (§ 18-140), so the state framework applies alongside these local procedures."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances § 18-189", name:"Dogs That Attack Domestic Animals", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["animal"], level:"Misdemeanor; fine up to $500 (§ 18-46). May trigger dangerous-dog determination.", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 18-189. Dogs that attack domestic animals.\nAddresses dogs that attack domestic animals — including that dogs deemed dangerous due to attacks on domestic animals shall adhere to the procedures relative to dangerous dogs, and provides for the handling and consequences of such attacks as set out in the section.", summary:"Addresses dogs that attack domestic animals: a dog deemed dangerous due to attacks on domestic animals must adhere to the dangerous-dog procedures, and the section provides for the handling and consequences of such attacks.", street:["An attack on a domestic animal (livestock/pet) can itself push a dog into the dangerous-dog track and its requirements.", "Distinct from an attack on a person — this section specifically covers domestic-animal victims."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 98-102 – 98-104", name:"Parking of Oversized/Commercial Vehicles; Residential Parking", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 98-109, fine up to $500, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 98-102. Parking of oversized vehicles or commercial motor vehicles.\n(1) It shall be unlawful for any person to park or store, or allow to be parked or stored, any oversized vehicle or commercial motor vehicle upon any public street, alley, or public right-of-way, except as specifically permitted (e.g., active loading/unloading or as otherwise excepted).\n\nSec. 98-103. Parking in nonresidential districts; Sec. 98-104. Parking in residential districts. [summarized] Regulate where oversized/commercial vehicles may be parked in nonresidential and residential districts, including prohibitions on parking or storing such vehicles in residential districts except for temporary active use (delivery/service).", summary:"Prohibits parking or storing an oversized vehicle or commercial motor vehicle on any public street, alley, or right-of-way (§ 98-102), and regulates such parking in nonresidential and residential districts (§§ 98-103–104), including barring storage of oversized/commercial vehicles in residential districts except for temporary active use. Penalty per § 98-109.", street:["Two common violations: oversized/commercial vehicle on the public right-of-way (§ 98-102) and stored at a residence/in a residential district (§ 98-104).", "Active loading/unloading or a temporary delivery/service call is the usual exception — overnight or ongoing storage is the target.", "Confirm the vehicle meets the 'oversized' or 'commercial motor vehicle' definition (§ 98-100)."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 98-105 – 98-107", name:"Prohibited Parking; Fire Lanes", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 98-109, fine up to $500, each day a separate offense", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 98-105. Prohibited parking in certain places. [summarized] Enumerates places where stopping, standing, or parking is prohibited (e.g., in front of driveways, on sidewalks, in intersections, and other listed locations), consistent with state law.\n\nSec. 98-107. Fire lanes.\nPursuant to Health and Safety Code § 431.001, it is hereby declared unlawful to park or stand a vehicle in any designated fire lane appropriately marked on privately owned or public property. Fire lanes must be marked as specified, and vehicles parked in violation are subject to citation and removal.\n\nSec. 98-108. Declared a public nuisance. A vehicle parked in violation may be declared a public nuisance and removed.", summary:"Enumerates places where parking is prohibited (§ 98-105) and makes it unlawful to park or stand a vehicle in any designated, appropriately marked fire lane on private or public property (§ 98-107), with violating vehicles subject to citation, nuisance declaration, and removal (§ 98-108). Penalty per § 98-109.", street:["Fire-lane parking (§ 98-107) is enforceable on private property too, as long as the lane is appropriately marked — check the marking.", "§ 98-105 is the general prohibited-parking list (driveways, sidewalks, intersections, etc.).", "A violating vehicle can be declared a public nuisance and removed (§ 98-108) in addition to the citation."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 98-124 – 98-126", name:"Motor-Assisted Scooters", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 98-126, fine up to $500", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 98-125. Restrictions and prohibitions for motor assisted scooters.\n(1) It is unlawful for a child to operate or ride a motor-assisted scooter on any path, trail, alley, street, or highway within the town, except as specifically permitted (with additional restrictions on where and how motor-assisted scooters may be operated, and equipment/age requirements as set out in the section).\n\nSec. 98-126. Penalty. A violation is a misdemeanor punishable by a fine up to $500.00.", summary:"Restricts and, for children, prohibits operation of motor-assisted scooters on paths, trails, alleys, streets, or highways within the town, with equipment, location, and age restrictions as specified (§ 98-125). Penalty: misdemeanor, up to $500.", street:["The section sets specific restrictions on where motor-assisted scooters may be operated and by whom — check the age and location limits for the specific violation.", "'Motor-assisted scooter' is a defined term (§ 98-124) — confirm the device fits before citing."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 98-200 – 98-203", name:"Golf Carts on Public Streets", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Misdemeanor; fine per the article penalty (up to $500)", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 98-201. Golf carts permitted and restricted.\nA person may operate a golf cart on a public street only if specified conditions are met, including: the street has a posted speed limit of not more than 35 miles per hour; the golf cart is operated during the daytime (unless properly equipped and permitted otherwise); and the golf cart meets applicable equipment and registration requirements.\n\nSec. 98-202. Prohibition. It is unlawful to operate a golf cart on a public street except as permitted by § 98-201.\n\nSec. 98-203. Exceptions. [summarized] Provides limited exceptions consistent with state law.", summary:"Permits golf-cart operation on a public street only under specified conditions — including a posted speed limit of no more than 35 mph, daytime operation (unless properly equipped/permitted), and applicable equipment and registration requirements (§ 98-201) — and makes operation outside those conditions unlawful (§ 98-202), subject to limited exceptions (§ 98-203).", street:["Golf-cart-on-street operation is lawful only within the § 98-201 conditions: ≤35 mph posted street, generally daytime, and proper equipment/registration.", "Operation outside those conditions (wrong street, after dark without equipment) is the violation under § 98-202.", "Tracks the state Transportation Code golf-cart framework — the local conditions mirror the state permissions."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances § 98-210", name:"Hand-Held Wireless Communication Devices While Driving", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["parking"], level:"Misdemeanor; fine per the traffic-article penalty (up to $500)", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 98-210. Regulating the use of hand-held wireless communication devices while driving.\nIt is unlawful to use a hand-held wireless communication device, including holding a wireless device to send or read a text or electronic message or to engage in a call, while operating a motor vehicle within the town, except as specifically permitted (e.g., hands-free operation, use while stopped, or emergency use). Additional definitions, exceptions, and equipment provisions are set out in the section.", summary:"Makes it unlawful to use a hand-held wireless communication device — including holding it to text, read messages, or make a call — while operating a motor vehicle within the town, except in permitted circumstances such as hands-free use, use while stopped, or emergencies.", street:["The offense is hand-held use while driving — holding the device to text or call. Hands-free operation is the primary permitted alternative.", "Common exceptions: use while the vehicle is stopped and emergency use — confirm none applies.", "Little Elm's local ordinance may reach conduct beyond the statewide texting-while-driving ban; apply the local terms as written."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 10-1 – 10-3", name:"Alcohol in Public Parks", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["alcohol"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 10-27, fine up to $500", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 10-1. Sale or provision of alcohol in public park.\n(a) It shall be unlawful for any person to sell, offer to sell, or in any way provide for the serving of alcoholic beverages in any public park, except as authorized under this article, including where: (1) such alcoholic beverage is sold or dispensed by the holder of an appropriate state permit/license under a special event permit issued pursuant to this article; and other stated conditions.\n\nSec. 10-2. Youth sports. [summarized] Addresses alcohol in connection with youth sports activities.\n\nSec. 10-3. Special event permit procedures for public park alcohol sales. [summarized] Sets the special-event permit process for authorized park alcohol sales.", summary:"Makes it unlawful to sell, offer to sell, or provide for the serving of alcoholic beverages in any public park except as authorized — chiefly under a special-event permit held by an appropriately state-licensed permittee (§§ 10-1, 10-3). Section 10-2 addresses alcohol in connection with youth sports. Penalty per § 10-27.", street:["Selling or serving alcohol in a public park is unlawful absent an authorized special-event permit — check for a § 10-3 permit before treating a park event as a violation.", "The authorization runs to a state-licensed permittee under a special-event permit; casual sale/service without that is the offense."] },
  { ord:"Little Elm Code of Ordinances §§ 10-23, 10-26 – 10-27", name:"Alcohol Business Hours; Beer Sales in Residential Areas", city:"Little Elm, TX", cats:["alcohol"], level:"Misdemeanor per § 10-27, fine up to $500", lvlClass:"m", text:"Sec. 10-23. Business hours.\nNo person shall sell, offer for sale, or deliver any alcoholic beverage except within those hours as prescribed by state law. The holder of a mixed-beverage late-hours permit issued by the state (or any equivalent late-hours permit/license) may offer alcoholic beverages during the extended hours authorized by that permit, consistent with the Texas Alcoholic Beverage Code.\n\nSec. 10-26. Sale of beer prohibited in residential areas.\nIt shall be unlawful for any person or dealer to sell beer in residential areas within the town.\n\nSec. 10-27. Penalty.\nAny person who violates or fails to comply with this article, or the provisions of the state rules, or any permit holder/operator of an alcoholic beverage establishment that does not comply with the requirements, is guilty of a misdemeanor (fine up to $500).", summary:"Limits alcohol sales/delivery to the hours prescribed by state law, with extended hours available only under a state late-hours permit (§ 10-23), and prohibits the sale of beer in residential areas of the town (§ 10-26). Penalty: misdemeanor, up to $500 (§ 10-27).", street:["Sales outside state-law hours (absent a valid late-hours permit) is the § 10-23 violation — check for a state late-hours permit before treating after-hours service as unlawful.", "Selling beer in a residential area is independently prohibited under § 10-26.", "The penalty reaches both the seller and a permit-holding establishment that operates out of compliance."] }
];
